<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
By CHERYL WITTENAUER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DE SOTO, Kan. (AP) -- It's a cold and damp Friday at Steve's Meat
Market, with temperatures nowhere near the sultry climes of
Abdirashid Sharif's native Somalia. But in his new U.S. home, this
Somali war refugee has discovered the familiar in rural Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   At an open-air market out back, Sharif and fellow Muslims buy
sheep, goats and cows then slaughter the animals themselves in
accordance with Islamic law. Muslims can eat only meat that is
halal, or lawfully slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   One day a week, as it has for at least 15 years, the small-town
Kansas butcher shop and slaughterhouse draws many Muslims,
transplanted to the Midwest from throughout the world. It's one of
a relative handful of such places serving an estimated 10 million
Muslims in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughter or ''sacrifice'' is accomplished by a slash to a
restrained animal's throat following a prayer, and is permitted by
a religious exemption to U.S. Department of Agriculture rules.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, the USDA requires that the animal first be knocked
out with a stun gun. Muslims, who view the animal as a gift from
God, consider their method more humane.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're very religious people,'' said Dick Dabbs, a butcher at
Steve's Meat Market who sharpens the knife before each kill, and
then hoses the bloodied floor. ''The animal has got to be killed on
the first slash or they won't eat it. Once that vein is sliced,
that animal is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Such slaughters go on all year, but demand increases in the days
leading up to Eid al-Adha, the Celebration of the Sacrifice, which
this year fell on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Eid al-Adha marks the end of hajj, the pilgrimage Muslims make
to the Grand Mosque in the Saudi Arabian city of Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   During the feast, observed by an estimated 1 billion Muslims
worldwide, believers slaughter sheep, goats, cows or camels to
commemorate the prophet Ibrahim's readiness to offer his son's life
to Allah, or God. For his obedience, Ibrahim was given a sheep to
sacrifice instead.
</P>
<P>
   Steve's and Star Packing Co. in the old ''butcher town'' section
of St. Louis do a brisk business in goats, lambs and cows. Both got
started in halal slaughter when approached by Muslims, whose
numbers are growing in the region. Some 15,000 Muslims live in the
Kansas City metro area and up to 40,000 around St. Louis, according
to estimates of the Islamic Society.
</P>
<P>
   The largest U.S. centers of Muslims are Chicago, Detroit, Los
Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''We get Bosnians, Somalis, Pakistanis, Iraqis, Serbs,
Croatians. We're the United Nations,'' said Anthea Richmond of Star
Packing. She said her husband's uncle began providing halal
slaughter for Muslims in St. Louis 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely how many slaughterhouses provide similar services
around the nation is not known. Of 1,170 federally inspected
establishments, fewer than 10 are halal, USDA spokeswoman Beth
Gaston said. But that does not include the plants USDA inspects for
cleanliness but not for slaughter; that applies to cases where meat
is slaughtered for personal use but not for resale in specialty
markets.
</P>
<P>
   At Steve's Meat Market, the meat is processed, cut and bagged at
lightning speed. Co-owner Mitch Prudden said his Muslim customers
prefer to take it home very fresh in small chunks for stew meat.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Morgan, an Oak Grove, Mo., livestock dealer who sells live
animals behind Steve's, points to a Muslim woman loading a garbage
bag of meat into her minivan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It moves from hoof to baggie in one hour,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Muslim tradition, the meat is divided among family, friends,
neighbors and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic humanitarian relief organizations, such as the Islamic
African Relief Agency USA in Columbia, Mo., encourage believers to
parcel some of their ''sacrifice'' to the needy by contributing
toward the purchase of animals for use in Kashmir, Chechnya, Turkey
and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   When his turn came at Steve's, Abdirashid Sharif made quick work
of it, saying a prayer and then lowering the knife. For some who
followed him, the job was a grim necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't like doing this,'' said Hassan Osman, another Somali,
whose grimace revealed his discomfort. ''But if you are Muslim, and
you buy a goat, you have to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   At Star Packing in St. Louis, Muslims with weak stomachs have a
way out. Every Thursday, Mohammed Waheed-uz-zaman Rana, a Saint
Louis University anatomy and neurobiology professor, conducts the
ritual slaughter for fellow Muslims in that city. Rana, from
Pakistan, figures he has killed thousands of animals over the last
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, begins with prayer: ''Oh God Almighty, this (animal) is
yours and I'm taking something from it. I ask permission of the
Creator to take this animal for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
