<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, March 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
US To Offer Ease on Luxury Imports
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a move to encourage reformists in Iran, the Clinton
administration is ready to announce a lifting of a ban on imports of luxury
goods and to offer a settlement of claims with Tehran, a senior U.S. official
said Thursday. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will make the offer in a
major policy speech here Friday to the American-Iranian Council, a private group
based in Princeton, N.J., that seeks better relations with Tehran. The partial
easing of sanctions and the offer to discuss claims each nation has against the
other will be coupled with a renewed proposal for formal talks, said the
official, who declined to be identified.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vt. House OKs Gay 'Civil Unions'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- The Vermont House approved Thursday a bill to allow
gays to form ''civil unions.'' If the bill becomes law, the state will have gone
further than any other in recognizing same-sex couples. Vermont's Senate is
expected to approve the bill by the end of next month. However, the federal
government still would not recognize such unions with regard to such things as
immigration rights, Social Security and federal taxes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Record 499.19-Point Gain for the Dow
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials rocketed 499.19 points Thursday in a
record-shattering rally as investors poured money into blue chips that had been
battered by Wall Street's frenzy for technology stocks. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed at 10,630.60. The 4.9 percent rise was not the best-ever daily
percentage gain. The technology-laden Nasdaq ended up 134.77 at 4,717.39, having
clawed back from an earlier loss of 127 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Burdened By Ireland Impasse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed to leaders in the Northern
Ireland peace process Thursday to put aside their differences and work to
restore the British province's independent government. Clinton addressed the
annual dinner of the American Ireland Fund, attended by David Trimble, leader of
the pro-British Ulster Unionists party, and Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams, whose
party is allied with the Irish Republican Army. Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Peter Mandelson suspended the province's nascent coalition government
last month because the IRA refused to give up its weapons. On Thursday,
Mandelson urged both sides to use their visit to Washington to restart the
process.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain: Bush Team Disrespectful
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- John McCain's supporters are accusing George W. Bush of
showing little respect for the senator and his political reform agenda, saying
''macho talk'' has killed hopes for an early endorsement that could be vital to
Bush's prospects in November's general election. In an interview with The New
York Times, Bush said he had no intentions of making concessions to McCain on
campaign finance reform. But the Texan and his advisers scrambled Thursday to
explain the remarks, fearing the fallout could further alienate McCain and his
independent-minded supporters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ray Reports on FBI Files
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Independent Counsel Robert Ray said Thursday he found no
credible evidence that first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton or senior White House
officials were involved in seeking the FBI background files on Republicans. Ray
said his office was ending the investigation with no prosecutions. The White
House has said the gathering of files was a bureaucratic blunder based on
outdated Secret Service lists of White House entry passholders.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Appeals Court Rejects Exxon Appeal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- An appeal by the Exxon Corp. on the $5 billion
Valdez oil spill civil verdict was rejected Thursday. The San Francisco-based
9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled the verdict should not be thrown out because
of irregularities during jury deliberations. The appeal of the punitive damages
verdict was one of several filed by Exxon and co-defendant Joseph Hazelwood, who
was in charge of the tanker Exxon Valdez when it drove onto a charted reef in
Prince William Sound in March 1989 and spilled 11 million gallons of Alaska
crude oil.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rose Friday morning, boosted by a record
surge on Wall Street. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 160.47
points to 19,413.70 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gonzaga Beats Louisville 77-66
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Gonzaga, the little Jesuit school that became the
darling of last season's NCAA tournament with its improbable run to the West
regional final, knocked off Louisville 77-66 in the first round Thursday night
behind Richie Frahm's 31 points. The Bulldogs (25-8) play the winner of Thursday
night's Northern Arizona-St. John's game in Saturday's second round. In other
games, it was Syracuse 79, Samford 65; Kentucky 85, St. Bonaventure 80; Oklahoma
74, Winthrop 50; Texas 77, Indiana St. 61; Auburn 72, Creighton 69; and Arizona
71, Jackson St. 47.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
