<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYPIRG: Upstate could lose in reapportionment  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- At least one upstate Senate seat and two
Assembly seats could be lost to the New York City region and one
congressional seat overall because of its declining population in
the region, a citizen's advocacy group says .
</P>
<P>
   Upstate lost 40,000 people between 1990-99, according to an
analysis done by the New York Public Interest Research Group using
U.S. Census data from July.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New York City, Long Island, Putnam, Rockland and
Westchester counties -- the downstate area -- picked up more than
240,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   That means when the state Legislature begins reapportionment
next year, the legislative lines will probably be redrawn to give
downstate areas -- New York City and the suburban counties --
additional seats at the expense of the upstate area, NYPIRG
spokesman Blair Horner said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The counties that lost the most people are Erie, Brooklyn,
Oneida, Broome and Onondaga. The ones with the greatest population
increases were Manhattan, Suffolk, Queens, Staten Island and
Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like the trends would be downstate because
reapportionment follows the Census figures,'' Horner said.
</P>
<P>
   Horner estimates that at least one upstate seat in the
Republican-controlled Senate will be shifted downstate, while at
least two seats in the Democrat-controlled Assembly will move
downstate.
</P>
<P>
   There is one caveat. After the 1980 population count, the state
Senate added a 61st seat. They could add more, thus diluting the
effects of any population shifts. The Assembly is limited to 150
seats.
</P>
<P>
   The only downstate areas to lose people were Brooklyn and the
Bronx, which together lost more than 42,000 people during the last
decade, Horner said. However, those districts probably won't lose
seats, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, lines there probably will be redrawn just to include
more people from higher-populated boroughs like Manhattan or
Queens, he said. ''Some or one of their legislators will be
representing a new borough or more of a new borough,'' Horner said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Horner wouldn't guess exactly which districts
legislators would change or what the new legislative map would look
like. ''The hidden artistic capabilities come out when they draw
these maps,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers will run on the new district maps for the first time
in November 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate also faces problems on the national government level.
The law limits the U.S. House to 435 seats and as the population
shifts, the Constitution calls for a redistribution of members
after each Census. If New York's population increase doesn't match
other states, it would lose one or maybe more seats.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate population losses mean that if New York loses any of its
congressional seats, that position will come at the expense of
upstate, Horner said. The first likely loss would be in the
Southern Tier or western New York, because those are places losing
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''After that, it becomes unclear,'' Horner said.
</P>
<P>
   Horner said he wants the state Legislature to make available on
the Internet the population figures and computer programs it will
use to figure out the Legislature's new district lines so regular
people can see what they are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want a more rational reapportionment,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0019 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
