<DOCNO> APW20000317.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assembly bills aim to revive freed inmate's $12.5 million lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Two lawmakers are attempting to make it
easier for wrongfully imprisoned inmates to recover monetary
compensation from New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Bills by state Assembly Democrats Susan John and David Gantt of
Rochester could revive a $12.5 million lawsuit brought by a former
prostitute who languished in prison for nearly a quarter-century
before her 1973 murder conviction was overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Tyson's lawsuit before the Court of Claims was thrown out
last August because a long-buried jailhouse interview with a
material witness who initially claimed he didn't see her with the
victim was not viewed as new evidence, a requirement under state
law.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unless the state chooses to prosecute her again, Ms. Tyson
cannot establish that she's not guilty,'' John said Thursday. ''I
think she is doing her best to get on with her life ... but this
would also give her an opportunity to get a measure of
vindication.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes in the law would give a handful of people
freed from prison because there was reasonable doubt about their
guilt ''the legal right to go to court and seek compensation'' by
proving their innocence, John said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the law was amended, Tyson, now 52, would still have to
prove she did not kill Philadelphia businessman Timothy Haworth the
night of May 24, 1973, and ''that is all she has ever wanted to
do,'' said her attorney, Bradley Kammholz.
</P>
<P>
   Haworth spent the day working as a consultant at Eastman Kodak
Co., then left his hotel around midnight to apparently solicit a
prostitute. He was battered with a brick and strangled with his own
necktie in an alley.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of physical evidence, Tyson and a fellow
prostitute, John Duval, were convicted on the basis of confessions
they insist were beaten out of them by police, and on testimony of
two teen-age runaways.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Wayne Wright, revealed in 1997 that he had lied
about seeing Tyson and Duval with the victim. Prosecutors then came
upon a synopsis of a police interview with the other teen, Jon
Jackson, in which he also denied seeing them with the victim --
contrary to what the teens had testified in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was freed in May 1998, Tyson had become New
York's longest-serving female inmate.
</P>
<P>
   While prosecutors decided not to retry her -- the city of
Rochester gave her $1.2 million in compensation -- they went after
Duval again. While Tyson had steadfastly maintained her innocence,
he had twice admitted his guilt before a parole board.
</P>
<P>
   At a retrial in which the defense maintained he lied to the
parole board to win his freedom, the 47-year-old Duval was
acquitted of murder on Feb. 3. He is also seeking damages for
unlawful imprisonment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0020 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000317.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Love Canal's Lois Gibbs comes to aid of contaminated Buffaloneighborhood  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Environmental activist Lois Gibbs is coming
to the aid of a Buffalo neighborhood built on toxic waste, calling
it ''another Love Canal.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is like deja vu,'' Gibbs said Thursday after touring
Hickory Woods, where dozens of homes were built on or near
thousands of tons of cancer-causing coke wastes left over from
steel-making operations.
</P>
<P>
   Residents want to be relocated.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs, who heads the Center for Environmental Health and Justice
in Washington, D.C., was a leader in the fight to clean up her
contaminated Niagara Falls neighborhood more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is another Love Canal,'' said Gibbs, who drew parallels
to her experience. ''We didn't know our homes were built on a dump.
We didn't know that when we dug in our yards we were endangering
our children ... The government allowed these homes to be built
knowing full well it was contaminated.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These people should be moved out today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hickory Woods site was left vacant and blighted after the
departure of LTV Steel and other manufacturers in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Buffalo purchased and began redeveloping it later
that decade, using federal and state funds to build approximately
60 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The contamination was discovered later.
</P>
<P>
   City officials recently announced that LTV Steel and its former
sister company, Donner Hanna Coke Co., will pay $500,000 to clean
up waste. Mayor Anthony Masiello said he would continue to press
the steel companies to take responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said, the Environmental Protection Agency
will conduct a soil analysis of the area.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should permit these experts to conduct their study and then
take appropriate action,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   But the residents do not want to wait. The city, they say,
should repurchase their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remediation is not what we want. We want out first, then they
can remediate later,'' said Linda Benns, a six-year resident.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowner Rick Ammerman cited numerous cases of cancer among
residents and accused the city of having ''a total disregard for
human health.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We hold those who planned this neighborhood improperly
responsible for that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Blake believes her 4-year-old son's vision and
developmental problems are due to exposure to lead and other
toxins.
</P>
<P>
   ''My son spends eight hours a day in school, in therapy,'' she
said. ''It's not fair to him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
