<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Physicians seeking union-like bargaining powers  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Workers of the world unite!
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, pediatricians, gynecologists and other physicians are
seeking to unite in union-like bargaining units which they say
would give them badly needed leverage in their dealings with health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   With one of the more formidable lobbying groups in Albany -- the
Medical Society of the State of New York -- behind the proposal,
influential legislators are listening.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Kemp Hannon, a Long Island Republican who chairs the
Senate's health committee, said he has been talking to Democratic
legislators in the state Assembly about drafting a bill to let
doctors organize.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tricky proposition technically, because the measure must
be structured in a way to legally circumvent federal antitrust
statutes.
</P>
<P>
   It may be even tricker politically trying to convince people
that doctors -- hardly regarded as an underpaid class of workers --
need help to make more money. Or at least that will be the reaction
of most to the notion of unionized doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Society is not using the word ''union'' in promoting
the legislation. It prefers the nebulous term ''collective
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not really a true union as you might think of the
union in a traditional sense,'' said Dr. Mark Fox, who is promoting
the issue on behalf of the Medical Society. ''This is a way for
physicians to come together and talk to one another about patient
care issues concerning the specific insurance plan and going to the
insurance plan and being able to sit at the table on an equal
footing with the plan and to discuss these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The fees doctors get for their services would be secondary
during those negotiations to issues involving the right of doctors
to treat patients free from what they regard as interference from
health maintenance organizations, the Medical Society insists.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said the result of tight controls by HMOs over the way
doctors treat managed-care patients has been the ''complete
disruption of the doctor-patient relationship and the sacred trust
that has existed between them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, HMOs see no reason to allow doctors to
unionize in New York, said Leslie Moran of the state Health Plan
Association. Patients' rights are protected by a series of new
measures, including an outside appeals process when HMOs deny
coverage to patients for procedures they consider medically
necessary, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Moran added that HMOs now essentially collectively bargain with
independent practice associations, which are coalitions of doctors
who offer various services from the same location.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that about 30,000 physicians might be
eligible to form union-like bargaining units under the legislation
being discussed in New York. Their participation will depend on how
dominant HMOs are in their regions. Sponsors say that the more
customers a managed care company has, the less bargaining power
doctors have in dealing with those HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Some statewide authority -- the attorney general, perhaps, or the
state insurance or health departments -- would have to assume
oversight over the activities of the bargaining units, Hannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors would not be allowed to strike or stage boycotts under a
unionized setup.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in Texas are the only ones who now have the right to
collectively bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the doctors' interest in hiking their own fees vs.
getting patients a better deal before HMOs is at the crux of the
debate over letting doctors collectively bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Hannon said he believes doctors' dissatisfaction with HMOs is
genuine, fueled by things like ''the need to spend countless hours
on the phone, justifying a series of tests which in their minds are
totally necessary for good health care.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to explore what's the proper balance out there
between making this affordable and making this accessible,'' Hannon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Horner of the New York Public Interest Research Group, a
critic of doctors on many issues, said there is plenty of
self-interest involved in the doctors' unionization push.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is as much an issue of patient protection as it is fees,''
Horner said. ''But I am sure what drives this issue in terms of the
trade association is economic impact (to its members).''
</P>
<P>
   Moran, of the HMO trade organization, agreed that ''it is not a
convincing argument'' by doctors to say patients' rights and not
doctors' fees are behind their promotion of the unionization bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''When someone says, 'It's not about the money,''' she said,
''the chances are it is about the money.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0020 </TRAILER>
