<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deputies Shot in Atlanta  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Two sheriff's deputies were shot Thursday night
while trying to serve a warrant against the former black militant
once known as H. Rap Brown, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they did not know whether Jamil Al-Amin, as Brown is
now known, fired the shots that wounded the Fulton County officers.
A manhunt was under way near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies were trying to serve a warrant from suburban Cobb
County for aggravated assault against Al-Amin when they were shot
about 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think both officers kind of walked into this,'' Sheriff
Jacquelyn Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said one officer was in critical condition at Grady
Memorial Hospital with abdominal and leg wounds. The other was in
guarded condition with leg and arm wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was a leader of the Student Non-Violent Coordinating
Committee and justice minister of the Black Panthers, which rose to
prominence in the 1960s. He once exhorted blacks to arm themselves,
saying ''violence is as American as cherry pie.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he has lived as the Muslim spiritual leader of
a community mosque and operated a small grocery in Atlanta's West
End. He has worked at trying to clean up drugs and prostitution in
the neighborhood since moving there in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
