<HEADLINE> SuperSonics 117, Grizzlies 103  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Gary Payton scored 30 points and dished out 16
assists, one short of a career high, as the Seattle SuperSonics
handed the Vancouver Grizzlies their 10th straight loss, 117-103
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's points total pushed him past 13,000 in his nine-year
career with 13,018. Payton scored 40 in Seattle's 113-103 victory
at Vancouver on Monday, one off his career high.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics forward Vin Baker, who missed the last two games with a
strained left hamstring, scored 21 points and pulled down seven
rebounds. Brent Barry also hit for 21, including four 3-pointers,
for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Payton hit 7 of 10 shots in the first quarter and had six
assists and four rebounds as Seattle led 40-26. Vancouver never got
closer than five points the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dickerson led the Grizzlies with 24 points, Mike Bibby
scored 23 and Shareef Abdur-Rahim 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics swept the Grizzlies 4-0 on the season and are 9-0
overall at home against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzlies trailed by as many as 16 points in the first
quarter, but scored the first eight points of the second, capped by
Bryant Reeves' dunk to get to 40-34. The Sonics rallied to go up by
10, but Dickerson's three-point play brought the Grizzlies to 64-57
at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson's jumper to start the second half got Vancouver within
five points. The Grizzlies got no closer the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Payton hit 7 of 10 shots in the first quarter and had six
assists and four rebounds as Seattle led 40-26.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who showed no signs of his injury, played 30 minutes. He
had eight in the opening quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle had a 17-6 run midway through the first period as it
turned a 11-10 advantage into a 28-16 lead. Baker had six points in
the run and Payton the final four points.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The 40 points given up by Vancouver in the first
quarter was a club record. ... Payton started his 299th consecutive
game Thursday, the longest active streak in the NBA. ... The loss
gave the Grizzlies a 5-68 all-time record in March. ... The
Grizzlies' game at home Friday against the Phoenix Suns starts a
nine-game homestand, the longest in team history ... Vernon Maxwell
needs just one more game to reach the 800 career mark in games
played.
</P>
</TEXT>
