<HEADLINE> Source: BMW To Sell Rover to Ford  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE, AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. has agreed to buy British
truck maker Land Rover from BMW Group as part of BMW's exit from
its six-year struggle to turn around the ailing Rover car group.
</P>
<P>
   BMW and Ford were set to announce today details of an agreement
concerning the Dearborn-based auto giant's acquisition of the
luxury sport utility unit, according to a source close to the
negotiations who would speak only on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after BMW announced its plans Thursday to sell
the Rover passenger car division to Alchemy Partners Ltd., a
British investment group.
</P>
<P>
   The investment group will take on the Rover and MG brand cars,
including their plant in Longbridge, England, and recast the
venture under the new name MG Car Co.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, those operations have burdened BMW
with $1.25 billion in red ink and dragged down profit an estimated
28 percent last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover, on the other hand is considered the crown jewel of
the Rover lineup. The company sells four models of SUVs, two of
which -- the Range Rover and the Discovery -- are imported to the
United States. The company built about 160,000 vehicles last year.
</P>
<P>
   The source could not provide other details, and both Ford and
BMW declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's deal with BMW for Land Rover is yet another step in a
trend of global consolidation among automakers. Earlier this week,
General Motors Corp. took 20 percent of the Fiat Auto company from
its Italian parent, a few months after taking a similar stake in
the Japanese parent of Subaru.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers believe such deals will cut the massive costs of
designing and building new vehicles by allowing companies to share
components and factories around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, details on the BMW-Alchemy pact remained a matter of
contention late Thursday. BMW said the two sides were still
negotiating the fine print of the arrangement after the company's
supervisory board approved its outline.
</P>
<P>
   BMW did say, however, that shifting the operations to Alchemy
will set the company back $3 billion, in the form of a one-time
restructuring charge.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it was unclear whether the price of the deal was
rolled into that charge. Some even speculated BMW wooed Alchemy
into taking the loss-making venture by throwing in a cash
incentive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even getting Rover for free would not be attractive to most
people. It's a cash-eating company,'' said Christian Breitsprecher,
an auto analyst with Deutsche Bank. ''I'm pretty sure Alchemy's not
paying anything for the deal and is getting something on top.''
</P>
<P>
   BMW did unveil plans Thursday to roll out a new line of the
sporty, subcompact Minis from its Oxford plant in early summer 2001
and continue building the Rover 75 luxury model in Oxford on a
contract basis for Alchemy. The company also plans to finish
construction of its new Hams Hall engine factory in Birmingham and
begin production there.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to shed Rover caused strife at BMW, leading to the
resignation of three members of the management board. The board has
already filled two of those spots, with the third being shared by
chairman Joachim Milberg and chief financial officer Helmut Panke.
</P>
<P>
   The Rover line -- headquartered in Warwick, central England -- was
bought by BMW in 1994 mainly to gain access to Land Rover and flesh
out BMW's models at the less-expensive end of the car market. BMW
has already pumped $3.4 billion into Rover since buying the group
for $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The strengthening of the British pound since 1997 has made it
more expensive for the German company to build Rover vehicles in
Britain and export them to other countries in Europe where it earns
revenues in weaker currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about BMW closing down plants or pulling out operations,
the British government has earmarked a $240 million subsidy for the
company, which the European Union Commission is currently
scrutinizing under EU competition rules.
</P>
<P>
   Without the subsidy, union leaders say 16,000 of Rover's 30,000
jobs could be at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 0111 </TRAILER>
