<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign finance reform bills pass key committee  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Republicans in the state Legislature are
railing against two campaign finance reform bills that would allow
candidates to pay for their campaigns with taxpayer money within
six years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The taxpayer financing is a mistake, and having a bill that
goes into effect in 2006 is phony,'' said House Minority Leader
Robert Ward, R-Northford.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would set up a voluntary, publicly funded
campaign finance system in 2006. Public money would be available
for candidates running for constitutional offices such as governor,
attorney general and treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would be paid for through a voluntary $5 check-off on
state income tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate bill, public financing would kick in for the
2002 gubernatorial election, and would start in 2006 for all
constitutional and legislative offices. Residents would be allowed
to donate $5 to the pool that would be used to fund those
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Senate bill have said it will take 200 years to
raise enough money to publicly fund every campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who pushed the House and Senate bills through the
Appropriations Committee Thursday admit the proposals aren't
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are probably deficiencies in both bills, and they're not
going to be rectified here,'' said Appropriations Committee
co-chairman William Dyson, D-New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill passed on a 25-17 vote. The Senate bill was
approved 25-18. Both now head to the Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Republicans blasted Democrats for killing another
campaign finance reform bill which would have limited contributions
from political action committees, lobbyists and other special
interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   That proposal, which died in another committee earlier this
week, would have applied to all state offices. It made no
provisions for public financing of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's have a meaningful discussion about real reform, which is
limiting proliferation of political action committees and special
interest money,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Brian Flaherty criticized the House bill for proposing
reforms only for constitutional offices, not legislative races.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we should be reforming the system for everybody
but the Legislature,'' said Flaherty, R-Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Andrew Fleischmann said the bill only targets
constitutional offices because candidates for those races scramble
to raise the largest amounts of cash.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at the pattern of spending, it's clear that that
is where the most significant issue lies,'' said Fleischmann,
D-West Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans bolstered their argument against public campaign
financing by pointing to a Hartford Courant/Connecticut poll that
said 77 percent of those asked are opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll of 509 randomly selected adults showed that
68 percent of those polled say some reform is needed. The poll has
a margin of error of plus or minus five percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ''The perception is that honesty is missing from the election
process, but I've never seen it suggested that a new source of
money was missing from the election process,'' Flaherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills would impose spending caps for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House proposal, gubernatorial candidates could spend
up to $3.95 million for an election, and people running for
constitutional offices could spend as much as $523,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill allows gubernatorial candidates to raise $5
million. Candidates for other statewide offices could collect
$750,000. State senate races would be capped at $105,000 and
candidates in House races could raise $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''People want the amount of money spent in campaigns to be
controlled or capped,'' said Roy Occhiogrosso, a spokesman for
Senate Democrats. ''People think there is too much money involved
in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say spending caps aren't worth considering in light
of a U.S. Supreme Court decision that they are unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. John G. Rowland has said he is open to campaign
finance reform, but insists that it include legislative races.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0121 </TRAILER>
