<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sun shining on solar power, clean energy as oil prices rise  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Fed up with high gas prices? Costly
heating oil leaving you cold? A group of alternative energy
advocates have some ideas for you.
</P>
<P>
   A four-day conference this week sponsored by the Northeast
Sustainable Energy Association brought together advocates for solar
power, electric cars and other alternative energy systems.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was not just for environmental types. One of
Thursday's keynote speakers was Michael Morris, chairman and chief
executive of Northeast Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these advocates have been waiting since the oil crisis
of the 1970s for the mainstream public to choose earth-friendly and
energy-efficient systems to build homes, cars and public spaces.
</P>
<P>
   The computer revolution, electric deregulation, environmental
concerns and costly fossil fuel could converge to create a great
opportunity, said Warren Leon, executive director of the energy
association.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a number of signs suggesting we could be on the
brink of a new era and a dramatic transformation to clean energy,''
Leon said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said a key factor in clean energy is electric
deregulation -- a series of laws in states around the country that
ended electric utility monopolies and allow consumers to choose
their power suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Many laws, including Connecticut's, require utilities to use
more nonpolluting power sources, such as solar, wind power or
hydroelectric plants.
</P>
<P>
   The system will allow electric companies to market power from
these sources, to attract environmentally driven customers.
</P>
<P>
   The laws also encourage research into generating power by the
sun, wind or fuel cells -- miniature power plants that generate
electricity chemically.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said it is possible in 10 or 20 years that each home and
business will have a fuel cell system.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds crazy, Morris said, imagine believing 20 years
ago that people today would be walking around with cellular
telephones in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will create new roles for traditional utilities,
away from generating power toward maintaining and designing such
systems for homes and businesses, Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   NU, the largest electric utility in New England, plans to merge
with Consolidated Edison Inc. of New York, making one of the
largest electric utilities in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Solar power providers hope to reap some of the benefit from
states' deregulation laws that put money into research.
</P>
<P>
   This winter's home heating oil price spike is encouraging people
to think about alternate ways to heat their homes, said Dan
Greenberg of Applied Power Corp., a Waltham, Mass. company that
installs and designs solar systems.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this continues, there's a good chance it will lead to an
uptick in business,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   For people bemoaning high gas prices, a new option is available:
electric-gasoline hybrid cars.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Robert Maddox, R-Bethlehem, three weeks ago got the
Honda Insight, a hybrid that goes 75 miles on a gallon of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The car, loaded with air-conditioning and other extras, cost
$20,495, said Maddox, who put the car on display at the conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0121 </TRAILER>
