<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine President Presents Shift  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GRAY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- When Argentina's former President
Carlos Menem needed to travel abroad, he flew aboard Tango 01, a
Boeing 757 that cost $66 million and came complete with a bedroom,
sauna and working space for a hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   Recently elected President Fernando De la Rua has decided to
travel lighter. Returning from his first overseas trip, he
disembarked from a commercial jetliner like any other passenger,
got in line at the airport in Buenos Aires and paid his customs
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The news made headlines, and the message was not lost: De la
Rua, the 62-year-old who took office Dec. 10, has shown in his
first 100 days that he wants to bring greater openness and
austerity to the presidency after Menem's 10 years of flamboyant
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Playing up his squeaky clean image, De la Rua won election for
the center-left opposition Alliance in October, harnessing voter
weariness with Menem's two terms and several corruption scandals,
none touching Menem personally.
</P>
<P>
   Charging through his first three months in office, De la Rua has
surprised many with a vigorous, take-charge attitude. The former
Buenos Aires mayor has moved quickly to revive Argentina's stalled
economy and enact promises of a more austere government.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has proven to be a stronger executive than I think anyone
thought,'' said Riordan Roett, an analyst at Johns Hopkins
University. ''He's taken on some tough issues and it seems he's
making all the right moves.''
</P>
<P>
   The country is struggling to shake off a yearlong recession that
left the unemployment rate as high as 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to prune a large federal deficit, De la Rua pushed
through a highly unpopular tax hike. The additional funds should
help Argentina trim its federal deficit by $2.5 billion -- from $7.1
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an intelligent start,'' said political analyst Felipe
Noguera. ''I'm not sure the man on the street is happy, but he's
doing these things because they are expected to bring benefits in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua's crowning achievement to date has been House passage
of his proposal to overhaul the country's antiquated labor laws,
against the protests of the country's once-powerful labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   He also argued in favor of allowing companies to determine their
pay scales -- a power that until now rested in the hands of national
union leaders and kept foreign investors at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The early victories have comforted the International Monetary
Fund, which recently approved a key $7.4 billion standby loan for
Argentina, one of the world's most indebted nations.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say De la Rua is making other important advances.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked to recast Argentina's government as more
transparent, at the same time that authorities are investigating
accusations of corruption against some former Menem officials.
</P>
<P>
   But drawing the contrast with Menem is not always easy.
</P>
<P>
   In January, De la Rua refused to use Tango 01 for his trip to
Sweden, instead flying first class aboard a commercial airliner.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua pledged to sell the luxury plane once in office, but
has been forced to back down. With the aircraft now only attracting
half its original price tag -- the highest bid has come in at $30
million -- it would prove a huge loss for a government preaching
fiscal restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Many say they welcome the change in style.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't totally agree with De la Rua's policies,'' said
Gabriel Gomes, a 36-year-old furniture store owner. ''But he has
brought some public confidence back into the presidency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 0123 </TRAILER>
