<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor appoints Wall Street honcho to review Nassau's finances  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki's appointment of Wall
Street's Frank Zarb to review the beleaguered financial situation
in Nassau County appears to be winning praise from both Democrats
and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb, the chairman of the National Association of Securities
Dealers -- which runs the NASDAQ stock market -- is being brought in
to determine the extent of the county's problems, as well as to
offer solutions to closing a budget gap predicted to hit $200
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to have an independent review,'' Pataki said at
a press conference Thursday in Manhattan. ''This is simply a
gathering of information and options at this stage. I am confident
Mr. Zarb will have full access to everything he needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican County Executive Thomas Gulotta said he thought
Zarb's presence could ''be a very positive and constructive
force.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference where he described his own proposal for
dealing with the budget gap, Gulotta suggested Zarb ''can help to
create the bipartisan support and the strength of political will
that is going to be necessary to resolve this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver and Assemblyman Thomas DiNapoli,
chairman of the Nassau Democrats, both endorsed Pataki's choice of
Zarb, but said a fiscal oversight board would eventually be
required to cure the county's budget headaches.
</P>
<P>
   ''Considering that Nassau County's financial situation is at
crisis levels, the need for an outside evaluation is appropriate
and responsible,'' Silver said in a statement. DiNapoli called
Zarb's appointment ''an important step toward coming together and
determining that there is a need for a fiscal oversight board.''
</P>
<P>
   The county's bond rating is currently one notch above junk
status; it's precarious financial position helped fuel a voter
revolt last November that saw the county's legislative body taken
over by Democrats for the first time since 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb is a former chairman of the Long Island Power Authority,
where he helped with the state takeover of the Long Island Lighting
Co. He also sits on the board of directors at Hofstra University in
Hempstead.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a complex nuclear formula,'' said Zarb, who noted
he is a business partner of Felix Rohatyn, who helped solve New
York City's financial crisis in the 1970s. ''It's a pretty straight
ahead business problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarb, who lives on Long Island, said he intends to spend the
next a week or so ''crunching numbers.'' Pataki said there was no
time limit attached to Zarb's assignment, though he expects a
solution ''in weeks, not months.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulotta's budget plan includes union give-backs, increases in
parks and other fees, deferred payments to the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority for maintenance of Long Island Rail Road
stations and other cuts.
</P>
<P>
   He warned of tax increases if no action is taken on his proposal
within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is a lack of political will, a lack of bipartisan
support, a lack of effort on the state or local level in order to
bring this about then very clearly there is going to be no
alternative but to increase local taxes,'' Gulotta said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, county Comptroller Fred Parolla announced his
own plan for solving the financial problem, the centerpiece of
which was a proposal to refinance $800 million in debt service
costs over a 14-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ''There appeared to be some good elements ... that could be
useful in terms of an overall five-year comprehensive plan,''
Gulotta said.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned, ''you've got to be a little bit careful when
you're restructuring debt because what you're really talking about
is taking the same debt, spreading it out over a long period of
time and ultimately increasing the expense of payback.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0124 </TRAILER>
