<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Views McCain as Political Ally  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CHARLES, Ill. (AP) -- George W. Bush insists he and John
McCain could make a dynamic duo in Washington, with the senator and
would-be president working together on issues such as overhauling
campaign financing and shoring up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor and presumptive Republican presidential
nominee put the positive spin on their relationship Thursday after
seeming dismissive of his former rival in a published interview.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that the Arizona senator helped produce record turnouts
in early primaries, Bush told The New York Times, ''Well, then, how
come he didn't win?'' Asked whether McCain had raised his
consciousness about reform, Bush replied, ''No, he didn't change my
views.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides said Thursday that the ''macho talk'' had killed
hopes for an early endorsement of Bush that could be vital to his
prospects of winning in November.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Allbaugh, Bush's campaign manager, called John Weaver,
McCain's top political adviser, to say he regretted that the
newspaper story didn't include more of the nice things Bush had
said about McCain. Allbaugh also reached out to reassure McCain's
allies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''People want to focus on areas where we disagree,'' Bush told
reporters in Springfield during a campaign swing through Illinois
that included a fund-raiser to help replenish his depleted campaign
kitty. ''I'm going to focus on areas where we agree, and there's a
lot of areas of agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   He named Social Security and campaign finance reform as
examples.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was equally deferential at later appearances in Wheaton and
St. Charles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to thank the senator for his campaign. I want to thank
the senator for his strong ideas on reform,'' he told a dinner of
over 1,300 DuPage County Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   At a fund-raiser in Wheaton, he said: ''I think it's very
important for us to recognize the contributions John made.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's effort at fence mending came as he fended off fresh
criticism from Democratic rival Al Gore and waded into a nasty
dispute between the National Rifle Association and President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He said the NRA had ''gone too far'' by accusing Clinton of
having ''blood on his hands'' for failing to enforce gun laws
before a deadly shooting last year in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush aligned himself with conservative groups during the
primary campaign, he is trying to shift back toward the political
center for the general election. Gun control is popular among
independent-minded voters, particularly the suburban women that
Bush and Gore are both courting.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says the Texas governor does the bidding of the gun lobby;
Bush strongly denies it.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is a gun rights supporter, Bush said: ''There's ways
to debate the issue without casting aspersions on the president
like that. I just think they've gone too far.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview published in today's editions of USA Today, Gore
called upon Bush to join him in backing pending federal legislation
to require mandatory child-safety trigger locks for new firearms,
end a loophole that exempts purchasers of guns at gun shows from
background checks and ban cheap handguns known as Saturday Night
Specials.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, campaigning close to home in Chevy Chase, Md., Gore
criticized Bush's five-year, $483 billion tax-cut proposal as
''economic snake oil.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president cast the fall election as a choice between
policies that underwrote the ''Clinton-Gore recovery'' and ones
that gave America the ''Bush-Quayle catastrophe,'' meaning the
recession that hit when Bush's father was president.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is so committed to this economic snake oil that ... he even
dismissed John McCain's campaign and said that he had learned
nothing from it and had no intention of taking any advice from the
McCain group,'' Gore said, accepting an endorsement from ACORN, an
organization of neighborhood groups.
</P>
<P>
   In a subsequent speech to the Amalgamated Transit Union in
Washington, Gore asked: ''How can somebody come before the American
people with a straight face and say let's get rid of what's working
and go back to what failed?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush took the criticism curtly.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wants to leave the money in Washington,'' the governor
said, referring to the lack of broad tax relief in Gore's agenda.
''He'll say anything to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Illinois swing marked his return to the fund-raising
circuit for the first time since mid-December. His
$1,000-per-person event in Wheaton was expected to raise $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's record-shattering $73 million campaign fund has
been largely depleted by the contest with McCain. His team plans to
raise up to $10 million in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   Both contenders were taking a long weekend off the campaign
trail, with Gore staying at home in Washington and Bush spending
the time at his ranch outside Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Bush campaign: http://www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign: http://www.algore2000.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
