<HEADLINE> Taiwan Vote a Test of Fear  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Worrying about threats of a Chinese
missile attack or invasion has become a presidential election
tradition in Taiwan's young democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's vote could be a test of how scared Taiwanese are of
China's massive military just 80 miles across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   Despite China's threat to invade Taiwan if the island declares
independence, the candidate who has come out in favor of a
permanent split with Beijing has a good chance of winning the close
three-way race. Such a victory could mean Taiwanese believe the
latest warnings of war with China are a big bluff.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji indicated that if
opposition presidential hopeful Chen Shui-bian won the vote, he
could spark a conflict with China. Zhu also wouldn't rule out
threatening military displays before the vote, saying ''wait and
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders ''are telling Taiwanese voters you have to
decide whether you want to vote for peace or war,'' said Yang
Kai-huang, a political science professor at Soochow University in
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's language was harsh, but nothing like Beijing's response to
Taiwan's first direct presidential election in 1996, when China
lobbed nuclear-capable missiles near the island's two major ports.
The United States sent two aircraft carriers and other warships to
the region to cool tensions.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Beijing is worried that if Chen is elected, he would
declare independence for Taiwan. China and Taiwan split amid civil
war in 1949, and Beijing has repeatedly threatened to invade if the
island tries to break away permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese investors were spooked by that prospect early in the
week, sending shares down almost 6.6 percent on Monday. Prices slid
sharply again Thursday, prompting the government to intervene with
massive purchases, but today prices finished almost 1 percent
higher in calmer dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chen, a former Taipei mayor, has said he would only
move Taiwan toward independence if Beijing attacks, his Democratic
Progressive Party still opposes reunification with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, China stepped up its threats, saying it would use
force if Taiwan indefinitely rebuffed reunification talks.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling Nationalist Party has tried to capitalize on the
tension, blaming Chen for stirring up China and assuring voters
that its candidate, Vice President Lien Chan, could best deal with
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   TV ads for Lien have shown young men marching off to war,
chanting a popular slogan of Chen's party, ''Long live Taiwan
independence!'' Other commercials show a Chinese submarine cruising
in the Taiwan Strait armed with nuclear-tipped missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Bi-khim Hsiao, a Chen spokeswoman, said the attack ads were
trying to ''demonize and radicalize'' Chen's party and were
upsetting ''domestic harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the duty of the government to alleviate tensions and
fear, but what they are doing is promoting fear,'' Hsiao said.
''The KMT (Nationalist Party) is the source of tension today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hsiao said Chinese individuals, who she would not identify, have
been meeting with DPP officials in recent months, preparing for a
possible Chen victory. Some have seemed genuinely interested in
understanding the party's views, while others simply delivered
anti-independence lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Although Beijing hasn't endorsed a candidate, it's widely
believed that it prefers Lien, a moderate who has never favored
independence. Like the other presidential hopefuls, Lien has said
he would expand trade ties with China if it doesn't compromise
Taiwan's security.
</P>
<P>
   The third major candidate is independent James Soong, a former
Nationalist leader expelled from the party for campaigning against
Lien. Beijing probably prefers Soong to Chen -- who is widely known
by his nickname, Abian -- but China may see him as less predictable
following the former Taiwan provincial governor's recent falling
out with the Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   ''If James Soong or Chen Shui-bian gets elected, it means people
have less fear of Zhu Rongji's remarks,'' said Alice Kao, a former
lawmaker with the pro-China New Party.
</P>
<P>
   Many Taiwanese have returned from abroad to vote, and Wu
Chun-hsiung, a real estate agent from Los Angeles, went beyond his
civic duty and actively campaigned.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all busy business people, but we have to do something at
this critical juncture,'' said Wu, as he passed out Chen flags to
Taipei office workers during the morning rush hour. ''China is such
an imposing hooligan. If they can't accept Abian, we can't expect
any other candidates to ease tensions with Beijing either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 0200 </TRAILER>
