<HEADLINE> Bush Attacks Gore Over IRS Attempt  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan congressional report describing
attempts by Vice President Gore's office to obtain IRS taxpayer
data for a union is now a presidential campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush said Thursday
that two calls to the Internal Revenue Service by two Gore aides
raise ''serious ethical questions.'' Gore's presidential campaign
countered that ''the only legitimate tax issue'' is Bush's
''scandalous tax scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush called on the vice president to further explain the 1997
contacts, described by the bipartisan Joint Taxation Committee as
''in violation of written White House policies.''
</P>
<P>
   White House staff members are prohibited from ''any
communication of any type with the IRS'' without approval of the
counsel's office -- except for someone's own personal returns. The
IRS treats taxpayer information as confidential and indeed rebuffed
Gore's aides, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's office says the contacts by the aides, including his
chief counsel at the time, were a ''simple status check.'' But the
committee's report said the information sought by the aides appears
to have been protected by tax confidentiality laws.
</P>
<P>
   From the campaign trail, Bush called the report a ''troubling
revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I call on the vice president to explain: Why did he seek to
obtain secret information, and what did he want to know and why did
he want to know it?'' Bush said in Springfield, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the contacts, coupled with Gore's campaign
fund-raising problems in 1996, ''aren't mistakes. These are habits.
They raise serious ethical questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign press secretary Chris Lehane accused Bush of
making ''wildly exaggerated accusations.''
</P>
<P>
   An IRS memo said Gore sought the information, which involved the
classification of a group of workers, in preparation for a meeting
with a union official. The matter was turned over to IRS
investigators, but no action was taken, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee report's main focus was to answer allegations by
nonprofit conservative groups that they were audited because of
their anti-Clinton views.
</P>
<P>
   The committee found no evidence to support that contention, but
determined that Gore's office and the Treasury Department
apparently tried in separate instances to obtain confidential
information. The IRS is prohibited by law from releasing specific
taxpayer data in almost all instances -- unless a taxpayer requests
his or her own information.
</P>
<P>
   Lindy Paull, the committee's staff director, said an IRS memo on
the contacts indicated that after one member of the vice
president's staff was unsuccessful in getting the tax data, a
second official made another effort ''to get the same
information.''
</P>
<P>
   The staffers making the calls, according to the memo, were
Kumiki Gibson -- Gore's counsel at the time -- and Joe Eyer, another
aide. Both contacts were on Jan. 28, 1997. Neither official still
works for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the second call, the IRS memo writer, in a portion
read to The Associated Press, wrote, ''I received another call from
a Mr. Joe Eyer who I believe ... said was Ms. Gibson's boss. He too
said he was counsel to the vice president.'' Eyer, in fact, was
assistant to the deputy chief of staff, Gore's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The memo also said, ''During the course of this conversation, at
some point I was reminded that the vice president was meeting with
the union president the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice presidential spokeswoman Laura Quinn said Eyer was not
Gibson's supervisor, that the aides were making ''a simple status
check'' and that any duplication of calls were ''inadvertent.''
</P>
<P>
   Both former aides have ''no specific recollection of these
specific calls,'' Quinn said. ''The theory that she (Gibson) made
the first call and a person of higher rank followed up is 100
percent incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's staff also said a check of his schedule around the time
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 0205 </TRAILER>
