<DOCNO> APW20000317.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Issue Ads Spending at Record Pace  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest groups seeking to influence elections
and legislation are on pace to spend record amounts on TV and radio
ads, and the tone already is more negative than in past years,
according to a report released today.
</P>
<P>
   More than $114 million has been spent or committed to
advertising by outside groups, based on a study of advertising
between January 1999 and March by the Annenberg Public Policy
Center at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising includes more attack ads than in previous years,
with about 40 percent of them criticizing a candidate or specific
legislation. Kathleen Hall Jamieson, director of the public policy
center, says that suggests the 1999-2000 election cycle will be the
most negative ever.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like there's going to be a lot of it and it's going
to be attack oriented,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, ads early in an election cycle were evenly divided
among attacks ads, advocacy ads promoting a candidate or position,
and contrast ads comparing the two parties. Attack ads became more
frequent as the election neared, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   As of early March, 37 groups have spent or plan to spend $114
million on issue ads this cycle. That includes a $20 million to $30
million pledge by Citizens for Better Medicare, a coalition led by
the pharmaceutical industry, and $20 million by U.S. Term Limits,
which supports legislation to limit the terms of members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   One in four ads deal with health care -- the most popular issue --
including several by groups trying to defeat the ''patients' bill
of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Big spenders on that issue include the American Association of
Health Plans, a managed care trade group, at $5 million; the
Business Roundtable, $5.5 million; the Coalition for Affordable
Quality Healthcare, $9 million and the Health Benefits Coalition,
$3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues addressed so far are the environment, gun control,
term limits and education.
</P>
<P>
   That advertising could help shape the public debate, Jamieson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ordinarily, the environment is not on the top of the issue
agenda,'' she said. ''The question is if you have enough
advertising back and forth, are you able to elevate it on the
national agenda? We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Environmental Trust has spent $11 million,
Republicans for Clean Air, $2.5 million and the Sierra Club has
spent $180,000, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995-96 cycle, the center estimated that $135 million to
$150 million was spent on issue ads by 27 organizations, about a
quarter of total political ad spending over those years. In
1997-98, the figures more than doubled to 77 groups spending an
estimated $275 million to $340 million.
</P>
<P>
   With eight months remaining until the November elections,
spending for the 1999-2000 election cycle is on pace to set a
record, the center concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike advertisements by candidates, issue ads are sponsored by
outside organizations and are subject to little or no regulation as
long as they are created independently and do not explicitly tell
viewers who to vote for.
</P>
<P>
   Precise totals for ad spending were not available because these
groups are not required to say how much they are spending or who is
donating the money that pays for the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the center gathers estimates from media reports and
independent groups that are willing to reveal their spending.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Annenberg Public Policy Center:
http://www.appcpenn.org/issueads/
</P>
</TEXT>
