<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singh, Waldorf Lead at Bay Hill  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG FERGUSON, AP Golf Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Tiger Woods' thrilling comeback to win
Pebble Beach last month seems to have had a lasting impact on a lot
of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when Jim Furyk won the Doral-Ryder Open by making
up a 6-shot deficit on the final nine, he attributed his
perseverance to being paired with Woods at Pebble Beach and
marveling at how he never gave up.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Vijay Singh used what he learned at Pebble to forge
a tie for the lead with Duffy Waldorf after the first round of the
Bay Hill Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Singh was within striking distance of the Pebble Beach lead in
the final round until he made a bogey on the par-5 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kind of gave up a little bit,'' he said, ''I shouldn't have
stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't at Bay Hill. Despite a sloppy bogey on the opening
hole, followed by another bogey from the bunker on the par-3 second
hole, Singh hunkered down, made six birdies and signed for a 68.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the way it's been for the last year. I get frustrated
very early and make a mistake,'' he said. ''But I'm kind of
changing the attitude a little bit and trying to not let any
mistakes bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, meanwhile, returned from a two-week break as if he never
left the tour. With birdies on all of the par 5s and no serious
mistakes, Woods breezed around Bay Hill for a 3-under 69 that left
him one stroke back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm hitting it pretty solid,'' Woods said. ''I came back
refreshed and ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at 69 was Honda Classic winner Dudley Hart and one-hit
wonder Mike Nicolette, the Ping Golf club designer who won Bay Hill
in 1983, quit the tour five years later and was as shocked as
anyone to be so close to the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not in their league,'' Nicolette said. ''Today, I was in
their league. Tomorrow, it's a municipal course round. I might
shoot 89.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson was 5-under for his last seven holes to salvage a
70, tied with players like Mark O'Meara and Stuart Appleby.
</P>
<P>
   The two kids from the 20-and-under league -- Sergio Garcia and
18-year-old amateur Aaron Baddeley from Australia -- both shot 75s.
Baddeley's round was particularly maddening, having played steady
golf except for a triple-bogey at the par-5 sixth. It could have
been worse. John Daly had an 18 on that hole two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Martin made a double-bogey on the last hole for a 74.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Hill has a strong field, with six of the top seven players
in the world ranking. That wasn't lost on Singh.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before the tournament starts, we kind of look around and know
who's playing,'' Singh said of a field that includes seven of the
top eight players in the world ranking. ''It makes you fight a
little bit harder out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh was beaten in the first round of the Match Play
Championship by Waldorf, who is quietly developing into a
consistent contender. Waldorf was among seven players who won twice
on the PGA Tour last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The wins kind of boost your confidence,'' Waldorf said. ''But
I think there are times where you have to go out and be confident
even if you're not making the putts or playing as well as you think
you should. That's the only way you're going to get to the place
where you want to be, which is contending and winning
tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   That's never been a problem for Woods, who hasn't finished lower
than 20th in a stroke-play event since he tied for 56th at Bay Hill
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Woods showed no signs of rust. Facing trouble on his opening
hole, he hit a flop shot from thick rough on No. 10 to within an
inch of the cup to save par, and got around with only a few
glitches after that.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied all of the par-5s and had eagle putts on three of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really didn't get myself in a lot of trouble,'' Woods said.
The lone exception was a 3-wood he sprayed into the trees on 18,
forcing him to pitch back to the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the third time in 13 rounds as a professional that
Woods shot in the 60s at Bay Hill, not a bad score in tricky
crosswinds that began in the morning and never let up.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anything under par is pretty good,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   With Woods, anything near the lead is not too bad, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
