<HEADLINE> NCAA Women's Tournament Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By CHUCK SCHOFFNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unable to finish the job on its first try, the Northeast
Conference is getting a second shot at Iowa State in the NCAA
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   St. Francis, the Northeast Conference champion, plays Iowa State
tonight in the first round of the women's tournament. Though
third-seeded Iowa State is expected to handle its 14th-seeded foe
easily, the same was thought of the Iowa State men against Central
Connecticut on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Central Connecticut, also of the NEC, tied the game at 69 before
second-seeded Iowa State pulled away to an 88-78 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was getting excited watching the game, especially when it
was tied,'' St. Francis scoring leader Jess Zinobile said. ''People
didn't think the game was going to be that close at all, and I
think a lot of people are overlooking our team, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest Regional game in Ames, Iowa, is one of 16 being
played at eight sites tonight in the tournament's opening round.
Sixteen more games are on tap Saturday, also at eight sites.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Connecticut (30-1), which has a home game with
Hampton (16-14) in the East Regional, is the only No. 1 seed
playing tonight. The other top seeds are Tennessee in the Mideast,
Louisiana Tech in the Midwest and Georgia in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lift St. Francis (23-7) got from watching Central
Connecticut, Iowa State holds every advantage against the Red
Flash, starting with the Hilton Coliseum crowd, which will be
13,000 and loud.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones (25-5) also are much taller in the middle and they
have sensational outside shooters. Led by second-team All-American
Stacy Frese, Iowa State is averaging nine 3-point baskets a game
and has made as many as 18 in a single night.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have seven people that shoot the three, it's coming
from everywhere,'' St. Francis coach Myndi Hill said. ''We've got
to be on our feet, we've got to have our feet moving, get our heads
up and get around screens.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn (21-7) also will need some tough defense in its Midwest
Regional game with Southwest Missouri State (23-8) in State
College, Pa. Auburn has to worry about one shooter: national
scoring leader Jackie Stiles.
</P>
<P>
   Stiles averages 27.7 points and scored 56 in the semifinals of
the Missouri Valley Conference tournament. She has taken almost
twice as many shots as anyone else on the team and can score off
the dribble, coming off a screen, on the run or with spin moves.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to have a great defensive plan to stop her,'' Auburn
coach Joe Ciampi said. ''Every indication is good things happen
when she has the ball. To be the leading scorer and have your team
win 23 ball games says a lot about the person and the team.''
</P>
<P>
   After complaining about being sent to Iowa State for the first
round of the tournament the last two years, Oregon finally gets to
play at home. The Ducks (23-7), seeded sixth in the West, play
11th-seeded Alabama-Birmingham (19-12).
</P>
<P>
   Oregon point guard Shaquala Williams said she and her teammates
are loose and ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we don't have much to lose, because people aren't
expecting us to go out and play well after the first round,'' said
Williams, who led the Ducks to the Pac-10 championship.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't lose any respect, because we don't really have any.
So I think we can use that as a motivating factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Mississippi State (23-7) was to have been the host
for that subregional but could not guarantee enough hotel rooms.
The Lady Bulldogs play St. Peter's (23-7) in the other game on
Oregon's floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton is bucking history in its game with Connecticut. As a
No. 1 seed, the Huskies have won their first-round games by an
average of 40 points. They beat St. Francis 97-46 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll have to play one of the better games we've ever
played,'' Hampton coach Patricia Bibbs said. ''Whatever we do, we
better try to do it better than the 30 others that didn't get it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   In Baton Rouge, La., Liberty (23-7) will make its fourth
straight NCAA appearance when it plays LSU (22-6) in the East
Regional. Liberty did not get past the first round in its three
previous trips.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first game is always a national championship game for
us,'' coach Carey Green said. ''Well, this is our national
championship game against LSU.''
</P>
</TEXT>
