<HEADLINE> Spring Training Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   After watching other teams pull off a four-way trade
at the
winter meetings, Texas, Toronto and Montreal got together for a
three-way deal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   First, Toronto sent David Segui and $825,000 to Texas, which
then dealt Lee Stevens to the Expos. To complete Thursday's deal,
Montreal sent Brad Fullmer to the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know how happy David would be DHing,'' Toronto manager
Jim Fregosi said. ''David will play more first with Texas than he
would have here.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui hit a combined .298 for Seattle and Toronto last season,
with 14 homers and 52 RBIs. A .285 career hitter, he was dealt by
Seattle on July 28 for pitchers Tom Davey and Steve Sinclair,
became a free agent after the season, then signed a $4,325,000,
one-year contract to stay with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens batted .282 last season for the Rangers, setting career
highs with 24 homers and 81 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I figured that they would release me before they would trade
me,'' Stevens said. ''It's going to be tough leaving Texas, because
it's the only place I have ever really stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fullmer split last season between Montreal and Triple-A Ottawa.
He batted .277 for the Expos with nine homers and 47 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ''My bat is my meal ticket,'' he said. ''I don't foresee any
problems as a DH, but I always thought my fielding was OK.'
</P>
<P>
   It was just three months ago that Colorado, Milwaukee, Oakland
and Tampa Bay joined for a nine-player deal at the winter meetings
involving Vinny Castilla, Rolando Arrojo, Jeff Cirillo, Scott Karl
and Aaron Ledesma.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, it was a high-scoring day as the San Francisco
Giants beat the Milwaukee Brewers 18-14, the Pittsburgh Pirates
defeated the Boston Red Sox 14-11 and the Cleveland Indians rallied
past the Kansas City Royals 11-10.
</P>
<P>
   At Scottsdale, Ariz., Milwaukee made eight errors and lost its
fifth straight.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Mark Loretta and first baseman Brian Banks made two
errors each for the Brewers, who have 13 in two games. Right
fielder Damon Hollins, pitcher Jim Bruske, catcher Creighton
Gubanich and second baseman Lou Collier also had error, but San
Francisco only scored three unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was probably one of the worst games you are ever going to
watch,'' Brewers manager Davey Lopes said. ''I'm not going to sit
here and criticize individuals. You can surmise it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bradenton, Fla., Pat Meares went 4-for-4 with three RBIs and
hit two of Pittsburgh's seven home runs. Kevin Young, starting
pitcher Todd Ritchie, John Vander Wal, Bruce Aven and Keith Osik
also homered for the Pirates. Aven's shot was a grand slam in the
fourth inning. Israel Alcantara homered for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was just one of those Florida days at McKechnie Field
where the wind was blowing and took everything right out of the
park,'' Meares said. ''I don't put a whole lot of stock in this.
It's nice to get some hits, but spring training really doesn't
matter. None of this starts counting until April 3, when we start
playing for real.''
</P>
<P>
   At Winter Haven, Fla., Dave Roberts hit a grand slam and Enrique
Wilson capped Cleveland's nine-run ninth inning with a three-run
homer.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's home run off Billy Brewer followed a two-run hit by
Jacob Cruz and Roberts' grand slam, both off Ken Ryan. It mirrored
Kansas City's 1999 regular season, when the Royals' bullpen blew 30
saves.
</P>
<P>
   In other games:
Twins 7, Reds 5:
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Myers, Fla., Ken Griffey Jr. hit his fourth home run of
the spring, a drive into the lake behind the right-field wall off
LaTroy Hawkins.
Dodgers 9, Mets (ss) 3:
</P>
<P>
   At Vero Beach, Fla., Shawn Green hit his first home run in a Los
Angeles uniform, and Devon White, F.P. Santangelo and Paul LoDuca
also homered. Mike Hampton allowed seven runs and 12 hits in 5 1-3
innings.
Orioles 9, Mets (ss) 3:
</P>
<P>
   At Port St. Lucie, Fla., Albert Belle and Greg Myers hit their
first home runs of the spring.
Astros 6, Braves (ss) 5:
</P>
<P>
   At Kissimmee, Fla., Craig Biggio, in a 1-for-23 slump, went
2-for-2. He singled off Tom Glavine the first inning and doubled in
the second, raising his batting average to .120. Atlanta's other
squad played Florida at Viera and was rained out after 3{ scoreless
innings.
Cardinals 3, Expos 1:
</P>
<P>
   At Jupiter, Fla., Kent Bottenfield struck out seven in five
innings, allowing three hits.
Yankees 8, Phillies 4:
</P>
<P>
   At Clearwater, Fla., Ricky Ledee went 3-for-4 with two homers,
and Andy Ashby had his fourth straight inconsistent start, giving
up four runs and eight hits in five innings.
Devil Rays 4, Tigers 1:
</P>
<P>
   At St. Petersburg, Fla., Esteban Yan was sharp again in his bid
to earn the fifth spot in the Devil Rays rotation, allowing one run
and two hits in five innings with four strikeouts.
