<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Investors Unfazed by tension  </HEADLINE>
By JOE McDONALD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- Yang Da-cheng hears China's threats to
attack his Taiwanese homeland. Then he gets back to work building
an amusement park for the children of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   As with Yang at his Shanghai Dream Park, thousands of Taiwanese
investors in China are conducting business as usual despite growing
tensions before Taiwan's presidential election Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While the close economic ties make force less likely, China last
month spelled out its bottom line: It will attack if Taiwan goes
independent, foreign forces intervene or Taiwanese refuse
indefinitely to negotiate unification.
</P>
<P>
   But commercial relations with the mainland are so smooth, Yang
said, that officials don't need to reassure him, as they once might
have, that his $400 million project is in no danger.
</P>
<P>
   ''They understand us. They realize we're not political, and this
doesn't affect business,'' said Yang, president of the 700-member
Shanghai Association of Taiwan Businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese have been investing in China for a decade, binding the
two sides closer together even as political ties languish and the
rival governments trade gibes and threats. If this standoff had a
peace movement, its activists would be executives in sober blue
suits and their slogan would be, ''Make money, not war.''
</P>
<P>
   China has been the focus of Taiwanese investment since the early
1990s, when the island lifted a ban on business ties dating to the
two sides' split amid civil war in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Taiwanese have pumped some $30 billion into China
and created millions of jobs. Factories set up to take advantage of
low Chinese wages make shoes, umbrellas and other goods that bring
in billions of dollars in export revenues. There are an estimated
800,000 Taiwanese businesspeople on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   But Taiwan still bans direct travel, forcing businesspeople to
visit the mainland via Hong Kong and other offshore spots. And, to
avoid becoming dependent on its giant neighbor, Taiwan limits
individual investments in what it calls a ''patience policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Even under such unhappy circumstances, investment and trade
will continue to increase,'' said Daniel Chen, executive vice
president of the Industrial Bank of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwanese companies have grown into a major commercial presence
in China, selling everything from office furniture to bottled
water. Dinghsin International Group claims the title of China's
biggest maker of instant noodles, selling 4 billion packets a year.
It has 22,000 employees in 30 mainland factories.
</P>
<P>
   And a new wave of companies from Taiwan's booming computer
industry is setting up factories both for export and to supply the
growing Chinese domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   Yang's Shanghai Dream Park, set on 200 acres where factories
once stood, also targets increasingly affluent mainland consumers.
Yang said it will employ about 2,000 people after its planned
opening next year.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist on the relationship, Chinese electronics maker
Bubugao Ltd. has imported Taiwan pop singer Chang Hui-mei to appear
in advertising on the mainland for its CD players and televisions.
</P>
<P>
   The latest escalation in China-Taiwan relations comes as Taiwan
prepares for Saturday's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Independence-minded Chen Shui-bian is a leading contender.
Although Chen has softened his earlier stance, saying he would only
declare independence if China attacked, his position has attracted
Beijing's ire.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Taiwan's biggest conglomerate issued a statement
Tuesday calling for whoever is elected president not to antagonize
China by advocating independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
