<DOCNO> APW20000317.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papal Visit Signals Healing, Hurt  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- At the Western Wall, a 13-year-old boy shrouded
in an oversized white prayer shawl recites Torah passages under the
supervision of a black-coated rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's proud relatives ululate and toss sweets to celebrate
his bar mitzvah, the Jewish rite of passage to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Snapping pictures, Christian pilgrims take in the scene from
behind a low barrier a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   For many, it is their first direct encounter with Jewish ritual,
and lends immediacy to a 2,000-year-old question: Can two faiths
that so directly challenge each others' basic beliefs learn to
accept one another?
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, who will visit the Holy Land late this month,
has gradually steered his church of 1 billion followers away from
the centuries-old ''Teaching of Contempt'' that says the Jews'
exile was punishment for the crucifixion of Jesus. Instead, he has
affirmed the validity of the Jews' own, separate covenant with God.
</P>
<P>
   Still, persecution of Jews by Christians through the ages, from
the Crusades to the Inquisition to the Holocaust, has left deep
wounds, and the pontiff's March 20-26 visit has brought resentments
to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Posters denouncing the pope as an anti-Semite and a pagan have
appeared in ultra-Orthodox neighborhoods. Even mainstream rabbis
are uneasy about what they call the desecration of the Sabbath
being caused by the visit: Thousands of Jews will have to work on a
Saturday to protect the pope.
</P>
<P>
   But the tension cuts both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's governments, which rest on the support of
ultra-Orthodox political parties, have been perceived as
occasionally insensitive to Christian interests.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Christians, including Roman Catholics, are sometimes
denied access to Jerusalem's holy sites because of Israeli closures
of the West Bank and Gaza Strip -- a complaint recently raised by
the pope's envoy, Archbishop Pietro Sambi, on Israeli television.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest dispute in Jerusalem's Old City, a parcel of land
containing the ruins of a Crusader church -- which some say may have
been built where Jesus was sentenced to death by Pontius Pilate --
has been leased to a Jewish seminary for use as an outdoor
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In a further complication, Israel has been riled by the
Vatican's recent political agreement with the PLO, which challenges
Israeli control of all of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Against this background, dialogue often seems impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Rossing, an interfaith activist, said that for Jews --
already a tiny minority of 14 million in a world with 2 billion
Christians -- the biggest obstacle is evangelism, a core commandment
of Christianity. The actual number of converts is tiny, though --
about 2,200 out of an Israeli population of 6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Holsinger, a 55-year-old school nurse from Dayton,
Ohio, said it was her duty to try to convert Jews, albeit with
kindness and patience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe they (the Jews) are blinded for our sake,''
Holsinger said during a sightseeing stop at the Western Wall, the
last remnant of the Jewish Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are the prayer warriors for them to see that the Messiah
has come,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli tour guide Daniel Rosenblum said that for many of his
Christian customers, especially evangelicals, acceptance of Judaism
seems difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ''They always try to persuade me (to accept Jesus). It sticks in
their throat that I, as a Jew, am unwilling to accept that Jesus is
the Messiah,'' said the secular Rosenblum.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes non-acceptance turns into hostility, he said. At the
Wall, for example, some pilgrims snicker or crack jokes at the
sight of black-coated Jews swaying in prayer or tying phylacteries
around their arms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The change in Catholic doctrine is often slow to filter down to
the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Angelika Aschenbrenner, a Catholic pilgrim, said that as
recently as 15 years ago, priests in her hometown of Deckendorf,
Germany, told worshippers that Jews had defiled the communion
wafers and Catholics had to do extra penance for that sin.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's chief rabbi, Meir Lau, gives much of the credit for the
change in doctrine to John Paul II, who he called one the best
friends Jews have ever had.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the Catholic Church has not done enough to confront
its actions during the Holocaust and should condemn the failure of
World War II-era Pope Pius XII to speak out against the Nazi
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Lau, who like John Paul was born in Poland, will receive the
pontiff at his Jerusalem office on March 23 and accompany him to
Yad Vashem, the Holocaust memorial.
</P>
<P>
   In their last meeting near Rome in 1993, the pope told Lau he
remembered Lau's grandfather, a prominent rabbi in Cracow where the
pontiff lived before World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The pope recalled how Lau's grandfather walked to synagogue on
the Sabbath, surrounded by dozens of grandchildren, and asked how
many had survived the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Five of 47, Lau said.
</P>
<P>
   The pope was deeply saddened by the answer, Lau said, and told
him mankind had an obligation to ensure the future of ''our older
brothers, the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Lau's office, city worker Dudu Atias sandblasted
graffiti reading ''Don't meet with the Pope'' off the stone facade.
</P>
<P>
   Next to him, five activists of the tiny Jewish extremist group
Kach posed for TV cameras, holding anti-pope posters.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tensions, many believe the very fact that the pope
is visiting Israel -- Pope Paul VI did not even mention the Jewish
state by name during his one-day drip in 1964 -- signals a turning
point.
</P>
<P>
   ''The important message (of the visit) is that the exile is
over,'' said Rabbi David Hartman, head of a Jerusalem seminary.
''There is no longer a notion of wandering Jews. They have regained
their biblical status of the People of the Covenant.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Israeli government Web site for pope's visit
http://www.papalvisit.gov.il
</P>
<P>
   Vatican Web site for millennium in the Holy Land
http://www.greatjubilee2000.org
</P>
<P>
   Live view and background on the Western Wall
http://www.kotelkam.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
