<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officer fatally shoots unarmed man in Manhattan  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A struggle with an undercover police officer
left an unarmed man fatally shot. Now police are trying to
determine whether the officer's weapon was fired accidentally.
</P>
<P>
   The early Thursday shooting -- the second fatal police shooting
this year -- happened just two weeks after police shot and killed an
unarmed man in the Bronx. Eleven people died in police shootings
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest shooting, Patrick Dorismond, 25, of East Flatbush,
Brooklyn, died from a bullet wound to the chest at St. Clare's
Hospital in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, three undercover officers from a narcotics
module of the NYPD's Gang Investigation Unit had been performing
drug buy-and-bust operations in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   They had made eight arrests Wednesday night involving drugs,
said Police Commissioner Howard Safir at a news conference Thursday
at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   At about 12:30 a.m. Thursday, the officers were near the Wakamba
Bar at 37th Street and Eighth Avenue -- a few blocks from Penn
Station and Madison Square Garden -- and one of the cops approached
two men standing in front of the location, Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men was Dorismond, who was employed by the 34th
Street Partnership -- a group of businesses in the midtown area -- as
part of its security force. Richard Dillon, the partnership's vice
president of security and operations did not release any
information regarding Dorismond's employment history.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said the officer engaged the men in ''a conversation
relative to drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior police official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the undercover officer asked the men where he could buy
marijuana. The men took offense, and a scuffle broke out, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The undercover officer was attacked by these two
individuals,'' Safir said. ''He was wearing a transmitting device
and he gave a signal that he was in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Anthony Vasquez, who was standing about 20-30 feet
away, came to the aid of the officer, said Safir.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani added that Vasquez's firearm discharged
once during the altercation. ''Patrick Dorismond was hit in his
chest and subsequently expired,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   No drugs or other contraband were found on Dorismond.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said police were investigating how the gun went off.
According to the police source, the undercover officer who was
allegedly attacked by the two men, told the District Attorney's
office one of the men yelled ''Get the gun!,'' which resulted in
the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Police could not immediately confirm alleged eyewitness reports
that Vasquez was hitting Dorismond with his service revolver when
it went off.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said Dorismond had been arrested three times in Brooklyn:
in 1987, when he was 13, for robbery and assault; in 1993 for
attempted robbery and assault; and in 1996 for criminal possession
of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez, 29, of Suffolk County, had three ''incidents'' on his
record, police said. In January of 1996, while he was still in the
Police Academy, he shot a Rottweiler that was attacking his family.
The shooting was deemed justified.
</P>
<P>
   In February of 1997, he pulled out his service revolver to break
up a fight in Pennsylvania, but he did not fire it and no one was
injured. Vasquez was placed on modified duty -- his gun and badge
were taken away and he was assigned to a desk job. He was returned
to full duty on Nov. 14, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Just four days before returning to full duty, Vasquez was
involved in a domestic dispute with his wife, but the incident was
deemed unsubstantiated, police said. Vasquez has been on the force
for almost five years.
</P>
<P>
   This shooting comes just two weeks after another undercover
officer fatally shot an unarmed man in the Soundview section of the
Bronx, blocks from where unarmed immigrant Amadou Diallo was shot
and killed last year by four police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Ferguson, 23, was carrying heroin and fleeing police
when he was killed inside a Bronx apartment building on March 1.
The officers pursuing him had clearly identified themselves, police
said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson's death came days after a jury acquitted all four
officers of murder in the Diallo case, and it sparked some outrage
among residents who claim police officers can get away with murder
in minority neighborhoods. Both Ferguson and Diallo were black.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Giuliani urged citizens not to jump to conclusions
about the latest police shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone should allow the facts to be analyzed and
investigated without people trying to let their biases, their
prejudices, their emotions, their stereotypes, dictate the
result,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0228 </TRAILER>
