<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Defends Refusal on Gore Counsel  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno is reluctant to
release a memo critical of her for retaining control of the
campaign finance investigation and defends her refusal to order an
independent counsel probe of Vice President Al Gore in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes she is tempted to release both the critical
memorandum as well as memos from other subordinates who advocated
the course she took, she said Thursday. Some Republicans in
Congress have regularly called for her resignation over these
decisions, which also have become grist for GOP attacks on Gore
during the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I often wake up in the morning thinking that (all the memos
should be released) or wake up in the middle of the night thinking,
yes, that's what we should do,'' Reno said at her weekly news
conference. ''But I have come to realize more and more that there
are institutional concerns that are extremely important.''
</P>
<P>
   Department staff lawyers, ''who give me such candid advice,
expect that their deliberative memos will not be released,'' Reno
said. ''And I want to make sure that future attorneys general are
not hampered by precedents that I might inappropriately
establish.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Government Reform
Committee, has subpoenaed the critical memo for a second time. It
was written in late 1998 by the department's campaign finance task
force chief, Charles LaBella, who has long been publicly known to
have advocated an independent counsel for campaign finance
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Burton subpoenaed the memo earlier, but he settled for being
allowed to read a copy of it after Reno argued release could
imperil pending investigations. He renewed his subpoena after some
excerpts leaked to the Los Angeles Times this month, including
LaBella's contention the department used ''gamesmanship,''
''contortions'' and ''intellectually dishonest'' double standards
to avoid an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the department was reviewing whether circumstances had
changed enough to allow release now but that she had yet to receive
a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if White House fund-raising remains under investigation,
Reno replied, ''I don't want to foreclose any avenue down the road,
but at this time I do not have specific and credible evidence of
any violation by a person who was a covered person when the
Independent Counsel Act was in effect.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, when that now-expired act was still in force,
she rejected an independent counsel to look into whether Gore lied
to investigators in saying he did not know some of the money he
raised during office telephone calls was spent directly on the
Clinton-Gore re-election, which was prohibited, instead of on
general party advertising, which was permitted.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, LaBella, FBI Director Louis Freeh and a senior Reno
aide, Robert Litt, recommended an outside counsel; Lee Radek, head
of the criminal division's public integrity section, and other
aides were opposed, department officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went through it carefully and could show no instance where
he (Gore) knew that what he had said was false,'' Reno said. ''We
also found very clearly that he had no motive to give a false
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged an assistant U.S. attorney in Los Angeles was
ordered to turn over to the public integrity section an earlier
probe of Gore's appearance at a fund-raiser at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Independent Counsel Act ... prohibited the use of grand
jury subpoenas or immunity or anything such as that,'' Reno said,
so the public integrity division routinely took over such cases to
ensure compliance.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the department recently obtained a conviction of
fund-raiser Maria Hsia in the temple case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 0229 </TRAILER>
