<DOCNO> APW20000317.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rose Friday, boosted by record
gains on Wall Street and an encouraging economic report from the
Japanese government. The dollar edged higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 313.09
points, or 1.63 percent, to 19,566.32. On Thursday, the average
closed up 174.63 points, or 0.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.96 yen in afternoon trading, up 0.48 yen
from late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its overnight level of
105.56 yen late in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, technology and telecommunication stocks led
gains as investors were encouraged by record-breaking gains on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   In New York trading on Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial
average rose 499.19, or 4.9 percent, to 10,630.60. That shattered
the Dow's previous record one-day rise of 380.53 points, set on
Sept. 8, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in Tokyo said that the explosive growth in the United
States of Internet-related businesses -- and the bull market they
have helped create -- may be a preview of things to come for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no reason everything we've seen in the U.S. -- in the
old economy and the new economy -- won't transfer over to Japan,''
said Robert Sasaki, head of the quantitative strategy group at
Jardine Fleming Securities Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Also improving sentiment was the Japanese government's monthly
assessment of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Economic Planning Agency said that signs of recovery are
emerging in areas including corporate investment, although it added
that the nation's overall economic situation remains severe.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 28.65 points, or 1.74 percent, to 1,674.22.
The TOPIX closed up 40.14 points, or 2.5 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar edged higher amid lingering
fears that Japan's central bank will step into the market to block
further gains by the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan bought dollars and sold yen twice in the last
two weeks, and traders said financial authorities have kept
tensions high by conducting daily checks on the volume of dollars
that Japanese overseas investors plan to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Tokyo is concerned that a strong yen will cripple the country's
nascent economic recovery by cutting into the value of its
dollar-based export earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Among other currencies, the euro was quoted at 102.90 yen, up
from 102.34 late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell
to 1.8300 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8400 percent. Its
price rose 0.08 points to 99.74.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
