<HEADLINE> Candidates on the Issues: Children  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Three days a week, The Associated Press picks an
issue and asks
the presidential candidates a question about it. Today's question
is from a survey by the National Association of Children's
Hospitals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Children
</P>
<P>
   If you could tell Americans one thing they need to know about
your commitment as president to acting on behalf of children, what
would you tell them?
</P>
<P>
   Republican George W. Bush: ''I have worked to strengthen
families, improve public schools, and increase access to quality
health care so no child is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore: ''I am committed to providing access to
affordable quality health care for all children, making preschool
universally available and bringing about revolutionary improvements
in our schools.''
</P>
