<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Slowing Aid to Mozambique  </HEADLINE>
By CRAIG NELSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- With heavy rains forecast for central
and northern Mozambique during the next five days, international
aid agencies are scrambling for ways to rush food to flood
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   The British navy anchored a floating helipad at the mouth of the
swollen Save River on Thursday to speed food to 45,000 flood
victims near the central Mozambican town of Machanga.
</P>
<P>
   From deck of the ship Ft. George, five British helicopters will
deliver 153 tons of food to survivors gathered in 14 sites near
Machanga, said Lindsey Davies, a spokeswoman for the World Food
Program.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. food agency has delivered more than 2,600 tons of food
to flood victims since Feb. 11, more than half of it by airplane
and helicopter, Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to look at all ways to get food in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Monthlong flooding in central and southern Mozambique has killed
at least 492 people, left 330,000 homeless and caused an estimated
$250 million in damage to roads, bridges, railways and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Rain in central Mozambique has slowed some aid deliveries this
week, and there were renewed fears of flooding. The Zambezi and
Buzi rivers were reaching a ''critical level,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   International aid groups have said they would like to end their
dependence on helicopters by the end of March and distribute more
aid in trucks, which are less expensive and can carry larger loads.
But the continued rain has washed away some roads.
</P>
<P>
   ''The unpredictable weather that's hampering our road access
will continue to make helicopters a vital source of aid for those
who need it,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 aircraft in Mozambique are assisting with the aid
effort, most of them helicopters, aid officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of refugees have been going back to their devastated
towns and villages to begin rebuilding their lives despite the
government's urging that they remain in aid camps for now.
</P>
<P>
   Their return complicates efforts to deliver food and other
supplies, since aid groups now need to send assistance to the
refugee camps and the villages.
</P>
<P>
   After a ruinous civil war that ended in 1992, Mozambique's
economy had been recovering when the floods struck. The growth
rate, roughly 10 percent a year, is expected to fall this year
because of the disaster. The country remains one of the poorest in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Relief organizations: http://www.interaction.org
</P>
<P>
   World Food Program: http://www.wfp.org/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
