<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl To Return to German Parliament  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Only months ago, Helmut Kohl's legacy as Germany's
unification chancellor seemed unshakable, when crowds of hundreds
cheered him on the 10th anniversary of the Berlin Wall's fall.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the crowds most often seen around Kohl have been the
media stationed outside his Berlin apartment, trying for comment
about his Christian Democratic party's scandal. Kohl's home also
was the target of protesters last week who demanded that he face
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl was to return to his parliament seat today for the first
time in months, seeking to reclaim some of his tarnished legacy by
appearing for a ceremony honoring the East German vote that set the
stage for Germany's reunification.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal erupted after Kohl admitted last year he accepted up
to $1 million from sources he has refused to name, saying he gave
them his word. Anonymous donations are illegal in Germany, and
prosecutors have launched an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The former chancellor's silence also has sparked a parliamentary
investigation into influence-peddling during his 16 years in
government, which ended with his party's defeat in 1998. The
scandal has since grown to include secret accounts, falsified
financial reports and more illegal cash handovers during his
quarter century as party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from all of Germany's major political parties
are to speak during today's three-hour event in the Reichstag.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl wasn't scheduled to speak, although all eyes are likely to
be focused on him. He last appeared in parliament Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's former right-hand man, Wolfgang Schaeuble, was pressured
out of the party's leadership last month by fellow conservatives
angry over his handling of the finance scandal. That means he moves
out of the first row in parliament to make way for the new faction
leader, Friedrich Merz.
</P>
<P>
   It was on March 18, 1990 that East Germans held their first
democratic parliament elections, electing parties that pledged to
reunite their country with West Germany. That summer, the
parliament voted to unify and Germany's two halves that had been
divided since World War II become one country again on Oct. 3,
1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
