<DOCNO> APW20000317.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mohegan Indians withdraw development offer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The Mohegan Indians and a Boston real
estate firm have withdrawn their offers to develop the former
Norwich Hospital site, clouding the future of the property.
</P>
<P>
   Mohegan tribal leaders made their decision Thursday shortly
after learning that Gov. John G. Rowland is giving other real
estate firms in Connecticut the next six months to find a corporate
client for the 470-acre parcel.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston firm, Spaulding and Slye, said Wednesday they would
need at least twice as much time to find a client.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal Chairman Roland Harris said the move was not related to
Rowland's action.
</P>
<P>
   ''In these types of projects, you have to decide whether you
want to continue or not,'' Harris said. ''We've got a lot going on
here. Other options may come along.''
</P>
<P>
   The tribe had proposed a hotel, golf course, spa, condominiums
and other amenities at the former psychiatric hospital, located in
Preston across the Thames River from the Mohegan Sun casino.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said the tribe still wants to proceed, but not on the
Norwich Hospital property. He would not say whether other sites are
being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish the state of Connecticut well in finding another
developer, because it benefits us all,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Spaulding &AMP; Slye officials said the governor's move puts the
development process back to square one.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm kind of perplexed with what the state is attempting to do
here,'' said David Vickery, principal analyst. ''They're not going
to fulfill what they think they want in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   A local advisory committee chose the Mohegans and Spaulding &AMP;
Slye as finalist to develop the project from dozens of potential
developers that submitted proposals more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has been awaiting an economic analysis of both
proposals from the University of Connecticut and comments from the
Department of Economic and Community Development. The panel then
was supposed to make a final recommendation to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   But Rowland opened up the project to other developers, saying
Thursday that the fate of the site, vacant for several years, has
dragged on long enough. He said it is unfair for Three Rivers
Community-Technical College, which hopes to build a consolidated
campus on the site, to wait for Spaulding &AMP; Slye to find a client.
</P>
<P>
   The company had initially represented Pfizer Inc. in the
selection process, but the pharmaceutical giant eventually dropped
out of the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland's decision came after a meeting with the Preston
selectmen, who have voiced strong opposition to the Mohegans'
proposal. The selectmen said they believe the site is well-suited
for a corporate entity and claim the region needs diversity, not
just more casino jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The truth is, if the town wants to hold up anybody with zoning
and permitting, they can. They want to run this thing out for five
years, they can, with those issues,'' Rowland said. ''So responding
to the selectmen, I said, 'Okay, fine. We'll get five marketing
companies to market this thing and whoever brings somebody in,
we'll look at the proposals, see if something works.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Preston First Selectman Robert Congdon, however, does not
believe that the time frame laid out by the governor is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that you market this piece of property in six
months,'' said Congdon. He said the advisory committee spent eight
months waiting for a consultant's report on the property. ''The
plan is destined to fail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000317.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spitzer: Evidence against Port Authority head is rock solid  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The state attorney general, accused of
politically targeting a longtime ally of Gov. George Pataki,
promised to show ''rock solid evidence'' that the chief of the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey had perpetrated a real estate
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert E. Boyle, head of the bi-state agency, received
Pataki's full support on Thursday and vowed to battle the
allegations made by prosecutor Eliot Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Describing himself as ''enraged,'' Boyle said Spitzer's charges
were based on ''incomplete and inaccurate allegations that go back
10 years.'' The 26-page civil complaint was ''a political
lawsuit,'' Boyle said in an angry three-paragraph statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is a Republican, while Spitzer is a Democrat. Spitzer
quickly shot back that he would not back off the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have rock solid evidence to prove that Mr. Boyle breached
his duty,'' said Darren Dopp, spokesman for Spitzer. ''We'll prove
it in the court.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll have to, Boyle said. He announced that he would not quit
his $165,000-a-year job, and promised to fight charges that he
profited from an allegedly shady 1990s real estate deal involving a
nonprofit hospital where he served as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to stay on the lucrative PA job was backed by
Pataki, who praised his beleaguered appointee.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a little shocked that something dating from 1990, 1991,
was brought up,'' Pataki said about the suit. ''I'm surprised by
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki stopped short of saying that Spitzer was politically
motivated. The governor said he would not ask Boyle to resign, and
expressed support for Boyle's reappointment when his current term
expires next month.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki appointed Boyle to the Port Authority job in early 1997.
Prior to that, Boyle had served as president of the Javits Center --
another job provided by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, as treasurer for Pataki's inaugural and transition
committees, Boyle helped raise more than $2.5 million for the newly
elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle allegedly hid his financial interest in a Westchester
County building, then used his position as chairman of the Hudson
Valley Hospital Center to influence its decision to lease and
eventually buy the property, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Due to Boyle's ''improper conduct,'' hospital officials -- after
paying $530,000 to renovate the Croton Building -- paid $550,000
more for the building in 1993 than it would have cost two years
earlier, said the complaint by Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint seeks an unspecified amount in damages,
restitution and interest to be determined at trial. Also named in
the complaint were two people who served on the board at Hudson
Valley Hospital Center, Arthur Clements and Ruth Woolfe.
</P>
<P>
   The charge against Boyle, 63, of Croton-on-Hudson, first emerged
in the federal tax-fraud case of Albert J. Pirro, a prominent
Republican lobbyist and the husband of Westchester District
Attorney Jeanine Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation -- later dropped by the U.S. attorney's office --
described a real estate deal that he and Albert Pirro entered into
with the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's suit, which covers the same transaction, alleges that
Boyle ignored his legal obligations to protect the hospital in
favor of his desire to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, Boyle learned two things in early 1991:
that the hospital was looking for new office space and that a
building in nearby Croton-on-Hudson was up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle, after allegedly telling Pirro to buy the building, became
a secret 45 percent partner in Pirro's real estate company,
Distinctive Properties. Boyle then arranged for the hospital to
lease space in the building, which Distinctive Properties had
purchased in April 1991 for $950,000, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital spent $530,000 to renovate the building and hired
Rogene Industries, a construction company owned by Boyle, as
construction manager. The building was sold to the hospital by
Distinctive Properties in 1993 at a $550,000 profit.
</P>
<P>
   The bi-state Port Authority oversees the region's three airports
along with many of its bridges and tunnels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0301 </TRAILER>
