<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 03:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BMW To Sell Land Rover Line to Ford  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE, AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- BMW Group is ending its vexing experiment
with its British-based Rover division, spinning off the
money-losing automobile unit to a British investment group while
agreeing to sell the profitable Land Rover line to Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ford CEO Jac Nasser said Thursday that the Dearborn-based auto
giant had a memorandum of understanding with BMW to buy Land
Rover's assets, and expected to complete the deal in the third
quarter of this year, assuming European regulators approve.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was valued at less than $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we think of our strategy of developing the premier
markets, particularly in off-road and 4x4 vehicles, we can't think
of a better group of brands and products than Land Rover,'' Nasser
said.
</P>
<P>
   BMW and Ford were to announce details of the agreement Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after BMW announced its plans Thursday to sell
the Rover passenger car division to Alchemy Partners Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   The investment group will take on the Rover and MG brand cars,
including their plant in Longbridge, England, and recast the
venture under the new name MG Car Co.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, those operations have burdened BMW
with $1.25 billion in red ink and dragged down profit an estimated
28 percent last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover, on the other hand is considered the crown jewel of
the Rover lineup. The company sells four models of luxury SUVs, two
of which -- the Range Rover and the Discovery -- are imported to the
United States. The company built about 160,000 vehicles last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser said Ford would get the four models of sport utility
vehicles made by Land Rover and Land Rover's manufacturing and
engineering offices, but no debt. Land Rover will join Jaguar,
Volvo, Aston Martin and Lincoln in Ford's Premier Automotive Group
for luxury vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's deal with BMW for Land Rover is yet another step in a
trend of global consolidation among automakers. Earlier this week,
General Motors Corp. took 20 percent of the Fiat Auto company from
its Italian parent, a few months after taking a similar stake in
the Japanese parent of Subaru.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers believe such deals will cut the massive costs of
designing and building new vehicles by allowing companies to share
components and factories around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the BMW-Alchemy pact remained a matter of contention
late Thursday. BMW said the two sides were still negotiating the
fine print of the arrangement after the company's supervisory board
approved its outline.
</P>
<P>
   BMW did say, however, that shifting the operations to Alchemy
will set the company back $3 billion in the form of a one-time
restructuring charge. Analysts said it was unclear whether the
price of the deal was rolled into that charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even getting Rover for free would not be attractive to most
people. It's a cash-eating company,'' said Christian Breitsprecher,
an auto analyst with Deutsche Bank. ''I'm pretty sure Alchemy's not
paying anything for the deal and is getting something on top.''
</P>
<P>
   BMW also unveiled plans Thursday to roll out a new line of the
sporty, subcompact Minis from its Oxford plant in early summer 2001
and continue building the Rover 75 luxury model in Oxford for
Alchemy. The company also plans to finish construction of its new
Hams Hall enine factory in Birmingham and begin production there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 0319 </TRAILER>
