<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 03:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITS  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It's a march of thousands, but today, the St.
Patrick's Day parade was expected to beam a spotlight on two: Rudy
Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the city's main political man was set to walk in
today's parade, and the nation's leading lady was to make her debut
at the historic parade. And each step taken by the U.S. Senate race
opponents would be watched -- for distance to each other and
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   But prayers came before politics.
</P>
<P>
   A Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral was to start the day. A major
figure could be missing this year: 80-year-old Cardinal John
O'Connor, whose health has been failing since he underwent brain
surgery in September. Church officials said he probably would not
greet marchers as usual in front of the cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   After Mass, the city's police force was preparing for another
kind of drama: the politics of sex, as represented by the Irish
Lesbian and Gay Organization, which was banned from marching.
</P>
<P>
   They planned a protest parade about 90 minutes before the 11
a.m. start of America's oldest and biggest St. Patrick's Day at
45th Street and Fifth Avenue. Walking from 59th Street down Fifth --
opposite the parade route -- the protesting marchers would end their
action at 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   As has become traditional, some will then turn around and try to
join the actual parade.
</P>
<P>
   And then, Giuliani was expected to kick off the event.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton created her own drama by just saying she would
participate -- against ILGO's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Though she had joined an inclusive Queens parade recently, ''it
doesn't matter where else you march, how many times you march, or
what spin you put on marching -- what matters is integrity,'' ILGO
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the 10th time the New York-based ILGO has been
barred from making marching under its own banner.
</P>
<P>
   The Ancient Order of Hibernians, a fraternal Catholic group that
runs the official parade, has repeatedly maintained its right to
exclude ILGO. And in February, a Manhattan federal jury ruled that
the city had not violated the group's First Amendment rights by
denying it a marching permit.
</P>
<P>
   The group's members aren't taking it calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by an Irish contingent, ILGO predicted a massive civil
disobedience march for today with a cast of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The 239th annual march would feature shamrocks and ''Kiss me,
I'm Irish'' buttons.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the protesters were expected to wear ''Kiss me, I'm
queer'' buttons -- as they did Thursday afternoon for a reception
honoring them in the office of Manhattan Borough President C.
Virginia Fields.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering of more than 100 included 53 gays and lesbians who
traveled from Ireland, where they're allowed to march as official
groups in St. Patrick's Day parades.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm lesbian, queer, Irish,'' announced Ailbhe Smyth, head of
women's studies at University College in Dublin. ''But I have to
say that in Ireland, we no longer have this kind of intolerance,
this kind of homophobia, this kind of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite opposition from the Catholic group that organizes the
parade, Catholicism was not missing from the gathering in Fields'
office.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Roche, a lesbian from Cork, Ireland, wore a gold cross
around her neck and noted, ''I go to Mass.''
</P>
<P>
   At home in Ireland, said the 30-year-old chef, ''there's not
that much discrimination. Here, we're hidden away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 0337 </TRAILER>
