<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Head North  </HEADLINE>
By THOMAS WAGNER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Following Wall Street's lead, Asia's top three
stock markets rose sharply today, even though a two-day trading
frenzy of the Dow industrials left some analysts worried about what
may happen next on the jumpy U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the world's second largest economy, stocks roared
ahead at the opening and remained high all day, due in part to the
Dow's biggest-ever daily point gain Thursday. The Nikkei 225 Stock
Average closed 313.09 points, or 1.63 percent, higher at 19,566.32.
</P>
<P>
   Traders also were encouraged by a new government report giving
an upward assessment of the Japanese economy, which recently
slipped back into a recession. The report said parts of the
economy, including corporate capital investment and personal
consumption, were on a sounder footing.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the coming few days, I think the Tokyo stock market will
have good momentum,'' said Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, a strategist at
Daiwa Securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's other two top stock markets earned even bigger gains,
following the lead of the Dow Jones industrials, which rocketed
nearly 500 points Thursday following a 320 point gain on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index jumped 723.99 points, or 4.43
percent, to 17,082.99.
</P>
<P>
   Traders credited Wall Street's record showing, but also said
they were relieved by the fact that China's military hasn't
attacked Taiwan because of its national election Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   During Taiwan's first direct presidential election in 1996,
China lobbed nuclear-capable missiles near the island's two major
ports. The United States sent two aircraft carriers and other
warships to the region to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Taiwan's military said things seem calm in the
80-mile-wide Taiwan Strait that separates Taiwan from China.
</P>
<P>
   ''This time the Chinese are only talking,'' one Hang Seng dealer
said in Hong Kong, which reverted to Chinese rule in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Although Taiwan and mainland China have been governed separately
since splitting amid civil war 51 years ago, China views Taiwan as
a renegade province and is demanding quick progress in
reunification talks by the two governments. The outcome of
Saturday's vote for the three top candidates could conceivably
spark a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In Singapore, the Straits Times Index opened sharply higher
today and ended the day at 2,094.47, 72.36 points, or 3.58 percent,
above Wednesday's tally. A holiday closed the market Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Dow industrials shot up 499.19 points Thursday
to close at 10,630.60 as investors poured money into blue chips
that had been battered by Wall Street's frenzy for technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning reversal of fortunes and came on the busiest
day ever in the history of the New York Stock Exchange. In just two
days, the Dow stocks wiped out more than 40 percent of their losses
over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   However, analysts remained wary that the rally might be nothing
more than another volatile day in a volatile year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this week's gains, the Dow still remained 9.3 percent
below its Jan. 14 record of 11,722.98.
(twx)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 0532 </TRAILER>
