<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 08:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets ended the week higher
across the board Friday on the back of the biggest-ever point gain
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index surged 723.99
points, or 4.4 percent, closing at 17,082.99. On Thursday, the
index had slumped 388.20 points, or 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers said the bulk of trading in Hong Kong took place in the
last hour, with investors snapping up banking and property stocks
following overnight gains on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 499.19, or 4.9 percent, to close at
10,630.60.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover was light because many investors stayed on the
sidelines amid concerns about Saturday's presidential election in
Taiwan. Relations between Taipei and Beijing will be further
strained if pro-democratic candidate Chen Shui-bian wins the Taiwan
elections, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained
313.04 points, or 1.63 percent, to 19,566.32. On Thursday, the
average closed up 174.63 points, or 0.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Wall Street's rally, the Nikkei was boosted by
the Japanese government's monthly assessment of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese Economic Planning Agency said that signs of
recovery are emerging in parts of the economy, which recently
slipped back into a recession.
</P>
<P>
   In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 105.94 yen,
up 0.46 yen from Thursday and also above its overnight level of
105.56 yen late in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore stocks also soared, bolstered by Wall Street's sharp
gains. The benchmark Straits Times Index rose 72.36 points, or 3.6
percent, to 2,094.47.
</P>
<P>
   The Taiwanese market ended higher as buying by government funds
overcame weak sentiment on the last trading day before the island's
presidential election Saturday, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
   The Taipei market's Weighted Stock Price Index rose 80.51
points, or 0.93 percent, to 8,763.27.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
   WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher on the back
of Wall Street's record rally. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index
rose 35.05 points, or 1.8 percent, to 1,999.31.
</P>
<P>
   MANILA: Philippine stocks rose in step with robust gains on Wall
Street. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 16.31
points, or 1 percent, to 1,646.28.
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY: Australian shares closed generally stronger, taking the
lead from their U.S. counterparts. The All Ordinaries Index rose
0.7 percent, or 23.2 points, to 3,203.4.
</P>
<P>
   SEOUL: Share prices closed higher. The Korea Composite Stock
Price Index rose 14.35 points, or 1.7 percent, to 855.57.
</P>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed higher. The
benchmark Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, rose
14.29 points, or 1.6 percent, to 934.78.
</P>
<P>
   JAKARTA: The key Composite Index rose 3.983 points, 0.68
percent, to 590.852.
</P>
<P>
   BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed higher on selective buying in
energy and building stocks. The Composite Index rose 3.91 points,
or 1 percent, to 399.74.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
