<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex Ambassador Morris Abram Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Morris B. Abram, a lawyer, educator, ambassador
and American Jewish leader who served the administrations of five
U.S. presidents, has died of pneumonia, a spokesman for United
Nations Watch said today. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Abram died Thursday at a hospital in Geneva, said Michael
Colson, an official with the nonprofit organization Abram chaired
until his death. Abram had remained in the Swiss city since he
stepped down in 1993 as U.S. ambassador to U.N. organizations here.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan paid tribute to Abram, saying
he was ''stunned'' by the news of his death and ''will miss him
greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While Mr. Abram was often critical of the United Nations, it
was always in the attempt to make it a better institution,'' Annan
said through his spokesman, Fred Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Abram served on the prosecution staff at the Nuremberg
Trials. Over the next 20 years, he worked on the Marshall plan and
the Peace Corps as well as with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents John F. Kennedy, Lyndon B. Johnson, Jimmy Carter,
Ronald Reagan and George Bush also appointed him to U.S. civil
rights commissions and other panels and international bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Abram, born June 19, 1918, in Fitzgerald, Ga., received degrees
from the University of Georgia, University of Chicago Law School
and attended Oxford University as a Rhodes scholar. A book he wrote
in 1948 about how to stop violence in his community led to anti-Ku
Klux Klan legislation, and he argued in favor of ''one man-one
vote'' in a landmark voting rights case before the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   He was president of Brandeis University in Waltham, Mass., from
1968-1970 and served as chairman of the National Council for Soviet
Jewry and as president of the American Jewish Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Abram published an autobiography titled ''The Day is
Short,'' describing his struggle with leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, he chaired the Conference of Presidents of
Major American Jewish Organizations and was named one of the 50
most influential Jews in the world in 1994 by the Forward
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce M. Ramer, national president of the American Jewish
Committee, said Abram was ''a giant'' who ''was dedicated to
righting the wrongs. He started with a passionate commitment to
civil rights in Georgia at a time when it was difficult to be in
that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Abram moved to Geneva in 1989 when Bush appointed him
representative to the U.N. offices based here. When he stepped down
in 1993, he joined with Edgar Bronfman, president of the World
Jewish Congress, to found U.N. Watch. The group monitors the United
Nations, and Abram was frequently critical of the world body's
treatment of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Abram is survived by his wife, Bruna Molina, and five children
from a previous marriage. The children -- three sons and two
daughters -- live in the United States, Colson said.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral is planned for Cape Cod, Mass., at a date to be
determined, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 0922 </TRAILER>
