<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 80.97; Nasdaq Gains 80.44  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks extended their gains today building on
the momentum from Thursday's extraordinary surge as the technology
sector once again took center stage.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 80.97 at 10,711.57 in
heavy trading at midday, adding to Thursday's 499.19-point surge,
the largest one-day point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's bold advance during the previous two days, which
included a 320-point surge Wednesday, was a stunning reversal of
fortunes. In those two days, the Dow stocks wiped out more than 40
percent of their losses over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher today. The Nasdaq
composite index was up 80.44 at 4,797.83. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 14.97 at 1,473.44.
</P>
<P>
   ''Momentum from yesterday's rally is carrying tech stocks
higher,'' said Paul McEnroe, a trader at Brown Brothers Harriman in
New York. ''But with the market's recent volatility, it's anybody's
guess where we take it from here.''
</P>
<P>
   The tech sector was leading the way today on both the Nasdaq and
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, Applied Materials rose 6 55/64 to 94 51/64, Sun
Microsystems rose 4} at 95{; and Qualcom rose 3[ to 136. On the
NYSE, Nortel Networks rose 8~ to 128|; and America Online rose 2{
to 64[.
</P>
<P>
   New inflationary pressure was also a consideration today.
Consumer prices rose 0.5 percent in February, the biggest jump in
10 months, led by a record increase in fuel oil prices and sharply
higher gasoline costs, the Labor Department reported. But excluding
the volatile energy and food categories, the ''core'' inflation
rate was a moderate 0.2 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   The figures appeared to cheer markets because they showed no
signs of a steep resurgence in inflation, something that would lead
the Federal Reserve to push up interest rates sharply. The Fed,
however, is widely expected to raise rates one-quarter point at a
meeting Tuesday, marking a fifth increase since June.
</P>
<P>
   In the inflation-sensitive market for government bonds, yields
on 30-year Treasury securities were flirting with a dip below 6
percent for the first time in nearly six months.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other unsettling factors is that today is a ''triple
witching'' day on Wall Street, a quarterly event that occurs when
contracts on stock options, index options, and index futures all
expire. Trading to settle such contracts often contributes to
market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   On the NYSE, declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-6
margin, while volume came to 682.78 million shares at 11 a.m. EST,
up slightly from Thursday's record-shattering pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.38 to 575.62.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
