<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> St. Patrick's Day parade spotlights Giuliani and Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It's a march of thousands, but today the St.
Patrick's Day parade beamed a spotlight on two: Rudy Giuliani and
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the city's main political man led the parade, and the
nation's leading lady made her debut at the historic parade. And
each step taken by the U.S. Senate race opponents was watched -- for
distance to each other and demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, which appeared smaller than in years past, perhaps in
part because Mother Nature offered up a freezing rain and swirl of
light snow, did it's best to embrace the politics.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy posters and Hillary shamrock stickers were as common as
green hair and ''Kiss me, I'm Irish pins'' along the route.
Giuliani's hometown supporters turned out in force, including about
100 women from the National Women's Republican Club who held signs
that said, ''Hillary, you need more than a seat, you need a
couch.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all from New York,'' said Giuliani supporter Kathleen
McCreary. ''We aren't bused in like Hillary's supporters are.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady was booed loudly along the avenue and heckled
with shouts of ''Go back to Arkansas,'' and ''Find your own
state!'' Clinton, accompanied by fellow Democrats City Council
President Peter Vallone and former Mayor Ed Koch, ignored the crowd
and continued smiling and waving. Her supporters tried to cheer her
on but they were outshouted at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's right,'' Jimmy Whelan, 67, of West Orange,
N.J., said of the emphasis on the Senate race. ''This is supposed
to be a religious-based event more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The day began that way with a Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral
attended by 5,000 people, including Gov. George Pataki, the mayor,
Clinton and Parade Grand Marshal Kevin Cahill, who is Cardinal John
O'Connor's personal physician and president of the Irish American
Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and Giuliani sat in the front row but not together, while
the first lady -- Giuliani's Democratic rival in the U.S. Senate
race -- sat several rows behind them.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-year-old cardinal, whose health has been failing since he
underwent brain surgery in August, did not attend. He also did not
greet marchers in front of the cathedral, where he traditionally
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a wonderful day but we were all saddened by the empty
chair on the altar,'' the governor said as he left the cathedral.
''We just pray for his health.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spoke at a breakfast hosted by City Council
President Peter Vallone, also wished the cardinal well. She said
she brought greetings from the president who ''as we speak is
meeting with the parties in the White House concerning the peace
process in Northern Ireland. He sends his best wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   She also made reference to her new status, saying, ''It is just
a great pleasure to be here as a New Yorker for St. Patrick's
Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani declined an invitation to attend Vallone's breakfast
because he was going to one hosted by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the start of the parade, some 66 members of the
Irish Lesbian and Gay Organization were arrested when they tried to
march down Fifth Avenue from 59th Street to 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The group did not have a permit and only marched one block
before police in riot gear stopped them. They were arrested without
incident and charged with disorderly conduct. An ILGO band played a
jaunty version of ''When the Saints Go Marching In,'' as police
made the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest St. Patrick's Day parade in the nation, which
stretches up Fifth Avenue from 44th to 86th streets and over to
Third Avenue, stepped off at 11 a.m. with Giuliani, Pataki and
Police Commissioner Howard Safir in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the start of the 239th annual march, Giuliani
mingled with a cluster of spectators holding up anti-Clinton
posters, including one that said: ''We've had our fill of Hill and
Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Giulliani, asked about Clinton's participation in the parade,
said he hoped she wouldn't get lost.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is her first parade. This is my 20th,'' he said. ''I've
lived in this state all my life, I've lived in this city all my
life. I've marched in this parade when I was a little boy. ... This
is my home.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's participation angered the Irish gay group.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot support Hillary,'' Emmaia Gelman, 25, of the Bronx,
said at the ILGO protest. ''She cannot trade civil rights for
votes. She has shown that she has no moral center and that she does
not understand civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the 10th time the New York-based ILGO has been barred
from marching in the parade under its own banner.
</P>
<P>
   The Ancient Order of Hibernians, a fraternal Catholic group that
runs the parade, has repeatedly maintained its right to exclude
ILGO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
