<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police union does about-face, urges parade boycott  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- There will be plenty of green in the
city's annual St. Patrick's Day parade. Just very little blue.
</P>
<P>
   In a late about-face, Syracuse police have decided to skip the
parade Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the 450-member Syracuse Police Benevolent Association
considered boycotting the parade because of grievances with Police
Chief John Falge but decided that their presence in the parade
meant too much to the community. Between 150 and 200 officers
usually march.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the police union opted to walk apart from Falge and his
deputy chiefs in a show of no confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The situation changed Thursday after Falge put out a memo that
officers not marching with him could not wear their uniforms. He
later issued a second memo saying officers could wear their dress
uniforms in the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Police union president Jeff Piedmonte said that took the wind
out of the officers' sails.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's the point of marching if the kids don't know who you
are?'' Piedmonte said.
</P>
<P>
   Police union board members voted Thursday afternoon to skip the
parade for the first time in its 17-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if I paid them if I could get most officers to
march,'' Piedmonte said, adding that he expected some officers to
still take part.
</P>
<P>
   ''The PBA and the banner won't be there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have been without a contract since Dec. 31. Relationships
soured further when Falge sided against officers in an assault case
brought against a veteran officer who was suspended for four months
without pay for hitting a 12-year-old girl with a nightstick while
trying to break up a domestic dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Falge criticized officers after nearly 100 of them showed up in
uniform outside the courtroom in what they said was a show of
support for the accused officer. The victim's family, the police
chief and mayor all said the presence of the white officers lined
up on either side of the small hallway to the courtroom was
intimidating to the black family, and stirred racial tensions in
the community.
</P>
<P>
   Falge said Thursday he thinks the entire issue has been a
misunderstanding and hopes the department can move on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 1314 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000317.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Rates Cited in Rover Sell-Off  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- BMW's decision to dump its Rover
off-road and passenger car lines reflects the growing rift between
countries using Europe's single currency and stubborn holdouts such
as Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The German automaker said Friday that the strong British pound
had hurt profitability and blamed the British government for not
doing more to keep it in line with the struggling euro. Britain
angrily retorted that the Rover sell-off was premature and
needlessly threatened thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We reached a limit in what we could tolerate in terms of
economic and business considerations,'' BMW chairman Joachim
Milberg said. ''We had to act now. We had to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Milberg said BMW lost $343 million in the past year alone simply
through a 12 percent increase in the value of the British pound
against the euro, which Germany shares with 10 other European Union
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, Denmark, Sweden and Greece are EU members but do not
use the euro. Britain in particular has vehemently resisted
adopting the currency and stuck with the pound, which has remained
strong despite the euro's decline since its Jan. 1, 1999, launch.
</P>
<P>
   Dearborn, Mich.-based Ford Motor Co. will pick up Land Rover for
$2.9 billion, while British investment group Alchemy Partners Ltd.
has agreed to take over the MG and Rover passenger car line. BMW is
footing $3 billion in costs just to dump the loss-making car
venture.
</P>
<P>
   BMW shares dropped 5.5 percent, or 1.76 euros, to 29.99 euros
($29.09) Friday on investor disappointment that the company was
selling largely profitable Land Rover. The drop came in stark
contrast to the 13 percent increase BMW saw Wednesday when it was
leaked that it would shed Rover's car division.
</P>
<P>
   Milberg acknowledged that BMW's decision to ditch Rover was
influenced by weak sales, falling prices and shrinking market share
as well as currency problems.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted that exchange rates figured strongly in the
calculation because the strong pound made it more expensive to
build Rover vehicles in Britain and export them to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The policy of the U.K. government made the already difficult
situation at Rover even more acute,'' Milberg said.
</P>
<P>
   British officials brushed off the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've never disguised the fact that the strength of the pound
has hurt some parts of manufacturing,'' said a spokesman for Prime
Minister Tony Blair, speaking on customary condition of anonymity.
''The government is not going to devalue artificially because that
route has led in the past to economic failure and boom and bust.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the British government worries that 16,000 jobs are at
stake, particularly at a Rover passenger car plant in Longbridge
that will be run by Alchemy.
</P>
<P>
   A strong currency can encourage companies to move production and
jobs to cheaper countries, but it also helps quell inflation and
attract investors. Keeping that balance has been a sore spot
between Britain and the euro countries.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Ford is shifting production of its Fiesta compact to
Germany because of similar currency-related cost increases at its
Dagenham plant in England.
</P>
<P>
   BMW says the pound stood at 2.53 marks ($1.24) when it took over
Rover in 1994 and has since appreciated to 3.18 marks ($1.56).
</P>
<P>
   Analysts sided with the British government, saying BMW was
masking a more fundamental problem -- a 25 percent drop in sales
over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Exchange rates are a bit of an excuse really,'' said Mark
Little, an auto analyst with Deutsche Bank in London. ''The weak
sterling hasn't helped things at Rover, but the simple bottom line
is that the Rover brand just doesn't work any more. It doesn't have
the prestige and appeal it once had.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. at http://www.ford.com
</P>
<P>
   BMW at http://www.bmw.com
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover at http://www.landrover.com
</P>
</TEXT>
