<HEADLINE> Docs: Normal Life for Tiger Victim  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Doctors said today that Jayton Tidwell has
cleared the first hurdle in his recovery and they are optimistic
that the little boy whose right arm was ripped off by a tiger will
have a nearly normal life.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old remained in serious but stable condition today at
Memorial Hermann Children's Hospital, where surgeons reattached his
limb just above the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ''As of this morning, we've now cleared the first hurdle, which
is the first 24 hours worth of blood flow in and out of the limb,''
surgeon Dr. Mark H. Henry said today on NBC's ''Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   It will take about six months before physicians begin to learn
the extent of Jayton's recovery. The boy faces more surgery and
rehabilitation over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   ''He looks perfect. He couldn't be doing better than he is right
now,'' Henry said this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Jayton should be able to live a normal life, Henry said, though
he never will have full use of the arm. The boy is right-handed, as
far as Henry knew, but should be able to transfer functions to his
left hand if he needs to.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no way he'll be 100 percent,'' Henry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengal tiger was kept in the back yard of the boy's uncle,
Larry Tidwell, in a working-class section east of Houston. The
animal attacked Wednesday afternoon when the child stuck his arm
through a gap in its chain-link cage, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Tracy Olivas, who called the tiger a nice and even
passive animal, said she rushed from her home when she heard
Jayton's ''bloodcurdling scream.''
</P>
<P>
   While Olivas' husband and Tidwell's wife coaxed the tiger to one
side of the cage, Tidwell's son retrieved the boy's arm. They
packed the limb in ice, and a medical team took it to the hospital
with the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery to reattach the limb began Wednesday night and lasted
for nine hours. Henry said the necessary blood vessels and nerves
were reconnected before a crucial six-hour window had closed.
</P>
<P>
   Tidwell was cited for keeping a dangerous animal without a
permit, a misdemeanor punishable by a $500 fine. Tidwell told
reporters: ''We're not telling anybody anything. The No. 1 thing is
that baby right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivas said the declawed tiger, named Cheyenne, is a 4-year-old
female that weighs about 400 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It will be quarantined for 30 days in order to comply with state
laws regarding an animal that bites a person. Determined to keep
his pet, Tidwell told animal control officers he will renovate the
animal's pen to comply with state permit requirements. The cage
needs a roof and a cement floor, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
