<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bodie Shivers as Death Valley Bakes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- California cornered the nation's hottest times
and chilliest moments last year, reporting the communities with the
most daily high and low temperatures in the 48 contiguous states.
</P>
<P>
   Death Valley, Calif., lived up to its hot reputation. It had the
nation's highest temperature 86 times in 1999, more than double the
runner-up, McAllen, Texas, which was hottest on 41 days, according
to an annual compilation in Weatherwise magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Death Valley also scored the year's hottest high, 123 degrees on
July 1. The lowest low was -43, recorded Jan. 1 at Tower, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the ledger, Bodie, Calif., a ghost town 50
miles south of Lake Tahoe, was the coldest place on 71 days,
followed by Wisdom, Mont., which was coldest on 45 occasions,
according to the report compiled by David Hickcox of Ohio Wesleyan
University.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the five cities recording the most daily highs were
Lake Havasu City, Ariz., 34 days; Laredo, Texas, 31 days; and
Lajitas, Texas, at Big Bend National Park, and Thermal, Calif.,
each with 27 days.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the coldest five were Shirley Basin, Wyo., coldest
on 24 days, and Tower, Minn., and West Yellowstone, Mont., 22 days
each.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Weatherwise magazine: http://www.weatherwise.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
