<HEADLINE> Undercover Cop Shoots Unarmed Man  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Police were trying to determine whether an
undercover officer's weapon was fired accidentally in a struggle
that left an unarmed man dead.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's police shooting -- the second fatal one this year --
happened just two weeks after officers shot and killed an unarmed
man in the Bronx. Eleven people died in police shootings last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest incident, Patrick Dorismond, a black security
guard, died at a hospital from a bullet wound to the chest. No
drugs or other contraband were found on his body.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, one of three Hispanic undercover officers
performing drug ''buy-and-bust'' operations approached Dorismond,
25, and another man outside a bar a few blocks from Penn Station
and Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The officer engaged the men in ''a conversation relative to
drugs,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir said at a news conference
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The two men attacked the officer, and Detective Anthony Vasquez,
29, came to his aid, Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who also attended the news conference,
said Vasquez's firearm discharged once during the altercation.
Safir said police were investigating how the gun went off.
</P>
<P>
   Police could not immediately confirm witness reports that
Vasquez was hitting Dorismond with his service revolver when it
went off.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, another undercover officer fatally shot an
unarmed man in the Bronx, blocks from where unarmed immigrant
Amadou Diallo was shot and killed last year by four white police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   All the officers in the Diallo case were acquitted of murder,
sparking outrage among residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
