<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-NJ--Obit-Rodeo Daredevil, Bjt,500  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo pursuing
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- Dorathy Yurkiewicz, a former rodeo
daredevil and stunt rider who turned in her spurs to become a
foster mother, has died. She was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Yurkiewicz, of Edison, who rode Brahma bulls, gave sharpshooting
demonstrations and had knives thrown at her, performed as Dot Cole
in the 1930s and 1940s after running off with her rodeo cowboy
lover at age 15.
</P>
<P>
   ''She never glamorized herself or thought about herself as
anybody special,'' said her daughter, Gail Lisa, 48. ''She'd rather
be remembered as a foster parent than a rodeo star.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Newark, Yurkiewicz was a feisty 5-foot-5-inch tomboy who
met and married 16-year-old Ted Cole after dropping out of high
school. The two toured with the Milt Hinkle Texas Rangers Rodeo,
the Sons of the Pioneers and the Roy Rogers rodeo companies.
</P>
<P>
   She made her mark as the first woman to ride a Brahma bull in a
national rodeo, according to the Women's Professional Rodeo
Association. ''Back in the days when rodeo was a big act, she was a
big part of it,'' said Jerry Gavin, a longtime family friend.
</P>
<P>
   Performing with her husband, she would be tied to a rotating
wheel while he threw knives at her. But she always insisted that he
have a couple of drinks first, according to Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were afraid that if he were sober, he'd try too hard and
he'd miss,'' Lisa said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, she spent nine days in jail after being pulled over by
police in New Jersey on the lookout for bank robbers. The police
found a cache of weapons, including a sawed-off shotgun, when they
searched her truck and didn't believe she was a rodeo sharpshooter,
so they jailed her.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, her rodeo colleagues verified her story and she was
released.
</P>
<P>
   ''She thought it was hysterical,'' said Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   In eight years with rodeos, she traveled all over America and
the world. But in 1944, her desire to raise a family prompted her
to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   Twice married, she had five children and raised 32 foster
children after moving to Union Beach. She never regretted giving up
the rodeo, but carried the memories of it with her for her whole
life. She taught her children rope tricks, yodeling, songs -- all
seven of her grandchildren and all seven of her great-grandchildren
learned ''You Are My Sunshine'' -- and other acts.
</P>
<P>
   Stricken by diabetes, which blinded her in her later years, and
liver problems, she remained active in community organizations. She
was a member of the Democratic Club of Union Beach, raised money
for the American Heart Association and was a member of the Cullen
Center for Seniors in Hazlet.
</P>
<P>
   And she yodeled all the way to the end. Her daughter recalled
her yodeling in the car on the way home from a doctor's visit last
Friday, two days before her death. ''She let out the most beautiful
yodel, in a very light tone,'' Lisa said.
</P>
<P>
   Yurkiewicz is survived by two daughters, two sons, a brother and
a sister.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral services were Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 1425 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
