<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 13.34; Nasdaq Rises 62.77  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks pushed higher today, extending Thursday's
remarkable gains, as investors have once again grown enamored with
the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average pulled back from an earlier
surge in choppy trading but remained up 13.34 at 10,643.94 in heavy
trading at midafternoon, adding to Thursday's 499.19-point surge,
the largest one-day point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's bold advance during the previous two days, which
included a 320-point surge Wednesday, was a stunning reversal of
fortunes. In those two days, the Dow stocks wiped out more than 40
percent of their losses over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher today. The Nasdaq
composite index was up 62.77 at 4,780.16. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 9.97 at 1,468.44.
</P>
<P>
   The tech sector was leading the way today on both the Nasdaq and
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ''The techs are rocking and rolling and the overall market is
acting very well given the recent runups. The Dow rose 800 points
in two days and it's still moving higher,'' said Alfred Goldman,
director of market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said the gains on both markets were surprising since
today is a ''triple witching'' day on Wall Street, a quarterly
event that occurs when contracts on stock options, index options,
and index futures all expire. Trading to settle such contracts
often contributes to market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, Applied Materials rose 7 5/16 to 95\, Sun
Microsystems rose 4] at 95[; and Qualcom rose 3 1/16 to 135 15/16.
On the NYSE, Nortel Networks rose 9{ to 129\; and America Online
rose 2\ to 63~.
</P>
<P>
   ''Momentum from yesterday's rally is carrying tech stocks
higher,'' said Paul McEnroe, a trader at Brown Brothers Harriman in
New York. ''But with the market's recent volatility, it's anybody's
guess where we take it from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Large brokerage firms were also up across the board, with Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter up 6 5/16 at 87 1/16, Merrill Lynch up 5 3/16
at 105 11/16, discount broker Charles Schwab up 5} at 55{.
</P>
<P>
   New inflationary pressure was also a consideration today.
Consumer prices rose 0.5 percent in February, the biggest jump in
10 months, led by a record increase in fuel oil prices and sharply
higher gasoline costs, the Labor Department reported. But excluding
the volatile energy and food categories, the ''core'' inflation
rate was a moderate 0.2 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   The figures appeared to cheer markets because they showed no
signs of a steep resurgence in inflation, something that would lead
the Federal Reserve to push up interest rates sharply. The Fed,
however, is widely expected to raise rates one-quarter point at a
meeting Tuesday, marking a fifth increase since June.
</P>
<P>
   In the inflation-sensitive market for government bonds, yields
on 30-year Treasury securities were flirting with a dip below 6
percent for the first time in nearly six months.
</P>
<P>
   On the NYSE, declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 8-to-7
margin, while volume came to 943.43 million shares at 2 p.m. EST,
down somewhat from Thursday's record-shattering pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.25 to 572.99.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
