<HEADLINE> Residential Hotel Fire Injures 14  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) -- An early morning fire at a
four-story residential hotel injured more than a dozen people.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. T. Mixon this afternoon said he was unaware of any
fatalities. Earlier, a man who answered the phone at the Highland
Park Department of Public Safety and gave his name as John Casatera
had said there was one dead.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen people were treated at two Detroit hospitals; seven of
them remained hospitalized this afternoon. At least two were
injured when they jumped from windows, while others suffered from
burns and smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said a man was clinging to an upper-story window for
several minutes before he fell to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were screaming, 'Hang on, hang on.' But he just couldn't
hang on any longer,'' said Sharon Joseph, 50. ''I can't imagine
what was going through his mind. And then he fell.''
</P>
<P>
   WXYZ-TV said the man was in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Ronald Parham said investigators believe the fire began
when a woman accidentally knocked over a burning candle in the
roughly 80-unit, 100-resident building.
</P>
<P>
   Highland Park, an impoverished city of about 25,000, was the
former headquarters of Chrysler Corp. before the company moved to
Auburn Hills.
</P>
