<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arnold Newman's Photos Displayed  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arnold Newman has snapped them all, from
Russian composer Igor Stravinsky to Nazi industrialist Alfried
Krupp -- with dozens of artists, poets and presidents along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Many are included among the 160 photos in the Corcoran Gallery
of Art's ''Breaking Ground'' exhibit which opens Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Newman pioneered ''environmental portraits'' with the subject in
surroundings representative of his or her life -- catching the human
animal in its native habitat.
</P>
<P>
   In the Stravinsky photo, his head and shoulders appear in a
corner of the photo, overshadowed by the raised lid of his grand
piano. The frame on the lid looks like a hugely exaggerated symbol
in a musical score, the one that shows a note is to be played flat.
</P>
<P>
   Krupp, who was sentenced to 12 years in prison at the Nuremberg
trials, sits bathed in an evil greenish-yellow light. Behind him
looms a prison-like factory, part of the industrial empire restored
to him when he was released.
</P>
<P>
   At 82, Newman thinks he may someday go back to painting, where
he started, but quit because he was too poor to finish art school.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's Al Hirschfeld, he's 97 and still at it,'' Newman
mused.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld, who actually will be 97 in June, is best known for
caricatures of entertainment figures. Newman has a pensive Woody
Allen on the dust jacket of his catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Active and talkative about history and politics as well as
photography, Newman led reporters through a preview of the show,
reliving his 62-year career. He explained that for important
historic figures he liked an intensely close-up portrait, ''showing
every pore.''
</P>
<P>
   President Truman posed for Newman soon after he left office in
1953.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't resist asking him afterwards: 'Mr. President, why
did you drop the bomb?''' Newman said. Truman talked to him for a
half-hour, convincing him that ''he saved thousands of lives, not
only American lives, but Japanese lives. The Japanese would have
fought down to the last baby,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newman also told a story about Pablo Picasso, whom he
photographed in southern France a year later. Picasso asked him if
he would like to do Henri Matisse -- the aging painter who was one
of the leaders of the French impressionists.
</P>
<P>
   ''Picasso picked up the phone and started a long conversation,''
Newman recalled. ''My French is like that'' - he held two fingers
half an inch apart - ''but I could hear his tone going lower and
lower. Finally he put the phone down. 'Fini... fini... (finished),'
he said. Matisse died a few months later.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman's portrait of Picasso -- a single eye peering out of a
torn paper frame -- faces the title page of the show's catalog.
</P>
<P>
   ''People talk about piercing eyes,'' Newman said. ''It's usually
not true, but Picasso's eye went right through.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Arnold Newman - Breaking Ground'' closes May 21. Suggested
contributions are $3 for adults, $1 for seniors and students, and
$5 for family groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
