<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Tribune, L.A. Times win Headliner honors  </HEADLINE>
With BC-NJ--Headliner Awards-List, 2-Takes
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- The Chicago Tribune and ABC News have
captured top honors in the 66th annual National Headliner Awards, a
national journalism competition sponsored by The Press Club of
Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Announced Friday, the awards will be presented at a May 6
banquet at Caesars Atlantic City Hotel Casino.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune won first place for public service and Best of Show
in the print division for its examinations of prosecutorial
misconduct and flaws in the death penalty system in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Ken Armstrong, Maurice Possley and Steve Mills, the
''Trial and Error'' series showed how prosecutors cheat and hide
evidence but are rarely punished for it. ''The Failure of the Death
Penalty in Illinois'' stories showed how bad lawyers, faulty
evidence and forced confessions have undermined the administration
of capital punishment in that state.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was powerful journalism,'' the Headliner judges wrote.
''The impact was profound. The governor of Illinois placed a
moratorium on all executions and lawmakers around the country are
now taking a close, hard look at the death penalty issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC News, and its Peter Jennings and Tom Yellin, won best
documentary and Best of Show in television for ''The Century,'' a
12-hour series examining the most extraordinary events of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   ''The judges recognize the enormous task undertaken to review
the century, bringing perspective and remembrances as we enter a
new millennium. Thank you, ABC News,'' the judges wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Times photographer David Bohrer won top honors in
that division for his ''unforgettable'' image of police officers
leading children away from the site of a shooting at the North
Valley Jewish Community Center in Granada Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   KCBS radio in San Francisco was the top winner in radio, taking
first place in investigative reporting and Best of Show for ''MUNI
Workers Comp,'' a four-part series exposing abuses in the San
Francisco transit agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press won first place for coverage of a major
news event or topic by a news service or syndicate for its stories
on the alleged massacre of South Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers
at the village of No Gun Ri in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Other AP first-place winners were Helen O'Neill, for feature
writing; J. Pat Carter for spot news photography; Eric Draper for
feature photography and the AP staff for informational or
illustrative graphics.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,600 entries were received for the annual
competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
