<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Police Monitor Pilgrims  </HEADLINE>
By BASSEM MROUE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINA, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Officers scrutinized security screens
Friday for any sign of accidents, illnesses or the first shoves of
a stampede as 2.1 million hajj pilgrims wound down the annual
Muslim pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the hundreds of cameras placed along the pilgrimage
route were trained Friday on Mina, where pilgrims symbolically
stoned the devil. The city was the site of a stampede two years ago
that killed 180 people.
</P>
<P>
   Other cameras scanned pilgrims praying in Mecca's Grand Mosque.
</P>
<P>
   A bridge near the Jamarat -- the three pillars representing the
devil -- was packed Friday with tens of thousands of pilgrims. A
helicopter flew overhead and policemen urged people to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of ambulances were parked nearby, but by day's end all
had gone smoothly. The scene will continue Saturday and Sunday,
when the last of the pilgrims complete the ritual.
</P>
<P>
   This year's hajj has been one of the most trouble-free in years:
There have been no large-scale tragedies, although six women were
crushed to death at the Grand Mosque last week and five people have
died in traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hajj this year is considered better than the past ones,''
said Brig. Abdulaziz M. bin Saeed, commander of the Public Security
in the holy areas. ''Mecca is totally under control and we have two
new camera networks in the Jamarat area.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, fire tore through a sprawling, overcrowded tent city at
Mina, trapping and killing more than 340 pilgrims and injuring
1,500. In 1994, a stampede killed 270 pilgrims. The most deadly
hajj-related tragedy was a 1990 stampede in which 1,426 pilgrims
were killed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dozens of cameras at Mount Arafat and Muzdalifah,
bin Saeed said there are 53 cameras in Mina and 650 in Mecca's
Grand Mosque. There have been fewer accidents this year, he said,
and more pickpockets have been arrested. Figures were not
available.
</P>
<P>
   In case something does go wrong, officers can guide policemen
and pilgrims via dozens of loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel so good, the Saudis are organizing everything and its
going normal,'' Mohammed Aref Khan a 42-year-old Pakistani said
after throwing stones at the pillars and leaving the area.
</P>
<P>
   Friday also marked the beginning of the three-day Ayam
al-Tashreek or ''days of drying meat,'' which follows Eid al-Adha,
the feast of sacrifice holiday celebrated throughout the Muslim
world with the slaughtering of sheep, cows and camels.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday was a good day for barbers, whose open-air shops were
packed with pilgrims paying $2.75 a piece for haircuts or to shave
their entire heads at the end of the hajj. Islam's founder, the
Prophet Mohammed, shaved his head after making the pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   The hajj is one of the five pillars of Islam and is required at
least once in the lifetime of every Muslim who is financially and
physically able to perform it.
</P>
<P>
   After the devil-stoning ritual, which began on Thursday,
pilgrims head to nearby Mecca, where they circle the Kaaba, the
cubic stone in the center of the Grand Mosque, Islam's holiest
site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
