<BODY>
<HEADLINE> INS Allows Somalian To Seek Asylum  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Immigration officials granted conditional parole to
an 18-year-old Somali man who is seeking political asylum after
claiming his life would be in danger from rival clans if he
returned home.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Kare Abshir Jama was released from Krome Detention Center
in Miami late Thursday after unidentified sponsors willing to
support him stepped forward, INS spokesman Rodney Germain said. He
would not identify the sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Jama arrived in the United States by himself Dec. 23, saying he
had no known living relatives left in Somalia. He had been in INS
custody since his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The INS initially blocked Jama's attempt to apply for legal
status through an INS program for abused or abandoned juveniles and
a federal judge said he lacked jurisdiction to hear the teen's
case.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge's ruling, an INS dentist examined Jama and
concluded from his teeth that he was an adult subject to INS adult
rules. Jama was then transferred from a juvenile center where he
had been staying to Krome, an INS detention center for adults.
</P>
<P>
   Jama's lawyer, Cheryl Little, commended the parole but cautioned
that her client still has to go through the difficult political
asylum application process.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll do our best,'' she said. ''At least we have some good
news now.''
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit, Jama said that when civil war broke out in
1990, he left Somalia with his father for a Kenyan refugee camp
before settling in Ethiopia. The teen wrote that in 1996, he saw
his father killed by bandits.
</P>
<P>
   Jama said he is from the minority Madiban clan and that he could
be killed by members of rival Somali clans if he returns to his
homeland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
