<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal John O'Connor too sick to attend St. Patrick's Day Mass,parade  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS OLERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For 15 years every March 17, Cardinal John
O'Connor reigned on the cathedral steps, blessing children and
greeting thousands of St. Patrick's Day parade marchers. The ailing
leader of 2.4 million Catholics was forced to stay home on Friday,
disappointing his flock.
</P>
<P>
   Five thousand worshippers packed St. Patrick's Cathedral for the
pre-parade Mass, which is also attended by many New York and Irish
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''His eminence (O'Connor) joins his prayers with yours and with
the intercession of St. Patrick prays for your good health and
happiness,'' said Bishop Patrick Sheridan, pinch-hitting for the
cardinal, who has been ailing since undergoing surgery in September
for a brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We pray may God continue to bless him,'' Sheridan said.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Zwilling, the cardinal's spokesman, said he was in his
residence adjoining the cathedral, and had not been in his
archdiocese office since March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a big disappointment for him not being able to be here,''
Zwilling added.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, 80, has missed public Mass for the last several weeks,
including Ash Wednesday Mass and services. He has suffered partial
hearing loss and difficulty reading as a result of his illness.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're praying for him,'' said Ann Coyle of Bronxville, N.Y.,
attending the parade with two friends from Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't think he'd be here, as much as I wanted him to be
here,'' added Coyle, a retired magazine business manager.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Mary Martin of the Franciscan Sisters of the Atonement
shivered on the steps of St. Patrick's Cathedral, as a freezing
rain and light snow fell. She made a 45-mile train trip from
upstate Putnam County to attend the cardinal's Mass, and was
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I miss the cardinal. That's why I came down here,'' she said.
''He's done everything for New York. The parade's not the same
without him.''
</P>
<P>
   On every St. Patrick's Day for the last 15 years, the cardinal
has stood on the steps of the cathedral for hours waving and
personally greeting marchers -- thousands of police officers, city
workers, commissioners, politicians and visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who attended the Mass Friday, said he
had greeted the cardinal in 15 previous St. Patrick's Day parades.
</P>
<P>
   ''I missed him at the Mass, and I missed him in front of St.
Patrick's. I'm very hopeful that he's going to make a full,
complete recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass, Gov. George Pataki said, ''We were all saddened
by the empty chair on the altar. We just pray for his health.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
