<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Faeroes Negotiate With Denmark  </HEADLINE>
By JAN M. OLSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- Denmark toughened its stance toward
the Faeroe Islands on Friday, saying the 18 rocky North Atlantic
islands would have to give up Danish subsidies within four years if
they wanted independence.
</P>
<P>
   The islands' nationalistic government and offshore oil prospects
have awakened old Faeroese dreams of political and economic
independence from Denmark, which provides them with $130 million
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Faeroese Prime Minister Anfinn Kallsberg and Hoegni Hoydal,
Faeroese minister for Home Rule affairs, presented Danish officials
with a plan to grant the islands independence but keep Denmark's
Queen Margrethe as their head of state and continue to link their
local currency to the Danish krone.
</P>
<P>
   They also want a 15-to-20 year transitional period, during which
Denmark would continue its subsidies, which account for one-third
of the territory's budget.
</P>
<P>
   But Danish Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen said Denmark
would only give the islands three to four years before cutting off
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not opposed to them becoming a sovereign state,'' Nyrup
Rasmussen said at a news conference, after four tense hours of
talks. ''But total independence leads to a complete halt of the
economical support.''
</P>
<P>
   Both groups said talks would continue, but offered no details.
</P>
<P>
   Independence is an emotional issue for many of the 45,000
islanders, who retain their old Faeroese language and flag and
generally refer to the islands as a nation. The people have
substantial autonomy, except in foreign affairs, military concerns,
courts and police.
</P>
<P>
   To secede from Denmark, the islanders would have to vote in a
referendum later this year. Independence would also require that
Denmark change its constitution -- a lengthy process that would
involve separate votes in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time the Faeroes, which have been Danish
territory for more than 600 years, have sought independence.
Earlier attempts in 1906 and 1946 failed when islanders rejected
the plans in referendums.
</P>
<P>
   The archipelago's economy relies heavily on fish sales and
exports, which make up more than 95 percent of its gross domestic
product. But Faeroe officials are pinning their future economic
hopes on oil. The government plans to launch the first licensing
round for offshore oil exploration in Faeroese waters, although it
has yet to set a date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
