<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Squatters Ordered Off Farms  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- A judge on Friday ordered a group of
squatters, including black veterans of Zimbabwe's war for
independence, to end their illegal occupation of white-owned farms.
</P>
<P>
   The squatters, who have occupied more than 500 farms for the
past month, must leave within 24 hours, High Court Judge Paddington
Garwe ruled. He instructed police to help remove the squatters and
to ignore any counter-orders from President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   The squatters are led by veterans armed with spears, axes,
knives and guns. The judge's order to remove them goes against
statements from Mugabe and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Mugabe said the squatters were protesting land
ownership by whites in the colonial era and that they could remain
on private properties until the government gave them their own
plots. Earlier, Police Chief Augustine Chihuri said police were
powerless to enforce private ownership laws in this case because
the occupations are political.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition groups have accused Mugabe of promising free land and
allowing the veterans to seize land in an effort to shore up his
collapsing support before elections in April.
</P>
<P>
   In February, 55 percent of voters here rejected a revised
constitution backed by Mugabe that would have empowered him to
seize white-owned land without paying compensation. The rejection
was Mugabe's biggest political defeat since he led the nation, then
known as Rhodesia, to independence in a seven-year bush war.
</P>
<P>
   Alleged government infringements of Zimbabwe's bill of rights
have long strained relations between Mugabe, 76, and the nation's
independent judiciary. Garwe's order was expected to again set the
two on a collision course.
</P>
<P>
   The judge issued his order in a closed hearing with lawyers
representing the veterans and a union of about 4,000 white farmers.
He instructed the police chief to deploy enough men to evict all
squatters who remain on private land, identify all the squatters
and properly investigate offenses committed on occupied farms.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans, who fought in the war that led to independence in
1980, blocked entry to the High Court building and chanted
revolutionary songs Friday as Garwe prepared his order.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours earlier, veterans assaulted a CNN television crew
that was filming them on a white farm northwest of Harare. Husband
and wife crew Bob and Amy Coen were treated and released for minor
injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
