<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paterson closes school for a second Islamic holiday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PATERSON, N.J. (AP) -- The closure of Paterson's public schools
for an Islamic feast day on Friday marks the second Islamic holiday
for such a closing in the state's third-largest school district.
</P>
<P>
   No other district in New Jersey closes for Islamic holidays,
said Mike Yaple, spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Students were off from school Friday for the first time for Eid
al-Adha, a festival marking the end of a Muslim's required journey
to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, the schools have closed on Eid
al-Fitr, which marks the end of the Islamic month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims within the Paterson district welcomed the latest
closure. Eid al-Adha is celebrated with a feast.
</P>
<P>
   ''Newark doesn't have it. Jersey City doesn't have it. They are
far behind,'' Lal Pathan, director of the American Muslim Council
of New Jersey, told The Star-Ledger of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims comprise 21,000 of the more than 150,000 people in
Paterson, and account for about 3,700 school-aged children, Pathan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eid al-Adha is a three-day festival that starts on the 10th day
of the Muslim month of Thul-hijjah, which begins with the sighting
of the new moon. This marks the end of the hajj, the journey to
Mecca that a Muslim is required to make once in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   However, starting dates of Eid al-Adha varies, according to
Islamic clerics and mosque officials who either rely on the moon's
sighting in Saudi Arabia or in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a big problem for us right now,'' said Yaser El Menshawy,
chairman of the Council of Mosques of New Jersey, an organization
of mosques and Islamic groups. ''Within one town, you'll have
mosques celebrating it Thursday and some Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Muslims in Paterson at Masjid An-Nur Islamic Center
and the Islamic Center of Passaic County began celebrations on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of the day, people visit one another and there's a lot
of going to each other's homes and eating there,'' said Imam Hamzah
Abdus-Salaam of the Masjid An-Nur Islamic Center.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, there are 45 recognized religious school
holidays, Yaple said.
</P>
<P>
   ''School boards can add religious holidays to its own
districts,'' Yaple said. ''But there's a fine line between church
and state. For instance, you can't close a school for religious
reasons, but you can close it for pragmatic reasons because
students can't be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 1709 </TRAILER>
