<HEADLINE> Ecuador OK For Banana Sanctions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Ecuador has received the go-ahead from the World
Trade Organization to impose $201.6 million in annual sanctions
against the European Union in their long-running banana dispute,
diplomatic sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The amount was specified by WTO arbitrators. The South American
nation had requested permission to impose sanctions to the value of
$450 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador, the world's largest producer of bananas, pushed last
year to impose the sanctions following a WTO ruling that the EU
banana import policy discriminates against Latin American
producers.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is already imposing sanctions of $191.2
million per year against the European Union over the same issue.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador has said its retaliation would consist of suspending
agreements on ''intellectual property,'' which require it to
respect copyrights and to pay for the right to broadcast music and
films.
</P>
<P>
   It sees this as a way for the developing country to take action
against the much richer EU without damaging its own economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Ecuador sanctions would apply to 13 of the 15 EU members.
Denmark and the Netherlands, which have consistently urged the EU
to agree to U.S. demands in the banana fight, would be exempted.
</P>
<P>
   The European rules were declared unfair by the WTO because they
favored bananas from former colonies in Africa and the Caribbean at
the expense of Latin American producers and their U.S.
distributors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
