<HEADLINE> Arrest in Germany School Shooting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSENHEIM, Germany (AP) -- The father of a 16-year-old student
who allegedly shot the headmaster of his boarding school was
arrested Friday on weapons charges after police found three illegal
weapons among the 46 guns in the family's home.
</P>
<P>
   The student apparently had a key to get to the guns, which
included 43 rifles, two machine guns and a military assault rifle.
Private citizens are not allowed to own the latter two types of
weapons in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth-grader allegedly returned to the Castle Brannenburg
school in the Bavarian town of Brannenburg on Thursday after having
been suspended the day before, shot the headmaster in a stairwell
and then turned the handgun on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they believe the boy was seeking revenge for the
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   His father, a 43-year-old businessman whose hobby was shooting,
had a license to own guns that did not cover the machine guns or
assault rifle. Neither the father's name, nor those of the
headmaster or student, were released.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at separate hospitals treating the 57-year-old
headmaster and student said Friday they both remained in critical
and life-threatening condition.
</P>
<P>
   The student had been expelled Wednesday from the boarding school
near the Austrian border because of his ''rebellious behavior'' and
sent home.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, he came back to the school with two
large-caliber guns and 100 rounds of ammunition, police said. When
he met the headmaster in a stairwell, he shot him in the neck, then
fired several shots at his own head.
</P>
<P>
   The headmaster, who had also taught the boy's computer science
class, had received the results of a drug tests earlier that day,
which police said showed the student had been using marijuana. He
was to have been expelled from the school he had attended for 2{
years.
</P>
<P>
   The other 94 students, who range in age from 12 to 18 and come
from across Germany to study at the coed school, were returned home
after the shooting and the school building remained closed Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
