<HEADLINE> Koehler: IMF Should Focus on Crises  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Germany's Horst Koehler, poised to take the
helm of the International Monetary Fund, said Friday the
organization must emphasize preventing future financial crises by
monitoring countries' economies more closely.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler also said he was ready for discussions with
congressional and other critics who say the IMF has become too
expensive, powerful and secretive and want to scale down its
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The 182-nation, Washington-based organization has become one of
the world's most important financial institutions, bailing out
economies in the late 1990s as economic turmoil swept the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, 57, the head of the European Bank for Reconstruction
and Development, said he expected the IMF's 24 executive directors
to formally select him as president next week after the withdrawal
of Japanese and American candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I sense that there is broad support emerging from shareholders
but a decision still has to be made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   An overwhelming majority of the IMF's members have signaled they
will back Koehler as the first German to head the agency since it
was established after World War II. But he will take office
weakened after a bruising five-month struggle to select a successor
to Frenchman Michel Camdessus, who stepped down as head of the IMF
in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union endorsed his candidacy Monday and his
accession became a foregone conclusion when the Clinton
administration endorsed him hours later after rejecting Germany's
first candidate as unqualified. Under an unwritten agreement, a
European has traditionally headed the IMF and an American has
headed the World Bank, its sister institution.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a red security badge marked ''visitor,'' Koehler held
his first news conference at IMF headquarters and said he felt ''it
is now more important for me to listen carefully before making any
specific statements on the role of the fund, listen to IMF
shareholders, to its staff but also to outside experts.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in the future, he said, the IMF should ''focus even
more on crisis prevention and we should make the best use of the
strength of this institution'' by providing countries with good
advice on sound economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if recent evidence of Russian attempts to mislead the IMF
over central bank activities indicated the IMF needed to change its
approach, Koehler said ''what happened in Russia ... reveals the
need to be more careful'' in future lending.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler said he was ''open to discussion and dialogue with the
U.S. congress about reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would hold similar talks with nongovernmental
organizations such as development and environmental groups because
''there is an obligation to explain'' IMF policies. Some of these
groups have threatened to disrupt the meetings next month of the
IMF and the World Bank. Koehler said he did not know if he would be
in office in time for these meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler agreed the selection process to choose a new IMF leader
''was not the best and should be reviewed and improved.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he looked forward to working closely with Stanley
Fischer, the American who filled in as acting director after
Camdessus left. He said he expected Fischer, who played a leading
role in resolving recent financial crises, to remain at IMF as No.
2 for some time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
