<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Markets Likely To Remain Volatile  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Now that blue-chip stocks have burst out of a
months-long slump, Wall Street analysts are wondering whether the
market's surge is the sign of a turnaround or just another volatile
swing in a volatile year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, the best-known barometer of the U.S. stock market, rose
a record 499.19 points Thursday, adding to a 320-point gain in the
previous session. With those two sessions, the blue-chip index
wiped out more than 40 percent of its losses over the last two
months. It also finished a week of the biggest point gain in
history and the steepest weekly percentage rise in almost 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Activity was choppy today as some traders sold shares to cash in
on the remarkable runup. Volume was slightly behind Thursday's
record-shattering pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow gryated in a relatively narrow range through much of the
day and closed down 35.37 at 10,595.23. Even with the slip Friday,
the rise of 666.41 points for the week was the greatest weekly gain
ever, surpassing the 586.68 points that had been the record since
the week ended July 2, 1999. The 6.71 percent rise in the Dow this
week was the most since a 7.85 percent of the week ended Aug. 2,
1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index gained 80.74 at 4,798.13.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq broke out of a three-day slump Thursday to finish up
134.77 points.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's gains were breathtaking, to be sure. But will the
newfound strength stick?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's too soon to tell whether this is anything more than a
short-term head fake,'' said David G. Sowerby, vice president at
Loomis, Sayles &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The market's gyrations this week have come amid extraordinarily
high volume. On Thursday, a record 1.48 billion shares changed
hands on the New York Stock Exchange as of the 4 p.m. EST closing
bell, surpassing the previous high of 1.35 billion set on Dec. 17,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, where volume typically exceeds that of the NYSE,
2.04 billion shares were traded. That made for a busy day, but fell
short of the record of 2.23 billion set March 1.
</P>
<P>
   With so many shares changing hands, it's become increasingly
common for market indexes to pitch violently throughout a session.
Years ago, a day in which the Dow moved up or down more than 100
points was considered remarkable. In the 52 trading days since Jan.
1, the Dow has subjected traders to 27 doses of triple-digit moves
either up or down.
</P>
<P>
   ''At these levels, you're going to get shakeouts from time to
time,'' Sowerby said.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just volatility that makes analysts question the
staying power of the market's gains. Most market watchers believe
the blue-chip stocks of the Dow were due for a rally, and the
technology stocks that dominate the Nasdaq were ready for a bout of
profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   But the factors that drove the U.S. stock market into its
bipolar state are still firmly in place.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among them: worries that burgeoning signs of inflation
will force the Federal Reserve to continue raising interest rates,
threatening corporate profits. Thursday's rally surprised some on
Wall Street because it came on a day when the government delivered
mixed news on inflation. There was more of the same today.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported this morning that consumer prices
shot up 0.5 percent in February, the biggest jump in 10 months, and
a slightly steeper gain than analysts had forecast. But excluding
the volatile energy and food categories, the ''core'' rate of
inflation rose a mild 0.2 percent in February, right on target with
many analysts expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ''As-expected data will encourage the markets,'' said Scott J.
Brown, chief economist at Raymond James &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported Thursday that its Producer Price Index
showed that wholesale prices surged 1 percent in February, the
largest gain in nearly 10 years, as gasoline, home heating oil and
other energy costs rose. But the core rate was up a more moderate
0.3 percent, also in line with forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts consider the CPI a more significant barometer of
inflation, because it measures price pressures at the consumer
level.
</P>
<P>
   The PPI and the CPI were critical to investor sentiment this
week because they were the last major economic reports to be
released before the Fed's meeting next Tuesday. In a continuing
effort to keep inflation at bay, the Fed has raised rates four
times since last June, and many investors are expecting a fifth
rate hike on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rising rates have been largely responsible for the market's
split, and an increase on Tuesday could send blue-chip and
technology stocks back on their divergent paths, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, the old economy companies will be affected first if
rates go up,'' said Vernon Winters, chief investment officer at
Mellon Private Asset Management. ''They have borrowing costs that
technology companies just don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks, which get most of their funding from venture
capitalists and from selling their coveted shares, have risen on
the belief that they will best survive higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   But many Wall Street analysts aren't yet convinced of that
argument. Winters, for one, believes technology stocks remain
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had a moonshot in technology stocks,'' said Winters.
''Now they're feeling some of the gravitational pull of the
Earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1738 </TRAILER>
