<HEADLINE> US Braces for China-Taiwan Tensions  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Taiwanese voters prepared to elect a new
president, Clinton administration officials and congressional
leaders braced for a possible escalation of tensions if the
pro-independence candidate wins Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While senior officials generally remained guarded in their
comments, one said a victory by presidential hopeful Chen Shui-bian
of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party would ''yield
potentially the greatest reaction from China.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment referred to China's warnings that any move by Taiwan
toward independence could lead to military action against the
island.
</P>
<P>
   The official declined to talk about U.S. military preparations.
On Capitol Hill, a spokesman for Senate Foreign Relations Committee
chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., noted that Helms asked the Pentagon
two weeks ago to provide him with a personal briefing on defense
plans for Taiwan if China were to do ''something stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, on the eve of the last Taiwanese elections, the
United States dispatched two aircraft carriers and other warships
to the region after China lobbed nuclear-capable missiles near the
island's two major ports.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, seeking to avoid pre-election controversy,
reiterated that the United States wants to see a resumption of the
cross-strait dialogue as soon as the election is over.
</P>
<P>
   Don Oberdorfer, of the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced
International Studies, expressed concern Friday that Chinese
belligerency could sour post-election prospects for a productive
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this foundation of bad blood, the dialogue may not get
very far,'' he said. ''If the Chinese feel Taiwan is slipping away,
then we could be in for very serious problems.'' He called the
Chinese threats ''disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration has steered away from expressing a preference
for any of the Taiwanese candidates in what is believed to be a
close race for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't support or oppose any candidate,'' State Department
spokesman James P. Rubin said. ''We support the democratic process
on Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Thiessen, a spokesman for Helms, said, ''We'll be
comfortable with the any of the three candidates. It's a decision
entirely and exclusively for the people of Taiwan to make. They
don't need our advice and they don't need Beijing's.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most outspoken pro-Taiwan voice on Capitol Hill has
been that House Republican Whip Tom DeLay, of Texas. In a speech
Thursday, DeLay said the Clinton administration has embraced ''a
level of appeasement'' toward China more craven than Neville
Chamberlain's attempts to placate Germany on the eve of World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, DeLay spokesman Jonathan Baron said DeLay is hopeful
that ''communist China will set a new course and react to the
results of this weekend's elections with restraint and good sense.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has said he believes the U.S. cannot under any
circumstances allow the People's Republic of China to impose a
communist future on Taiwan,'' Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   State Department:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/eap/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Library of Congress: http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/cshome.html
</P>
</TEXT>
