<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian, Europe Stock Markets Rally  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Wall Street settled down with a mixed
performance today, with the Dow industrials unable to build on its
stunning gains, as some traders took profits from two days of
remarkable advances. Even with a setback in the Dow, the stock
market's best-known indicator had its best weekly point rise ever
and its biggest percentage gain in nearly 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which surged nearly 500 points
Thursday in a record-shattering rebound, fell 35.37 to close at
10,595.23 in heavy trading. It spent much of the day swinging back
and forth in a relatively narrow range.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, the Dow's 666.41 point gain was the biggest point
rise in history, and the 6.71 percent increase was the largest
percentage gain since the week ended Aug. 3, 1984, when it rose
7.85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-focused Nasdaq composite index, which was lifted
by the Dow on Thursday, was up an additional 80.74 at 4,798.13.
</P>
<P>
   Asian markets, which closed today's sessions before Wall Street
returned to work, rallied on the heels of Thursday's stunning
gains. Stocks closed also closed higher in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Dow soared 499.19 points, or 4.9 percent, on
top of Wednesday's 320-point rally. Thursday's unprecedented rise
easily beat the record for the sharpest one-day Dow point rise ever
-- 380.53 -- which was set Sept. 8, 1998. But it was nowhere near the
record 15.34 percent jump on March 15, 1933.
</P>
<P>
   Among the unsettling factors is that today is a ''triple
witching'' day on Wall Street, a quarterly event that occurs when
contracts on stock options, index options, and index futures all
expire. Trading to settle such contracts often contributes to
market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. markets also have been jittery about prospects that the
strong American economy and tight labor market would rekindle
inflation, prompting the Federal Reserve to be even more aggressive
in raising interest rates. The Fed has raised rates four times
since June and meets again Tuesday, when it is expected to increase
rates a fifth time.
</P>
<P>
   A Labor Department report today provided mixed signals but
seemed to calm traders' fears that central bankers would raise
rates by more than a quarter point. Yields on 30-year Treasury
bonds today were flirting with a drop below 6 percent for the first
time in almost six months.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported a 0.5 percent increase in consumer
prices in February, the biggest jump in 10 months. But after
excluding the volatile energy and food categories, the ''core''
rate of inflation rose a mild 0.2 percent in February, which was in
line with many analysts expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported Thursday that its Producer Price Index
showed that wholesale prices surged 1 percent in February, the
largest gain in nearly 10 years. But the core rate was up a more
moderate 0.3 percent, also in line with forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Major European markets also rose modestly. In London, Europe's
largest market, the FTSE-100 closed up by less than 1 point,
Germany's benchmark DAX index was up 1.7 percent and the Paris CAC
40 index was 0.7 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's top three stock markets rose sharply.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the world's second-largest economy, stocks roared
ahead at the opening and remained high all day, due in part to the
Dow's surge Thursday. The Nikkei 225 Stock Average closed up 1.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Traders also were encouraged by a new government report giving
an upward assessment of the Japanese economy, which recently
slipped back into a recession. The report said parts of the
economy, including corporate capital investment and personal
consumption, were on a sounder footing.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index jumped 4.4.
</P>
<P>
   Traders credited Wall Street's record showing, but also said
they were relieved by the fact that China's military hasn't
attacked Taiwan in advance a national election Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Taiwan and mainland China have been governed separately
since splitting amid civil war 51 years ago, China views Taiwan as
a renegade province and is demanding quick progress in
reunification talks by the two governments. The outcome of
Saturday's vote for the three top candidates could conceivably
spark a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In Singapore, the Straits Times Index opened sharply higher
today and ended the day with a gain of 3.6 percent from Wednesday.
The market was closed Thursday for a holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1740 </TRAILER>
