<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Deports Red Army Members  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH PANOSSIAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Four members of the Japanese Red Army, a
shadowy ultra-leftist group accused of terrorist attacks in the
1970s, were reportedly on their way back to Japan Friday after
Lebanon denied them asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon had refused to extradite the three men and a woman to
Japan, so it deported them on a flight to Jordan. But once in
Amman, they were handed over to Japanese diplomats who took them on
a private plane back to Japan, diplomats in Amman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Amman-based diplomats spoke on condition they not be
identified further, and Japanese Embassy officials in Amman refused
to confirm or deny the information.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's official Petra news agency confirmed that the kingdom
''refused to allow entry to the four elements of the Japanese Red
Army.'' The report said they ''went to another side,'' but it did
not specify where they went.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth Red Army member -- Kozo Okamoto, who participated in the
1972 killing of 24 people in Israel -- was granted asylum in Lebanon
due to health reasons, a government statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's events were the latest development in Japan's longtime
attempt to get Lebanon to extradite the Red Army members.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government wants the five to stand trial in Japan
on charges of staging bloody attacks around the world. But Lebanon
has cited the lack of an extradition treaty between the two
countries and said the Japanese government does not have evidence
confirming its accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Okamoto, 51, is the best known of the five: He was involved in
the 1972 attack on Israel's Ben Gurion airport that left 24 people
dead. He was freed by Israel in a 1985 prisoner swap with
Palestinian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese statement said Okamoto was granted asylum because
he is still suffering ''from physical and psychological injuries
that he sustained while in Israeli prisons.'' It said the committee
considering the asylum requests had found that Okamoto was the only
one of the five who actually participated in ''resistance
operations'' against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   A prison official who would speak only on condition of anonymity
said Okamoto would remain at Roumyieh prison east of Beirut until a
place in Lebanon is found for him if he should choose to stay.
</P>
<P>
   The other Red Army members are Masao Adachi, 59; Kazuo Tohira,
46; Haruwo Wako, 50; and Mariko Yamamoto, 58. Last week, they and
Okamoto finished three-year prison terms for illegally entering
Lebanon, but they had remained in custody pending asylum decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Army members are considered heroes by many in Lebanon
and the Arab world for championing the Palestinian cause and
opposing Israel, which occupies a border zone in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lebanese capital, about 50 supporters of the Japanese
five protested outside Prime Minister Salim Hoss's Beirut residence
and clashed with riot police Friday night, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   At least four demonstrators were injured, and security forces
beat at least two journalists. They confiscated news photographers'
film of the clash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
