<HEADLINE> Soybean, Corn Prices Soar  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fears that top U.S. farm crops will be hurt by drought this year
intensified Friday after new forecasts called for dry weather in
the Midwest through spring, sending soybean and corn futures
soaring on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, gold sank to a seven-week low and cocoa fell.
</P>
<P>
   The latest drought fears emerged at the beginning of the week
when the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration warned
that the central United States faces a serious drought threat
because of a critical lack of soil moisture, with no relief in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   It said Nebraska, Iowa, Illinois and Indiana -- the top four
soybean-producing states and leaders in corn as well -- comprise the
driest area, prompting a strong runup in prices for the first half
of the week.
</P>
<P>
   When the National Weather Service reported after markets closed
Thursday that the outlook for the next 30 to 90 days is for
above-average temperatures and below-average precipitation, that
revived and accelerated the rally on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans, the leading U.S. crop, leaped to a 14-month high.
Corn, the No. 2 crop, reached a seven-month high.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government is beating the drought drum louder and
louder,'' said Tim Hannagan, head grains analyst for Alaron Trading
Corp. in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   While there's still plenty of time for rains to replenish soil
moisture -- corn planting is still about four weeks away and soybean
planting is six weeks off -- corn prices surged 6 percent for the
week and soybean prices rose 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, soybeans for May delivery rose 12 cents to $5.37{ a
bushel; May corn rose 5{ cents to $2.40} a bushel; May wheat rose 6
cents to $2.72\ a bushel; May oats rose 1{ cent to $1.22 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increase, Hannagan said there's plenty of room for
prices to rise if a comparison with the last big drought year,
1988, is a reliable guideline. Mid-March prices that year were more
than $1 higher than they are now for soybeans and 40 to 50 cents
higher for corn, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure there's much more volatility to come,'' he said.
''We're going to have rain, and when you get a rain period coming
in you can expect some sharp breaks'' in the rally.
</P>
<P>
   But, ''it looks like we're still pretty cheap,'' the analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gold prices fell again on the Comex division of the New York
Mercantile Exchange as traders positioned themselves ahead of the
last of five scheduled United Kingdom gold sales.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors believe the price will sink as a result of
Tuesday's auction by the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
   April gold settled down $2 at $285 per troy ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Cocoa reversed course from the seasonal rally that followed the
conclusion of big West African harvests, giving back all of
Thursday's big gains. Market-watchers called it a correction to an
overdone buying splurge the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   May cocoa fell $37 to $898 a ton on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP;
Cocoa Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
