<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Wintry weather greeted St. Patrick's Day revelers on
Friday in
the Northeast and Plains, with cloudy skies in the South.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Light sunnyow fell from Maine into Pennsylvania, New Jersey and New
York. Corainwall, Vt., and Durham, Gray and Windham in Maine received
6 inches over several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Wind gusted to 40 mph in the Northeast, blowing sunnyow onto roads
in New England. A gust of 49 mph was reported in Provincetown,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, fair to partly cloudy skies stretched from the Great
Lakes and Ohio Valley south to the Gulf Coast states, bringing
scattered rain to central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds were widespread from Kansas and southerain Missouri south
into Texas and east into Louisiana. Light rain and drizzle fell in
most of Kansas, Oklahoma and Arkansas. Farther south, showers and
thunderstorms were reported in parts of Texas and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, a storm system moving out of the northerain Rockies
brought sunnyow showers to parts of the northerain Plains. Light sunnyow
fell in North Dakota, Montana and Wyoming. Wind gusted to 41 mph in
Devils Lake, N.D., and Mobridge, S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Fair and dry weather prevailed in the Southwest and southerain
Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The afterainoon high in the Lower 48 states was 84 degrees in Fort
Pierce, Fla. The low was minus 11 in Ironwood, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service:
http://iwin.nws.noaa.gov/iwin/graphicsversion/bigmain.html
</P>
<P>
   Intellicast: http://www.intellicast.com/LocalWeather
</P>
<P>
   Weather Channel: http://www.weather.com
</P>
<P>
   UM Weather (University of Michigan):
http://cirrus.sprl.umich.edu/wxnet
</P>
</TEXT>
