<HEADLINE> World Mayors Plan Summit in Athens  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE CHAVRANSKI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Agreeing to work toward safety, social harmony and
respect for nature, more than 30 mayors from around the world
pledged Friday to make this week's inaugural summit a tradition and
planned a second gathering in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day Summit of World Mayors, which ended Friday,
illustrated ''a new model of cooperation -- modern, pragmatic and
adapted to the growing complexity of the world,'' Paris Mayor Jean
Tiberi said in a closing address.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting at the mayoral level provides a ''new breath in the
links of friendship among nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quality of city life in the new millennium was the theme of this
week's summit, which brought together 33 mayors from five
continents to exchange views on running cities from Phnom Penh and
Johannesburg to Tunis and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   In a ''Declaration de Paris,'' the mayors agreed to work toward
safety, integration, social harmony and respect for history and
nature.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed to hold a second summit in two years in Athens,
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   As Tiberi hosted the international delegates, a political crisis
closed in on him at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Accused of padding party membership rolls while head of a local
branch of President Jacques Chirac's conservative Rally for the
Republic party, Tiberi was suspended from his party functions on
Wednesday, drastically reducing his chances in municipal elections
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no intention of ceding,'' Tiberi said, calling the
accusations against him ''odious lies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
