<HEADLINE> Bakery strike continues for second full day on Friday, reachesN.J.  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS GOSIER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- A strike that shut down Interstate
Bakeries Corp.'s New England operations continued for a second full
day on Friday and even reached down the East Coast to shut down one
of the company's bakeries in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   As about 1,400 Teamsters continued to stop the shipment of bread
and other baked goods, 400 members of a bakers' union stopped
working Thursday evening at the Drake's bakery in Wayne, N.J., said
Mark Dirkes, the company's senior vice president for marketing in
Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey workers returned to their jobs on Friday, but the
plant remained shut down because its drivers belonging to the
Teamsters union refused to distribute the product.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters blamed Interstate Bakeries for the strike, saying
the company refused to honor arbitration rulings on issues
including an unfair labor complaint. Company officials who contend
they were shut out of the arbitration process have asked a judge to
rule on whether the arbitration was valid.
</P>
<P>
   The pickets continued despite heavy snow Friday morning outside
the J.J. Nissen baking plant in Biddeford, site of the company's
only bakery serving its customers in New England.
</P>
<P>
   The transport drivers, sales representatives, shippers and
receivers left their jobs Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 Teamsters were based in Biddeford, while the rest
distributed the baked goods throughout New England, said Bill
Turkewitz, a representative of Teamsters local 340 in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The Biddeford bakery was shut down after about 500 bakery union
members refused to cross the Teamsters picket line. The plant makes
J.J. Nissen, Wonder Bread, Hostess and Drake's products.
</P>
<P>
   One of New England's largest supermarket chains stepped up its
orders from other suppliers to make up for the products that were
no longer coming from the Biddeford plant. The Hannaford Bros.
grocery chain still had plenty of bread supplies Friday,
spokeswoman Caren Epstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Customers should see no shortage unless they are looking for a
particular Nissen's product,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between the company and the union broke down
Thursday afternoon, and Dirkes said Friday that he was not aware of
any negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters held out the threat of expanding the strike to
thousands of other union drivers across the country. But Teamsters
officials responsible for the decision could not be reached Friday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Teamsters represent 130,000 drivers in its bakery
division, which includes Interstate Bakeries and other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials maintained Friday that the company had plenty of
opportunity to participate in the arbitration hearings at the
center of the dispute and that the company is required to live by
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you get to an arbitrator, those decision are final and
binding. We all know that,'' said Robert Piccone, a Teamsters
representative in South Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   One decision stemmed from a union complaint that the company was
placing all four its brands on the same trucks. Drivers are
supposed to carry only one brand at a time because each brand has a
different pay scales, the union says.
</P>
<P>
   Union workers also were upset because a fired driver was not
allowed to return to his job despite an arbitrator's ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-17-00 1752 </TRAILER>
