<HEADLINE> Crude Prices Drift Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Crude prices dipped below $31 a barrel as
sentiment toward lower oil prices continued to prevail on the New
York Mercantile Exchange. Other energy futures fell as well.
</P>
<P>
   Since hitting a high of $34.20 on March 7, crude prices have
drifted lower amid pledges of an increase in oil production by OPEC
and non-OPEC countries later this year.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Friday, President Clinton said he had talked with
Saudi Arabia's King Fahd about the need to stabilize oil prices at
levels that satisfy both producing and consuming nations. Saudi
Arabia already has said it favors increasing production.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everybody's struggling now to find a consensus,''
Clinton told reporters when asked about the high oil and gasoline
prices during a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
   West Texas Intermediate crude for April delivery fell 18 cents
to $30.91 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   In other energy prices, April heating oil fell .31 cent to 71.72
cents a gallon, April unleaded gasoline fell .55 cent to 93.43
cents a gallon and April natural gas fell .66 cent to $2.785 per
1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, May Brent crude from the North Sea fell 22 cents to
$26.56 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
