<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Irish Leaders Hold Talks  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GALVIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton welcomed a parade of
Northern Ireland's quarreling leaders to the White House, hoping to
use the cheer of St. Patrick's Day to nudge them toward compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he urged them to avert a return to violence,
politicians on both sides of Northern Ireland's sectarian divide
remained skeptical Friday about chances for a quick end to the
stalemate over the Irish Republican Army's weapons and Britain's
decision to shutter the coalition government established under the
1998 Good Friday Accord.
</P>
<P>
   ''The good news about Ireland is that even though the
institutions have been taken down over the difference between the
parties on decommissioning, no-one wants to go back to the way it
was or give up the peace process,'' Clinton said. ''We need to
restore a process that will eventually lead to all the requirements
of the Good Friday Accord being observed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton welcomed Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, who started
the St. Patrick's Day ceremonies at the White House by presenting
Clinton with a crystal bowl brimming with shamrocks.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern said that he believes all parties remain committed to
peace, but ''It is not easy things that we're asking anybody to
resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks easy on paper,'' he said. ''But the fact is that
there are huge, deeply held fears and mistrust. Confidence has to
be restored.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also met with David Trimble, leader of the main
Protestant party the Ulster Unionists; Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams;
John Hume, leader of the moderate Roman Catholic Social Democratic
and Labor Party, who shared a Nobel Peace Prize with Trimble; and
Seamus Mallon, Hume's deputy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials cautioned against expecting breakthroughs.
Arriving at the White House, Trimble said his party has not ruled
out rejoining the government, but he demanded concrete evidence the
IRA will begin decommissioning weapons, or disarming.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did it last time on the basis of an expectation which had
been encouraged by Sinn Fein,'' he said. ''If we do it again, then
it has to be against a background of absolute certainty that this
time they will decommission within an appreciable period of time of
the formation of the executive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein's Adams blamed the British government for the impasse,
arguing it exceeded its authority in suspending a government that
voters in Ireland and Northern Ireland had approved.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one, and the British government especially, should be
vetoing what the people have voted for,'' Adams told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Adams conceded that the ''guns issue'' had to be dealt with, but
he countered Trimble's suggestion that the arms problem be solved
before the government can go back to work. He appealed to
Irish-Americans not to lose hope in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Keep your eyes on the prize,'' he said. ''The only way the
reactionaries, the only way the 'No' men ... will win is if the
rest of us give up. And Sinn Fein isn't giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern said resolving the situation before Easter will require
''a determination by all the parties to implement the Good Friday
agreements in full, to stop talking about reviews or amendments,
just concentrate about what's already on paper.''
</P>
<P>
   The British government's decision on Feb. 11 to close down the
coalition government in Northern Ireland came after Trimble
threatened to withdraw his party because the IRA had not begun
disarming.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Sinn Fein, the political ally of the mainly Catholic
IRA, noted that May 22 is the deadline for disarmament of both the
IRA and outlawed pro-British groups under the Good Friday agreement
overseen by former Sen. George Mitchell of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has not definitively said whether it will disarm. Sinn
Fein, eager to regain its two posts within the suspended 12-member
administration, says the IRA eventually may disarm, but only if
unionists allow the four-party coalition to work without
obstruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
