<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Lash Out in Education Ads  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the first ad salvos of the general
election, George W. Bush is going after Al Gore on education and
Gore is hitting back at Bush for opening with a negative tone.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after the two clinched their parties' nominations,
Bush was out first with his spot, which is filled with smiling
children but a razor-sharp message: ''Clinton and Gore had eight
years, but they've failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, the vice president responded with an ad of his
own: ''On the issue of education, America deserves a real debate,
not more negative ads from George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither campaign is spending much money on their opening ad
buys, but they signal an early start to what is sure to be a
vigorous tit-for-tat over the airways.
</P>
<P>
   Each ad makes selective use of education statistics, which can
be sliced in a myriad ways to prove a point. The Bush ad highlights
the worst of the national statistics. The Gore ad finds the worst
numbers out of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign is spending less than $100,000 to air its
60-second ad in six Illinois media markets, some of which reach
into neighboring battleground states of Missouri, Kentucky and
Iowa. Friday afternoon, the Gore campaign said it would air its
spot, also 60 seconds, in the same markets and would spend about
the same amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   With limited dollars remaining for the four months before the
party conventions, Gore had hoped to hold off for a while before
beginning TV advertising. But when Bush prepared to go on the air,
Gore advisers decided they had to respond immediately. They said
their ad might be up as early as Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   So while it's just nearing springtime on the calendar, the fall
campaign appears to be under way.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly eight months before Nov. 7, ''the general election has
begun,'' said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the University of
Pennsylvania's Annenberg School of Communication, who studies
political ads.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are running in markets across Illinois, with the notable
exception of the expensive Chicago market. Illinois holds its
primary election on Tuesday, though the ads are clearly intended as
early groundwork for the fall. They will air in Champaign, Peoria,
Rockford, Quincy, Harrisburg and Davenport, Iowa, which is on the
Illinois border. Quincy also reaches into Iowa, and Harrisburg
reaches Kentucky and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're able to reach four key swing states for the fall
election,'' said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore ad opens with what has become a familiar charge: that
the other side went negative first. It then proceeds to criticize
Bush's Texas record, much in the same way that the Bush ad
criticizes the national record.
</P>
<P>
   ''George W. Bush -- from South Carolina to New York he used dirty
politics to trash John McCain's record. Now he's running attack ads
against Al Gore,'' the Gore ad says.
</P>
<P>
   Education consistently ranks at the top of voter concerns,
particularly among women, whose votes could be decisive in the
fall. Since he wrapped up the nomination, Bush has been focusing
tightly on education, making it a daily theme. On Thursday, for
instance, he held an education forum at a school in Springfield,
Ill.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll out Friday shows Bush and Gore neck and neck with
voters on the issue of education, though other polls show Gore with
an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's education plan would remove many of the federal
regulations that govern the spending of education money. To keep
the money that aids the poorest children, schools would have to
show they are making improvements. Otherwise, the federal
government would give the cash directly to parents, who could use
it to send their kids to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed a massive new federal investment -- $115
billion over the next ten years, to be paid for out of the
projected budget surplus -- to triple the number of charter schools,
provide universal access to kindergarten, modernize old schools and
construct new ones, recruit new teachers, and give raises to
high-performing instructors.
</P>
<P>
   In his ad, Bush charges that under the Clinton-Gore
administration, national reading scores ''stagnated.'' But it
doesn't mention that they had been dropping through the 1980s.
Staying the same in the 1990s was arguably an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   And Jamieson noted that Texas scores followed the national
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's attacking Gore in an area in which he didn't make an
improvement in Texas,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1819 </TRAILER>
