<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Closes Down 35.37  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An across-the-board surge in technology stocks
couldn't prevent a modest selloff among large old-line companies
Friday as the Dow industrials faltered after two days of stunning
gains. Even with the mild setback, the Dow still had its biggest
weekly point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   Market analysts said mild profit-taking Friday in the wake of
Thursday's record-setting 499.19-point gain sent Wall Street's
best-known indicator slipping late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average pulled back from an earlier
surge and fell 35.37 to 10,595.23.
</P>
<P>
   But the benchmark index still ended the week with a gain of
666.41 points, the biggest weekly runup ever for the Dow,
surpassing the previous record of 586.68 set the week ended July 2,
1999. The 6.71 percent rise for the week was the biggest since the
7.85 percent in the week ended Aug. 3, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's bold advance this week, which included a 320-point
surge Wednesday, wiped out more than 40 percent of the average's
losses over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   ''We saw some profit-taking in some selective areas,
specifically the drug sector. But it wasn't a wholesale selloff,''
said Paul McEnroe, a trader at Brown Brothers Harriman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, judging from the recent market volatility, it's
anybody's guess where we go from here,'' McEnroe added.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were higher Friday. The Nasdaq
composite index closed up 80.74 at 4,798.13. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 6.00 at 1,464.47.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were higher on both the Nasdaq and the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ''The techs are rocking and rolling and the overall market is
acting very well given the recent runups. The Dow rose 800 points
in two days and it's still moving higher,'' said Alfred Goldman,
director of market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said the uniform gains among tech stocks was surprising
since today was a ''triple witching'' day on Wall Street, a
quarterly event that occurs when contracts on stock options, index
options, and index futures all expire. Trading to settle such
contracts often contributes to market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, advancers included Applied Materials, up 7 59/64
at 95 55/64, and Sun Microsystems, up 5] at 96[. On the NYSE,
Nortel Networks rose 8\ to 128, and America Online jumped 3 3/16 to
64 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Old-line stocks that make up the majority of the Dow Jones
average fell out of favor late Friday. They included drug companies
Merck, down 2\ at 62}, and Eli Lilly, down 3 5/16 at 61 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Large brokerage firms, meanwhile, shrugged off the volatility
and were up across the board. Charles Schwab rose 5 9/16 to 55
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   New inflationary pressure was also a consideration Friday.
Consumer prices rose 0.5 percent in February, the biggest jump in
10 months, led by a record increase in fuel oil prices and sharply
higher gasoline costs, the Labor Department reported. But excluding
the volatile energy and food categories, the ''core'' inflation
rate was a moderate 0.2 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   The figures appeared to cheer markets because they showed no
signs of a steep resurgence in inflation, something that would lead
the Federal Reserve to push up interest rates sharply. The Fed,
however, is widely expected to raise rates one-quarter point at a
meeting Tuesday, marking a fifth increase since June.
</P>
<P>
   In the inflation-sensitive market for government bonds, yields
on 30-year Treasury securities flirted with a dip below 6 percent
for the first time in nearly six months.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-7 margin on
the NYSE, where volume totaled 1.29 billion shares as of 4 p.m.
EST, down slightly from a record 1.48 billion in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.54 to 574.78.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.6 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index rose 1.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
rose 0.01 percent, and France's CAC-40 gained 0.7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
