<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush Lead Shrinking Among Men  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has seen his huge lead among
male voters cut in half by Al Gore, largely on the strength of
increased confidence in Gore's skills with the economy, a
bipartisan poll suggests. The two are running close among women
voters -- a cause of concern for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a time when Al Gore was doing so poorly among men,
one wondered if women could make up for it,'' said Celinda Lake, a
Democratic pollster who conducted the Voter.com-Battleground Poll
with Republican Ed Goeas. ''Now he's only 12 points behind among
men.
</P>
<P>
   The poll released Friday showed Bush with a 48 percent to 44
percent edge over Gore in the presidential race, down from a
13-point Bush lead in the same poll in January.
</P>
<P>
   The margin did not change substantially when poll respondents
were presented with a choice that paired Arizona Sen. John McCain
with Bush and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley with Gore. But
the data indicated McCain's presence could make a big difference in
competitive congressional races, and Goeas suggested McCain could
be a very valuable campaigner for candidates in those districts.
</P>
<P>
   Both pollsters noted Gore has improved his standing with the
public in many areas in the past two months, while Bush has slipped
to make the race very close.
</P>
<P>
   ''From a Republican perspective, the fact that Bush is even or
leading is something of a surprise and we'll take it,'' said Goeas.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who has focused his campaign heavily on his
economic role in the Clinton administration, is getting more credit
for his abilities on that issue. The candidates now are rated about
evenly on their ability to ''keep America prosperous.'' And that
played a role in cutting the margin that Bush, the governor of
Texas, held as recently as January, the poll indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed advantages for Republican Bush in voters'
concerns about the nation's moral climate. But a little anxiety
actually could help Gore, suggested Democrat Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ''When voters are a little jittery, they are less likely to jump
ship,'' she said. ''If things were to take a more negative turn,
then obviously that would be bad for the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had a 22-point advantage over Bush among poll respondents
on the question of experience, while Bush led on the question of
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has an advantage among Hispanics, a group that generally
identifies more with the Democratic Party. And Democrats need to
establish their traditional advantage among women voters to fare
well in November, Lake said.
</P>
<P>
   The new poll showed Gore with 48 percent support compared with
43 percent for Bush among women, a bit better for Gore than in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very identifiable problem,'' Lake said of Gore's
failure to open a wider lead among a group that is usually
Democratic-leaning. ''It's moms who are values-oriented and give
Bush credit on education.
</P>
<P>
   ''George W. Bush runs some education ads that would make most
Democrats weep,'' she said, noting ads that call for ''education
for every child in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If women were as enthusiastic for Al Gore as men are for
George W. Bush, Al Gore would be ahead,'' Lake said. ''A clear
factor in the race is the gender gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush led among men, 52 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll indicated Bush and Gore are about even in the public
view on many issues and candidate qualities, and the 2000
presidential election is likely to be ''one of the most competitive
in history,'' said Goeas.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that 56 percent of American voters said they were
conservative. The poll did not offer the category of moderate,
forcing people to choose between various degrees of liberal or
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of surveyed Americans described Gore as at least
somewhat liberal and seven of 10 described Bush as at least
somewhat conservative, suggesting to Goeas that ''Gore has some
work to do to get in line with the right-of-center American
electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority of likely voters have a favorable view of Gore, 52
percent, and slightly more have a positive view of Bush, 58 percent
in the telephone poll of 1,000 likely voters taken Sunday and
Monday. The poll had an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   When likely voters were asked which one issue was the most
important for the president to deal with, one in five chose
restoring moral values. Bush usually fares well in the polls on
that issue. Other top issues were improving education,
strengthening Social Security and improving health care. Gore leads
on the issues of Social Security and health care, while the two
were closely matched on education.
</P>
</TEXT>
