<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phone, Web Competition Rules Upheld  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An appeals court Friday largely preserved new
federal rules meant to open local phone markets to competition.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, however, found some parts of the Federal
Communications Commission regulations implemented last spring are
too broad. The rules generally were intended to make it easier for
upstart local phone companies to install equipment at facilities
belonging to the major players in the local markets -- the Baby
Bells and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   The rules were also meant to help newer companies that want to
provide both traditional local phone service as well as high-speed
Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia by and
large backed the FCC's rules. But the court found parts impart
overly broad authority to the newer entrants.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, the court challenged the commission's interpretation of
a statute that says major phone companies had to make room for
whatever equipment rival companies believe is necessary to get
access to the local phone network from the facility.
</P>
<P>
   In its rulemaking, the FCC explained this to mean any equipment
that is ''used or useful'' for connection to the phone network --
even if that equipment might have other completely unrelated
functions.
</P>
<P>
   GTE Corp. and other companies that had challenged the
commission's rules argued that this could open the door for
competitors to put in equipment beyond what is required, trampling
on the rights of the big carriers. The court said this view had
merit and sent that part of the rule back to the FCC for
clarification.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney associated with the petitioners hailed this part of
the court's decision as a victory, saying that it will prevent the
big carriers from losing control over their buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The petitioners had also protested the commission's decision
last spring to allow competing companies the option of being able
to rent a tiny amount of space at the facility of major local phone
companies, rather than being forced to rent a 10-foot by 10-foot
fenced enclosure, which can be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   On that point, the court said the petitioner's arguments went
too far and that the commission has the authority to order such
space-sharing. But the three judge panel did say that the FCC had
not demonstrated why the competing company -- rather than the major
local phone provider that owns the facility -- should determine
where to put their equipment. The court sent these portions back to
the FCC for further clarification.
</P>
<P>
   The court also upheld the commission's ruling for how the large
carriers would recover their costs.
</P>
<P>
   FCC officials said they viewed the decision as a win and that
the challenged portions of the rules were only peripheral.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
