<BODY>
<HEADLINE> R.J. Reynolds Switches Ad Agency  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. has replaced the
advertising agency that created the ''No Bull'' campaign for its
Winston brand, but says the new agency will continue to develop the
same theme.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, the nation's second biggest cigarette maker, said
Friday it has hired Doe-Anderson Advertising and Public Relations
of Louisville as the lead agency for Winston.
</P>
<P>
   The agency replaces Long Haymes Carr Advertising of
Winston-Salem, N.C., named to create Winston advertising in 1996.
In 1997 it developed the ''No Bull'' approach that called attention
to the absence of non-tobacco additives in the cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   With help from the ad campaign, Winston's market share rose in
1998 for the first time in 25 years, the company said. Winston's
share slipped in 1999 to 4.92 percent of the market from 5.2
percent in 1998, Reynolds officials estimated. It ranks behind
Doral and Camel as Reynold's third best-selling brand.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Leary, vice president of marketing at the Winston-Salem
based Reynolds, said the company was ''constantly evaluating ways
to strengthen the marketing communications for its brands'' and
felt the new agency would help in ''further evolving'' the ad
campaign in ''clear, engaging and contemporary ways,''
</P>
<P>
   Long Haymes Carr will continue handling media planning and
buying for all of Reynolds tobacco brands.
</P>
<P>
   Doe-Anderson had not handled tobacco advertising assignments in
recent years until taking on some special project work for Reynolds
late last year, agency chief executive Dave Wilkins said. Its
clients include National City Bank, based in Cleveland, and the
Valvoline Instant Oil Change brand.
</P>
<P>
   Jim White, chief creative officer at Doe-Anderson since October,
had been creative director at Long Haymes Carr when the ''No Bull''
campaign for Winston was introduced in August 1997, Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds spokesman David Howard said White's association with
Doe-Anderson was only one of many factors that went into the
decision to award the account to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Doe-Anderson nor Reynolds disclosed the size of the
Winston account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
