<HEADLINE> 'American Buffalo' Is Uneven  </HEADLINE>
V0729-----
r e *1404AP-Theater-America     03-17 0399
*1404 AP-Theater-American-Buffalo,0398   
'American Buffalo' Is Uneven   
An AP Entertainment Review, 
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The beat has been bobbled in the Atlantic
Theater Company's revival of David Mamet's ''American Buffalo,'' a
play whose profane banter demands a certain staccato rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   The play's sense of urgency as well as some of its humor has
been softened a bit, too, in this uneven production, which has
opened off-Broadway as part of the theater's season-long salute to
Mamet.
</P>
<P>
   We are in a world of petty thieves, bumbling con men who can't
plan -- much less carry out -- the heist of a rare coin collection.
The setting is a Chicago junkshop presided over by Don, a
garrulous, goodhearted fellow who takes a fatherly interest in
Bobby, his dimwitted young assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet is a master of macho conversation, and ''American
Buffalo'' is filled with the bluster and bullying of male bonding.
He has created one of his most completely realized characters in
Teach, the third member of this gang who couldn't shoot straight.
</P>
<P>
   Teach is a loudmouth, a nervous boor whose obscene rantings
overcompensate for his insecurities. As played by the hyper William
H. Macy, Teach dominates the evening. A veteran Mamet performer,
Macy knows his way around the playwright's style of writing, mining
its comic moments as well as its dramatic fireworks for all their
theatricality.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Baker Hall, who portrays Don, is less secure. Hall has a
great craggy face, perfect for the older man who has seen a lot in
life. Yet Hall's delivery often seems tentative, unable to sustain
the tension that the play demands. As Bobby, Mark Webber captures
the lad's dumb, almost vacant wonder.
</P>
<P>
   To really cook, ''American Buffalo'' has to have all three of
its players in top form, batting that ribald dialogue back and
forth with the ease of tennis pros.
</P>
<P>
   That's because not much happens in the course of the evening, as
this inept trio plan the heist. They argue a lot, and there's more
than a hint of violence, but even with that tension, director Neil
Pepe hasn't been able to inject much vitality into the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Designer Kevin Rigdon's junkshop setting fills the wide stage
with the leftover debris of modern life, providing an authenticity
that the production itself rarely achieves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1847 </TRAILER>
