<HEADLINE> Findings From New Presidential Poll  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some detailed findings from the
Voter.com-Battleground poll on
the 2000 presidential race concerning key voter groups and issues.
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOTER GROUPS
</P>
<P>
   Women: Gore had 48 percent to 43 percent for Bush. Gore ran
strongest among retired women and black women while Bush ran
strongest among white suburban women and mothers. They were about
even among Hispanic women.
</P>
<P>
   Men: Bush is at 52 percent with Gore at 40 percent. Gore has
trimmed his deficit among men by half as more men saw Gore as
capable of keeping the country prosperous. Both women and men saw
Gore as experienced, but men were more likely to see Bush as a
strong candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Parents: Bush was favored by more than 20 points among parents,
including among mothers. Democratic pollster Celinda Lake said
''moms will be a real battleground.'' More than a fourth of mothers
said moral values were their top concern.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics: Bush was at 51 percent and Gore at 45 percent, while
Hispanics overwhelmingly identify themselves as Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Democrats: Bush has a 52-39 lead among Reagan Democrats,
those who voted for Ronald Reagan and were Democratic at the time
of their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Independents: The two candidates about evenly split the
independent vote, an area where Bush had held a double-digit lead.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics: The candidates are about even among this
Democratic-leaning group.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats: Gore has increased his support among Democrats, with
more than eight of 10 backing him as they started seeing Bush as
more of a Republican after the primary battles.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans: Bush has very strong support among Republicans,
with nine of 10 in the party saying they support their nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   Bush issues: A fourth of Bush supporters said moral values was
the top issue with other issues grouped in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   Gore issues: Education was ranked first, followed by Social
Security and health care.
</P>
<P>
   Education: Bush and Gore were running about even on an issue
that is of crucial interest to Democratic voters and also is a top
priority for parents and women.
</P>
<P>
   Guns: Bush and Gore were running even on the issue of guns, an
issue that Democrats hope will be a wedge issue, especially for
women voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's influence: McCain's presence on the ticket didn't
dramatically change the dynamic of the race, a 48-42 Republican
advantage with him on the ticket and 48-44 for Bush without him.
But in key congressional districts, his presence on the ticket made
a big difference in the presidential race. GOP pollster Ed Goeas
suggested McCain would be very effective campaigning for candidates
in those districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1905 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
