<HEADLINE> Rwanda Complains About U.N. Reports  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Rwanda complained Friday of what it called
a ''pattern'' of attempts to discredit the government in recent
U.N. and media reports on Angola sanctions violations and Rwanda's
1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan Ambassador Joseph Mutaboba accused opponents -- whom he
defined as Hutu extremists responsible for the genocide, and their
supporters -- of trying to smear the Tutsi-led government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is it deliberate? Yes, I think it is,'' he told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Mutaboba repeated his government's rejection of a U.N. report
that said Rwanda allowed diamond and arms dealers to operate
relatively freely on behalf of Angolan rebels in the Rwandan
capital, Kigali.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions imposed on the UNITA rebels bar arms and fuel sales
and also ban diamond exports by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot say that they did not come. They may have come,''
Mutaboba said of the traders. ''But to go and say that they had
Rwandan authorities' backup, protection and so on, that's totally
wrong and it's a serious allegation.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for the independent panel that wrote the report to
produce solid evidence to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question about the 1994 genocide, Mutaboba also
sharply criticized a recent report by a Canadian newspaper that
Tutsis with links to the current government may have participated
in an assassination that helped spark the massacres.
</P>
<P>
   The report said three Tutsi informants had told U.N.
investigators that they helped shoot down a plane carrying Rwanda's
Hutu president in 1994 -- an attack that sparked the massacre of an
estimated 500,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of President Juvenal Habyarimana had long been
thought to have been the work of Hutu extremists.
</P>
<P>
   Mutaboba said he had been unable to locate the report and that
he doubted its existence. U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard has said the
U.N. war crimes prosecutor's office would have no comment on leaked
reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1906 </TRAILER>
