<HEADLINE> D'Angelo Puts on an Ambitious Show  </HEADLINE>
V0775-----
r e *1403AP-D'Angelo-Concer     03-17 0574
*1403 AP-D'Angelo-Concert,0573   
D'Angelo Puts on an Ambitious Show   
An AP Entertainment Review, 
By SHARONY ANDREWS GREEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Who better than a minister's son to flirt with
blasphemy while admirably steering an audience of hundreds back
home like prodigal girls and boys?
</P>
<P>
   R&AMP;B prince of the moment, D'Angelo, did it Thursday night at
Radio City Music Hall, the fourth stop on a tour for an artist
whose sophomore album, ''Voodoo,'' was delayed more times than fans
care to remember.
</P>
<P>
   But the patient doth inherit the earth. Or at least they inherit
the buff and bare-chested D'Angelo, who happily made up for their
wait.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Virginia native smoothly delivered song after
song with an often-falsetto croon reminiscent of Al Green and the
former Prince. Throughout his ambitious, almost-three-hour
performance, D'Angelo deftly played with themes of good and evil,
and took people on a tour of black music so steeped in Africa,
gospel, jazz, salsa and soul that it all appeared to be one when he
finished.
</P>
<P>
   While his lyrics carried more of what inarguably sells -- sex and
sin -- it was an honest effort that showed mad love and respect for
his real and musical ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   The show was funky. The show was real. Harking back to the
spirit of Curtis Mayfield and Marvin Gaye, he gave his audience a
slice of a tune called the ''Devil's Pie.'' He threw out the gaiety
of home and hearth in the playful ''Chicken Grease.'' And stroking
on melody, he gently rattled hormones with the one song that has
gotten continuous R&AMP;B airplay, ''Untitled (How Does it Feel).''
</P>
<P>
   That song speaks most clearly to D'Angelo's easy claim -- rivaled
only by Lauryn Hill -- to being the next best independent artist
after Prince. He croons like him. He defies reason sometimes just
like him. (How does anyone play nearly every instrument and write
every song on an album?)
</P>
<P>
   It's impressive, but you do hope for a polite parting of the
ways because it's hard to tell where Prince stops and D'Angelo
begins.
</P>
<P>
   The band and D'Angelo wore black in the first half, then smartly
donned white modern and tribal outfits in the second half.
Backdrops included stained glass windows and a wooden fence with
signs advertising sin.
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the millennium, when it's acceptable to question
the big picture, God -- like sex -- sells well, too. And perhaps
D'Angelo knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Keyboardist James Poysner often laced the thick sounds of the
organ under D'Angelo's vocal lines like an exclamation point, not
unlike in black churches when the music backing a pastor's words is
almost as important as the words themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The young audience stomped its feet like the good preacher-boy
instructed.
</P>
<P>
   Even the absence of rapper Q-tip, who was supposed to open the
show, didn't seem to faze anyone. Mos Def filled in.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz wonderchild Roy Hargrove, who leads his own quintet and big
band, and regularly performs and records with legends in his field,
showed humility as a backup musician in D'Angelo's court. The
10-piece band gave off a strong and pleasant vapor of the past, a
la Earth, Wind and Fire.
</P>
<P>
   If D'Angelo stays true to his instincts and sheds some of his
very-'90s fixation on the old school, he seems destined for even
greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. tour ends April 30 in Charlotte, N.C., after stops in
Washington, D.C.; Cleveland; Los Angeles and Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1931 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
