<HEADLINE> Former RI Tax Official Found Guilty  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID RISING, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- The city's former deputy tax assessor
was convicted Friday in the FBI-dubbed ''Operation Plunder Dome''
scandal in which bribes were accepted for lower property taxes at
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can you believe that?'' a crying Rosemary Glancy asked family
members after the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found Glancy, 47, guilty on all seven counts, including
attempted extortion and mail fraud. She will remain free on bail
until her sentencing June 1, and her attorney, Kevin Bristow, said
she could face years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   All six people indicted in the case have now either pleaded or
been found guilty. The FBI, which amassed more than 100 secretly
recorded conversations on video and audio tapes, said its
investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Glancy's hands often shook during the 8-day trial, and Bristow
said the 26-year city employee was almost made ''physically ill''
by the testimony against her, impeding her from taking the stand in
her own defense.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, a handful of City Hall employees gathered
to support her.
</P>
<P>
   ''We left City Hall just after the announcement was made,'' said
Allison Chiaverini, who worked for Glancy in the tax department.
''There were literally wails of anguish.''
</P>
<P>
   Former city employee Bernadette Pagliaro said Glancy was
convicted ''because of what a no-good bum says.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagliaro referred to numerous statements made by former tax
board chairman Joseph Pannone that implicated Glancy in the scheme.
Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Rose described Glancy as Pannone's
''right arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Pannone's conversations with FBI cooperating witness Anthony
Freitas, captured on tape, were the crux of the prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   The government withdrew its plea agreement with Pannone in
January, saying he had failed to fully cooperate. Pannone faces a
possible life sentence on 14 counts of extortion, conspiracy and
mail fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes played at Glancy's trial raised questions about the
role of Mayor Vincent A. Cianci Jr., Providence's longest serving
mayor. He has not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Richard Rose said former tax board member David Ead
described arranging a $10,000 payoff to ''the man downtown,'' while
Pannone boasted Cianci gave him tips on how to take bribes without
getting caught.
</P>
<P>
   Cianci called the accusations ''fantasy,'' and said Pannone's
banter caught on tape made him sound like a ''Goodfellas wannabe,''
referring to the 1990 mob film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1934 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000317.0193 </DOCNO>
