<HEADLINE> FBI Mole in Payoff Probe Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE ROBINSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- An undercover mole for the FBI who slipped
bundles of cash to Chicago politicians while wearing a wire in an
anti-corruption investigation was sentenced Friday to three years
and three months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing, federal officials said that corrupt
contractor John Christopher's role was the key to their most
successful undercover operation in Chicago. But they also said
there was no way they could overlook the crimes he committed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's well known, for those of you who are fishermen, that in
order to attract bottom feeders you usually use the stinkiest bait
that's available,'' said John Johnson, deputy chief of the FBI's
Chicago office. ''John Christopher was just that. Stinky bait. He
attracted the bottom feeders and those were the people that ideally
we wanted to catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher's eight-year odyssey through some of the murkiest
reaches of Chicago politics resulted in federal convictions against
18 officials and their associates, including six City Council
members.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher pleaded guilty to two counts of misdemeanor tax
fraud and one felony count of bankruptcy fraud as part of a deal in
which he agreed to serve as the government's undercover mole.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors asked U.S. District Judge Elaine Bucklo to show some
lenience and give him a sentence lower than the 33-month minimum
under federal sentencing guidelines. She refused, saying he had
gone uncharged for a number of criminal acts while working with the
FBI, including illegally dumping a huge mound of trash and dust on
Chicago's West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher also admitted exchanging $200,000 in ''old money''
stored for years by mobsters for fresh bills. But he wasn't charged
for that.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've already gotten the benefit of your cooperation,''
Bucklo told Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had anything to say, the husky contractor, who
according to U.S. Attorney Scott Lassar has mob connections, said
in a barely audible voice: ''I'm really sorry for what I did in my
past life. ...
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a big mistake, and I have an opportunity to lead a good
life now, if I could have that chance,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
