<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shippers Applaud Merger Moratorium  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID KOENIG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The fate of their $6 billion merger in doubt,
officials of Burlington Northern Santa Fe Corp. and Canadian
National railroads said Friday their next move will be consulting
the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Board on Friday ordered railroads to
suspend all merger activity while it writes new rules for
consolidations over the next 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   The board was responding to a barrage of complaints from
shippers, who say service on the nation's freight railroads has
declined due to recent mergers, and from rival railroads.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate effect of the board's action was to stop in its
tracks the deal to merge Fort Worth-based Burlington Northern with
Canadian National. The deal was announced last December.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they doubted the merger would go forward if the
courts uphold the transportation board's moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they're going to want to wait around 15 months
and keep the merger on the table,'' said Jill Evans, an analyst
with J.P. Morgan. She suggested the two railroads would instead
form an alliance that falls short of a merger.
</P>
<P>
   The transportation board acted after four days of hearings in
which shippers protested snarled railroad lines and late deliveries
that followed Union Pacific's 1996 purchase of Southern Pacific
Rail Corp. and last year's purchase this year of Conrail Inc. by
Eastern railroads CSX Corp. and Norfolk Southern Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of Burlington Northern and Canadian National would
create the largest railroad in North America, with about 50,000
miles of track from coast to coast in the United States and Canada.
It would be called North American Railways and be based in
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Krebs, chairman and chief executive of Burlington
Northern, said his company would review the transportation board's
decision ''to determine what appropriate legal action we can
take.''
</P>
<P>
   If the board decision withstands a court challenge, Krebs said
in a statement, the result would be to punish Burlington Northern
and Canadian National ''because of the failures of other
railroads.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Canadian National said bluntly that his company
was launching a legal challenge to the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Shippers viewed the moratorium as a victory, but only a limited
one.
</P>
<P>
   ''For us, the issue is competition, not the timing of the
moratorium,'' said Mike Heimowitz, a spokesman for the Chemical
Manufacturers Association. ''The board needs to put conditions on
these mergers that will encourage competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Shippers have gone to the Surface Transportation Board and
Congress seeking rules changes including help for ''captive
shippers'' -- those served by only one railroad. But Evans said
Friday's decision probably means Congress won't get involved in the
issue anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the moratorium, shares in the companies rose. Analysts
said rail stocks had been depressed lately because of uncertainty
over the transportation board's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern shares rose $1.25 to $22.25, and shares of
Canadian National rose 93} cents to $28.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Burlington Northern: http://www.bnsf.com
</P>
<P>
   Canadian National:
http://www.cn.ca/cnwebsite/cnwebsite.nsf/public/splashC
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 1952 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000317.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deal Ends Boeing Engineers' Strike  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. MARTINEZ, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- With its profits and share price sagging and its
customers clamoring for delayed jets, Boeing Co. cut a deal Friday
to end a 38-day strike by its engineers, one of the largest ever by
white-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative three-year contract gave a surprising, resounding
victory to the 13,000-member Society of Professional Engineering
Employees in Aerospace, which won raises, bonuses and extended
health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today is the day that the relationship between The Boeing Co.
and SPEEA has changed forever,'' said Charles Bofferding, executive
director of the union, who helped engineer the agreement. ''Today
they understand what we mean by respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The union will vote on the contract on Sunday, and the engineers
and technical workers could be back on the job at the world's No. 1
maker of passenger jets as early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The contract grants wage increases of at least 9 percent and
cash bonuses totaling $2,500 over 12 months, while the company
extended health coverage to domestic partners of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing originally offered no guarantee of pay increases and
asked workers to pay part of their health insurance premiums,
demands that angered workers and triggered the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing chairman and chief executive Phil Condit acknowledged
Friday that the company's attitude toward the union has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of us have a greater understanding of what is meant by the
issue of 'respect,''' he said. ''One day I hope we can all look
back on this as a turning point, a time when we more clearly
recognized the importance of listening to and seeking to understand
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members told union officials they did not like the fact
that the bonus money was tied to job retention and performance --
$1,000 30 days after the workers come back, $500 after Boeing
delivers 225 planes, and another $1,000 if Boeing meets its
delivery goal of 491 aircraft by March 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''My response to that is, at least there is bonus money,''
Bofferding said. ''Their previous offers didn't have any, and we
held out for it because our members wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's engineers design planes and inspect them prior to
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Their union has long been overshadowed by the powerful
Machinists union, whose members actually build the planes. The
engineers' union counts only about 13,000 members among the 22,000
eligible to belong. Its only other walkout lasted for just one day
in 1992, and the union had no strike fund when the current dispute
began.
</P>
<P>
   This time, 17,000 employees stayed out.
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists stayed on the job, but deliveries of commercial
aircraft were down significantly in February and were practically
nonexistent in March.
</P>
<P>
   Important Boeing customers such as American Airlines and United
Airlines missed deliveries and had to adjust their maintenance and
flight schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's costing us money,'' United spokesman Joe Hopkins said
earlier this week. ''We rely on Boeing for a wide variety of
services, and we've had to postpone some modifications because of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing stock dropped about 10 percent and the company warned
that its profits for the first months of the year would be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Condit told a news conference Friday that company executives
would study the financial impact of the strike over the weekend,
along with recovery plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, our focus is to deliver every one of those 491
airplanes scheduled for delivery this year and to meet all our
commitments to military customers,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike came at an awkward time for Boeing. The company was
only beginning to recover from two abysmal years in 1997 and 1998,
when its commercial aircraft division suffered heavy losses due to
snarled production lines and delayed deliveries. As it reorganized,
the company announced it would cut more than 40,000 of its 228,000
workers. The commercial division recovered in 1999, delivering a
record 620 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts, who were initially split on how the strike
would affect the company, agreed Friday that Boeing's recovery
would likely continue unabated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see a long-term effect here,'' said Joseph Campbell of
Lehman Brothers. ''They will pick up the pieces, put their
shoulders to it and bring home every Year 2000 prediction that
they've made.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing shares gained $2.38 to $38 Friday as of 4 p.m. Friday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   On the picket lines in front of Boeing's military division
Friday, strikers had mixed feelings about the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it'll get approved, but it's a compromise,'' said Dave
Keil.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't touch our benefits, and that was key for us,''
added picket captain Matt Renaud. ''Looking at it that way, it's a
win for the union.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit, himself an engineer and former member of the engineers
union, said he would create a task force to help improve relations
between engineers and the company.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Union site: http://www.speea.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.boeing.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
