<HEADLINE> UN Urged To Act on China, Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By GEIR MOULSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Two prominent human rights organizations urged the
U.N. Human Rights Commission Friday to put aside political
considerations and get tough on abuses in China and Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of rights violations in the two areas are expected to
cast a long shadow over the session of the 53-nation Rights
Commission which opens Monday and runs through April 28.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are quite a few untouchables'' at the commission, said
Isabelle Scherrer of Amnesty International. ''China has been one
for many years ... and we'll see whether this year the commission
can finally break its deadlock,'' Scherrer told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Human Rights Watch also demanded the
commission address abuses committed in the Chechen war and Chinese
crackdowns on dissent.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government announced Jan. 11 that it would seek a
resolution criticizing China. Last year's U.S. bid to rebuke China
failed, as did seven previous attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has been able to mobilize support from developing
countries, which dominate the commission, to block discussion of
its record. Both sides will be lobbying members heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, China has engaged in its most concerted crackdown on
dissent in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting China earlier this month, U.N. human rights chief Mary
Robinson asserted that right violations in China have worsened in
the past year. Robinson's scheduled visit to Russia and Chechnya
starting March 31 is expected to provide impetus for the commission
to take up rights issues there.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and other international officials have protested the
large number of civilian casualties in Russia's campaign against
Chechen rebels, and have called for independent investigations into
alleged torture and other abuses. Russia has denied the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Among other nations expected to face scrutiny at the commission
are Iran, Iraq, Myanmar and Cuba, all of whose records were
censured last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
