<HEADLINE> LatAm Parliament Elects Female Head  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- A Mexican senator was elected president
of the Latin American Parliament on Friday, becoming the first
woman to preside over the 35-year-old organization.
</P>
<P>
   Beatriz Paredes, 46, was elected by a large majority of the 150
Latin American legislators at the parliament's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Simon Bolivar, the 19th-century independence leader who
dreamed of a united South America, she said, ''today, it is
indispensable that we revive his vision to guarantee the future of
our societies.''
</P>
<P>
   The parliament represents 22 legislatures from Latin America and
the Caribbean, proposing solutions to regional problems. Each
country's legislature later decides whether to ratify the
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   One of the resolutions called for the countries of Latin America
to act together against the agricultural subsidies and
protectionist measures practiced by the European Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
