<HEADLINE> Bishop Leaves Troubled Chiapas State  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- Departing from
trouble-plagued Chiapas state, a Catholic bishop said Friday that
paramilitary groups are posing an increasing threat in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Raul Vera told reporters there were ''worrying signs''
that paramilitaries and police were working together in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems that the use of force has been chosen to resolve the
conflicts in the region,'' said Vera, former adjunct to
controversial Bishop Samuel Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Vera had expected to succeed Ruiz, who resigned when he turned
75 last year, but the Vatican announced Vera's transfer in December
to a post in the northern city of Saltillo,.
</P>
<P>
   Vera was assigned to the San Cristobal diocese in 1995 to
counterbalance Ruiz's advocacy of Indian rights. Officials and
landowners said Ruiz sided with leftist Zapatista guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   However, Vera quickly became an ally of Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   The government denies paramilitary groups even exist in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas staged a brief uprising in Chiapas in January
1994 to demand democracy and Indian rights. Peace talks are
stalemated.
</P>
</TEXT>
