<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former hostage, father of bombing victim criticize advances toIran  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The prospect of warmer relations with Iran
drew a chilly reaction Friday from a former hostage and the father
of a bombing victim who both have gone to court to try to make Iran
pay for terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Anderson, who holds Iran accountable for his seven years
in captivity in Beirut, said the Iranian government should ''take
responsibility for its acts and offer compensation to American
victims'' as a prerequisite for improved relations.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Flatow of West Orange, N.J., who blames Iran for the
1995 bombing in the Gaza Strip that killed his daughter, Alisa,
said the Clinton administration is putting ''caviar, carpets and
pistachio nuts'' before dealing with terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ''What troubles me,'' Flatow said, ''is nobody is saying to the
Iranian government: 'Look, you've been the prime sponsor of
terrorism. Send us a clear signal you're out of the business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Both men reacted after Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
announced that the Clinton administration will lift a ban on U.S.
imports of Iranian luxury goods in a step toward ''a new
relationship'' between the countries.
</P>
<P>
   The statement by Anderson, former chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, was released through the
office of Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Flatow, Anderson and three other hostages held with Anderson in
Beirut -- David Jacobsen, Joseph Cicippio and Frank Reed -- all sued
Iran in American courts under a 1996 law allowing Americans to seek
damages from nations that sponsor terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Iran declined to send any representative to court to respond to
the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Flatow won a judgment for $247.5 million. Jacobsen, Cicippio and
Reed won judgments totaling $65 million. Anderson, whose nearly
seven years in captivity in Lebanon made him the longest-held
American hostage, is awaiting a federal judge's ruling on his
request for $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has collected a penny. The Clinton administration has
opposed efforts to collect the judgments from frozen Iranian
assets, arguing that unfreezing the assets could result in
retaliation against U.S. diplomatic properties abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Albright told Congress last month that she was willing to work
with terrorism victims and their families to find a way to help
them collect. Flatow said he has yet to receive any such help.
</P>
<P>
   Mack and Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., are pushing legislation
that would help Flatow, Anderson and others collect judgments from
frozen assets. The Clinton administration opposes the bill.
</P>
<P>
   After Albright's announcement, Mack accused the administration
of ''unprincipled and inconsistent foreign policy.'' Lautenberg
said an easing of sanctions is premature.
</P>
<P>
   Flatow said it is possible that improved relations with Iran
will help him get the damages he won. But, he added, ''This is not
about the money. Frankly I think I'll never see a nickel, the way
things are developing. (But) I think we're entitled to an
accounting from Iran.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
