<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Executive Pleads Guilty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A former Disney Internet executive who
admitted flying to California to have sex with an e-mail
acquaintance he thought was a 13-year-old girl pleaded guilty
Friday to crossing state lines for the illegal tryst.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Naughton entered the plea in federal court to one
count of interstate travel with intent to engage in criminal
activity. He could face up to 15 years in prison when he is
sentenced on June 5. He will remain free on a $100,000 bond until
then.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton, 34, of Seattle, was arrested in September at the Santa
Monica Pier. As part of the plea bargain, he admitted that he had
flown from Seattle primarily to have a tryst with ''KrisLA,'' a
supposedly 13-year-old girl he had met in March 1999 in an Internet
chat room.
</P>
<P>
   The ''girl'' actually was an undercover FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   At his trial in December, Naughton contended that he believed
the girl was really an adult woman, and that they were both playing
out a sexual fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Naughton's guilty plea rebukes his prior claim that his chat
on the Internet was only a fantasy,'' said Thom Mrozek, a spokesman
for the U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   A call seeking comment from Donald Marks, Naughton's attorney,
was not immediately returned Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of his plea bargain, the government agreed to
dismiss two other charges of possession of child pornography and
use of the Internet to attempt to induce a minor to engage in
criminal sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   The jury in December had deadlocked over the Internet and
sex-travel counts, but convicted him of the pornography charge.
However, that charge was later dismissed after a judge ruled it was
based on an unconstitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton had faced a March 21 retrial on all three counts and
could have faced up to 35 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton, a former Disney Go Network executive, was fired and
lost $15 million in stock options when he was charged.
</P>
<P>
   He co-wrote the Java computer language and also wrote programs
for the Go Network designed to screen out foul language and
pornographic images.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
