<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Examiner Sold After 112 Years  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE LOCKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- In 1887, an eager young man begged to take
the helm of his family's ''miserable little sheet'' of a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The paper was the San Francisco Examiner. The young man was
William Randolph Hearst. What happened next became legend.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst used his father's millions to build an empire
commemorated in the veiled fiction of the movie ''Citizen Kane,''
an empire that would eventually include everything from slick
glossies like Cosmopolitan to Web sites like Women.com and trade
publications.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, a new chapter in the Examiner's history opened as the
Hearst Corp. announced it was selling the paper to the San
Francisco Independent, a free paper.
</P>
<P>
   The sale clears the way for Hearst to consummate its purchase of
rival San Francisco Chronicle and appears to keep alive the often
scrappy Examiner-Chronicle wars, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   It also is the latest twist in a newspaper saga that includes
earthquakes, fires, three shootings, one angry mob and the
thundering futility of Casey at the bat.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner began with a card game in the rambunctious
post-Gold Rush days of 1880.
</P>
<P>
   Mining, real estate and ranching millionaire George Hearst got
the then-unprofitable, 5,000-circulation Examiner as partial
payment on a gambling debt.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, his son, William Randolph Hearst, asked to
take over ''our miserable little sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have begun to have a strange fondness for our little paper --
a tenderness like unto that which a mother feels for a puny or
deformed offspring,'' Hearst wrote to his father. ''I should hate
to see it die now after it had battled so long and so nobly for
existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed with several million dollars from his father, the
23-year-old Hearst installed new presses, sent correspondents to
Asia, Mexico and Europe and recruited the likes of cartoonist
Thomas Nast and writers Jack London and Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Chronicle had an equally colorful beginning. That
paper began as the Daily Dramatic Chronicle, founded by the de
Young brothers, Michael and Charles, with a $20 gold piece they
borrowed from Michael's landlord.
</P>
<P>
   Writing florid prose and carrying pistols for protection, they
took on scoundrels of all types and became the dominant paper among
more than 100 in the frontier city.
</P>
<P>
   The paper started as free theater reviews but later switched to
news as the Daily Morning and Evening Chronicle. In 1879, the paper
made news of its own when Charles de Young shot and wounded mayoral
candidate Isaac Kalloch after Kalloch insinuated that the de
Youngs' mother ran a house of ill repute. The following year,
Milton Kalloch, Isaac's son, burst into the Chronicle newsroom and
shot and killed Charles de Young.
</P>
<P>
   In 1884, Michael, by then known by the more august M.H. de
Young, was the target of an attack when outraged sugar baron Adolph
Spreckels fired on him after the Chronicle published critical
articles. De Young survived.
</P>
<P>
   In 1905, the two papers struck a rare, collegial note, when the
Examiner lent its presses to the Chronicle after a mob set fire to
the Chronicle's building to demonstrate disagreement with the
paper's choice of candidate in a city election.
</P>
<P>
   That accord held a year later when the great earthquake of 1906
and its fires destroyed both papers' offices, sending them over to
Oakland to publish a joint Call-Examiner-Chronicle edition at the
obliging Oakland Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later came a milestone of a different sort when the
Examiner published the now-classic poem, ''Casey at the Bat.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1913, M.H. de Young reported that he had bought the Morning
Call and would fold it into the Chronicle. Public outrage forced
him to sell it to Hearst, who reopened it as an afternoon paper,
leaving just the Examiner and Chronicle in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers reached a truce of sorts in 1965 when the
Chronicle and Examiner combined their business operations but kept
their editorial department separate. The Call was folded into the
Examiner, which took the afternoon slot.
</P>
<P>
   But as with all afternoon newspapers, readership declined.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle, with a daily circulation of more than 456,000, is
now the largest newspaper in Northern California and the second
largest on the West Coast. The Examiner's circulation is 107,000
daily.
</P>
<P>
   While other papers were folded into newspaper groups, the
Chronicle and Examiner remained in private hands. Will Randolph
Hearst III, grandson of the founder, was publisher of the Examiner
from 1984-1994 and remained on the board. But the last descendant
of the de Young brothers was ousted from the Chronicle's management
in 1994 among bitter infighting among family members.
</P>
<P>
   De Young's granddaughter, Nan Tucker McEvoy, rejected a Hearst
Corp. offer of $800 million in 1993 for the Chronicle Publishing
Co., which included other newspapers, TV stations and book
publishing companies.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the potential for a huge payout outweighed the
family's sentimental ties to their media company.
</P>
<P>
   What's next for the Examiner?
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no idea,'' said Editor Phil Bronstein.
</P>
<P>
   But new owner and publisher Ted Fang was firm on the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''Saving the Ex today has made history,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
