<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, March 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Plans To Ease Fuel Prices
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clinton administration officials said today the president
is planning ''modest'' proposals to help ease high fuel prices but will make no
decision on drawing on the government's oil reserve until OPEC ministers meet
later this month. Clinton is expected to announce the additional measures as
part of his radio address tomorrow. No details were provided. Meanwhile, the
president appealed to the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries for a
''substantial production increase'' -- big enough to rebuild depleted reserves
and bring down high prices -- when oil ministers meet March 27.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gunmaker Agrees To Install Locks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a deal heralded as a way to save children's lives,
gunmaking giant Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed today to install locks on its weapons to
make them more childproof. In exchange, governments would drop lawsuits seeking
damages for gun violence. The agreement, reached after two months of
negotiations involving the company, state and local officials and the Clinton
administration, establishes an unprecedented ''code of conduct'' for selling and
distributing handguns. The National Shooting Sports Foundation, a firearms
industry organization, condemned Smith &AMP; Wesson, saying it had ''violated a
trust with their consumers and with the entire domestic firearms industry'' by
entering the agreement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Urged To Get Tough With China
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Two prominent human rights organizations urged the U.N. Human
Rights Commission Friday to put aside political considerations and get tough on
abuses in China and Chechnya. Reports of rights violations in the two areas are
expected to cast a long shadow over the session of the 53-nation Rights
Commission which opens Monday and runs through April 28.he New York-based Human
Rights Watch demanded the commission address abuses committed in the Chechen war
and Chinese crackdowns on dissent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Works for N. Ireland Peace
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On St. Patrick's Day, President Clinton welcomed Northern
Ireland's quarreling leaders to the White House, trying to nudge them toward
compromise. He welcomed Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern and David Trimble,
leader of the Northern Ireland's main Protestant party the Ulster Unionists;
Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams; John Hume, leader of the moderate Roman Catholics; and
Seamus Mallon, Hume's deputy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Bush Lead Shrinking Among Men
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bipartisan poll released today suggests George W. Bush's
huge lead among male voters have been cut in half by Al Gore, largely on the
strength of increased confidence in Gore's skills with the economy. The
Voter.com-Battleground Poll showed Bush with a 48 percent to 44 percent edge
over Gore in the presidential race, down from a 13-point Bush lead in the same
poll in January. Gore had a 22-point advantage over Bush among poll respondents
on the question of experience, while Bush led on the question of strength. The
two are also running close among women voters -- a cause of concern for
Democrats.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Seeks 'New Relationship' With Iran
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration today invited Iran to enter a
''new relationship'' with the United States to stabilize the Persian Gulf and
reverse more than two decades of icy distance. The U.S. lifted its ban on
imports of Iranian luxury goods, which include caviar and rugs. ''Iran thinks it
is positive and welcomes it,'' said Hamid Feza Asefi, an Iranian Foreign
Ministry spokesman, of the U.S. steps. Abraham Foxman, national director of the
Anti-Defamation League, said it was premature to begin normalizing relations
with a nation that has sponsored international terrorism and has shown continual
hostility toward the state of Israel.
</P>
