<HEADLINE> Nepal Ruling Party To Elect PM  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) -- Following a parliamentary rebellion and
the prime minister's resignation, the ruling party's 113 lawmakers
prepared to chose Nepal's new premier Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the ruling Nepali Congress party, Girija Prasad
Koirala, was considered the favorite in the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Instability has dogged Nepal's politics and the country has had
eight governments in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   King Birendra accepted incumbent Krishna Prasad Bhattarai's
resignation Friday, but asked him to continue in office until a
successor was found.
</P>
<P>
   Bhattarai, 76, resigned Thursday at the demand of 69 members of
his governing party, who blamed him for increasing crime, poor
administration and being unable to halt attacks by Maoist
insurgents in this Himalayan nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Nepali Congress won last year's election, taking 113 of the
205 seats in the House of Representatives, Nepal's lower house of
parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
