<HEADLINE> Friday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
CN Upset With U.S. Moratorium on Proposed Rail Merger
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Canadian National Railway's ambitious plan to
merge with U.S. giant Burlington Northern Santa Fe received a
stunning setback Friday when the U.S. government ordered a
moratorium on all railway mergers for at least 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Board issued the order following
hearings on the proposed $6-billion US merger of Texas-based BNSF
with Montreal-based CN, Canada's largest railway.
</P>
<P>
   CN reacted immediately, calling the ruling ''against the public
interest'' and said it has already filed an appeal with the U.S.
Court of Appeal in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of the Canadian and U.S. railways would have created
the largest North American railway with 80,000 kilometers of track
from Nova Scotia to Los Angeles and the Gulf of Mexico to
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. regulatory board said it wants to consider new rules
for such combinations, because the proposal came on the heels of a
string of U.S. mergers during the 1990s that caused rail car
shortages, shipping delays and depressed stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ------
More Atlantic Natives Say They Will Defy Fishing Regulations
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- An attempt to keep the peace in
Atlantic Canada's troubled fishery appeared to unravel further
Friday when some native bands threatened to make their own rules
for the impending season, rather than sign agreements with the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian Brook band in eastern Nova Scotia said it won't meet
with a federally appointed negotiator and will fish for lucrative
lobster without Ottawa's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   The defiance comes as James MacKenzie, hired by the federal
Department of Fisheries and Oceans to resolve the simmering
dispute, continues his sweep through the Maritimes in a bid to
reach deals with natives before the lobster season opens in May.
</P>
<P>
   MacKenzie is trying to persuade bands to sign agreements that
would allow them access to the commercial fishery while imposing
limits on what some natives say are untouchable treaty rights.
</P>
<P>
   Many say they don't need to negotiate since last year's Supreme
Court of Canada decision proved that Mi'kmaq and Maliseet people
have the right to earn a moderate livelihood from fishing, hunting
and gathering based on 18th-century treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Others charge that the negotiator is simply trying to woo
natives into compliance with promises of federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Children Killed in Crash of Vans Are Mourned
</P>
<P>
   ST-JEAN-BAPTISTE-DE-NICOLET, Quebec (AP) -- With seven white
roses, little Stephanie Madore remembered each of her playmates
killed in a horrific crash involving two minivans.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by her parents Friday, the five-year-old placed the
flowers and a drawing of her friends on orange wooden barricades
that replaced the metal guardrail strewn near Thursday's accident
scene.
</P>
<P>
   The young girl was just one of several people who passed by the
crash site either to look or lay flowers. Tears streamed down some
faces.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Auger, who ran the family day-care center, was driving
the minivan with the 10 children in tow when she lost control and
swerved into the opposite lane.
</P>
<P>
   She was broadsided by the driver of another minivan, sending her
vehicle over the guardrail and tossing many of the kids into a
nearby field. Her son was among the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Both Auger and the other driver, Wayne Kroeker, suffered minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A distraught Kroeker held a news conference at a hospital in
Nicolet to express his sympathy for the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   One of the surviving children remained in critical condition
Friday, while another was in stable condition. One child was sent
home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Coroner Raynald Gauthier said Friday at least two of the
children were buckled up because their bodies had ''very definite
marks that they were wearing seat-belts.''
</P>
<P>
   Provincial police have said they will speak to Auger when she
recovers from shock.
</P>
<P>
   The funerals will likely be held early next week but the exact
day has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Accused Nazi Collaborator Given More Time To Answer Charges
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- An 80-year-old Montrealer, accused of joining a
murderous German-controlled police unit in 1941, will contest the
allegations -- but not for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Justice Department's war-crimes unit contends Walter
Obodzinsky lied by withholding information about his collaboration
with Nazi forces in his native Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Obodzinsky, a Canadian citizen since 1955, had been given until
Friday to challenge the allegations that he deliberately concealed
his role in war crimes and should be deported.
</P>
<P>
   But the deadline has been pushed back, Max Wolpert, the
war-crimes unit's acting deputy director, said in an interview from
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   He said the extension was granted after Obodzinsky's lawyer,
Johanne Doyon, said she wanted to use the right to question a
government representative before filing a defense statement.
</P>
<P>
   Obodzinsky is the first person to be prosecuted under new 1998
Federal Court rules, which allow a default judgment if no defense
is filed and if a judge finds the government's evidence is
satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   Wolpert said he expects Doyon to question a representative from
the Immigration Department in May and to file a statement of
defense the next month.
</P>
