<HEADLINE> Taipei Mayor Mellows His Style  </HEADLINE>
By ANNIE HUANG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- As mayor of Taipei, Chen Shui-bian quickly
earned a reputation as a flamboyant corruption-buster, shaking up
the Taiwanese capital's lazy, inefficient government.
</P>
<P>
   He cleaned up the streets, shut down brothels and improved
traffic. But he was also criticized for pushing policies through
without gaining sufficient consensus, and was tossed out of office
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While his re-election bid went down in defeat, it gave Chen a
chance to fashion himself into a presidential candidate. He
mellowed his flamboyant style and nurtured the air of a more
tolerant leader.
</P>
<P>
   He also toned down his support for Taiwan independence, which
has in the past spooked many voters who feared it would lead to war
with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chen has said he would only move Taiwan toward
independence if Beijing attacks, his Democratic Progressive Party
still opposes reunification with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The DPP governs 70 percent of Taiwan on the local level with its
track record of fighting corruption -- which voters blame on the
Nationalists who have run Taiwan unchallenged for so long.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nationalists have controlled the president's office
since the island broke away from China amid civil war in 1949.
Taiwanese have been wary about letting the 13-year-old DPP take
control of state affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, who at 49 appears youthful and energetic, appeals to many
Taiwanese with his charisma and persistence, qualities he began to
display two decades ago as a defense lawyer for political
dissidents opposing the ruling Nationalists' repressive rule.
</P>
<P>
   Chen won key endorsements in the days before Saturday's
presidential election and began attracting large, enthusiastic
crowds at rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Born Feb. 18, 1951, Chen was the son of a poor sugar cane
laborer in southern Tainan County. After earning a law degree from
the elite Taiwan National University, he got involved in politics
defending political dissidents during Taiwan's martial law era,
which ended in 1987 after 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was jailed for eight months in 1986-87 for publishing a
dissident magazine. His wife, Wu Shu-jen, was run over three times
by a truck in what many believe was a politically motivated murder
attempt in 1985. Paralyzed from the waist down, she often appears
with Chen at rallies and is a close adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Chen Shui-bian's Democratic Progressive Party,
http://www.dpp.org.tw
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
