<HEADLINE> Parade Spotlights Giuliani, Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The green-clad marchers, bagpipe bands and hope
for peace in Northern Ireland took a back seat to politics Friday
at America's oldest and biggest St. Patrick's Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani basked in the adoration of the crowds,
while first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton was taunted by shouts of
''Go back to Arkansas!'' as she walked along the Fifth Avenue
parade route.
</P>
<P>
   The 239th annual march was a key event for the likely opponents
for a U.S. Senate seat. Rudy posters and Hillary shamrock stickers
were as common as green hair and ''Kiss me, I'm Irish'' pins along
the route.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone liked the parade's political bent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's right,'' Jimmy Whelan, 67, of West Orange,
N.J. ''This is supposed to be a religious-based event more than
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 15 years, Cardinal John O'Connor did not
attend the festivities. The 80-year-old cardinal's health has been
failing since he underwent brain surgery last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Lesbian and Gay Organization was banned from marching
under its banner for the 10th time. Before the parade began, 66 of
the group's members were arrested and charged with disorderly
conduct for marching without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   In Savannah, Ga., dark clouds gave way to sunshine in time for
the 176th St. Patrick's Day parade, where thousands lined the
streets of the coastal city famous for serving up green grits,
green eggs and -- of course -- green beer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just wall-to-wall people, I can tell you that,'' police
spokesman Bucky Burnsed said.
</P>
<P>
   The parade, which this year featured 300 entries, is the
nation's second largest after New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Mo., Jody Watson, who is in her 70s and known as
''the lone piper,'' led more than 200 groups in the city's 28th
annual parade. A 3-year-old girl was critically injured when she
fell off a float and was run over.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers estimated the crowd at about 500,000 spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The parade was brought to a halt at 13th and Grand by
matrimonial bliss. It was there that Whitney Hollon, 36, and Kevin
Albright, 35, were married by a county judge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to get married, but Valentine's Day was too early
and anything later was too late ,'' Albright said. ''Her sister
said 'Why not the parade?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
