<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, March 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taiwanese Begin Voting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- As the three top candidates running to succeed
President Lee Teng-hui wrapped up their campaigns, the election on Saturday was
too close to call. But there was a very real possibility the ruling Nationalist
Party could lose the presidency for the first time since Taiwan was separated
politically from China in 1949. In order to stand a chance at the polls, Chen
Shui-bian, the candidate from the opposition Democratic Progressive Party has
had to back off from his party's independence stance. Chen said he would declare
independence only if China attacks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gunmaker Agrees To Install Locks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gunmaker Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed today to install locks on
its weapons to make them more childproof. The company also will devote 2 percent
of firearms revenues every year to developing ''smart'' technology that limits a
gun's use to its rightful owner. In exchange, governments would drop lawsuits
seeking damages for gun violence. The agreement was reached through negotiations
with state and local officials and the Clinton administration. The National
Shooting Sports Foundation, a firearms industry organization, condemned Smith &AMP;
Wesson, saying it had violated a trust with consumers and the domestic firearms
industry.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
DNA Changing Limitation Statutes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With DNA being used to solve crime after crime, some states
are extending or dropping the statute of limitations on prosecuting rape and
other violent offenses in case a genetic match that can prove who did it turns
up decades later. Such changes in the law challenge the legal tradition that
says prosecutors have to bring charges within a certain amount of time after the
crime -- a rule based on concern that evidence might get lost and witnesses
prove untrustworthy after many years have gone by.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mozambique Food Shortages Feared
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- A U.N. agricultural expert said Friday that
thousands of Mozambican flood victims could face further hunger unless their
fields dry up enough for planting soon. Saturated soil and a shortage of seed
are threatening the start of the planting season, which traditionally begins in
early April. If the farmers can't plant, they'll miss the September harvest,
meaning they will be dependent of food aid until April 2001, the World Food
Program said last week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Works for N. Ireland Peace
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- On St. Patrick's Day, President Clinton welcomed Northern
Ireland's quarreling leaders to the White House, trying to nudge them toward
compromise. He welcomed Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern and David Trimble,
leader of the Northern Ireland's main Protestant party the Ulster Unionists;
Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams; John Hume, leader of the moderate Roman Catholics; and
Seamus Mallon, Hume's deputy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Deal Ends Boeing Engineers' Strike
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- With its profits and share price sagging and its customers
clamoring for delayed jets, Boeing Co. cut a deal today to end a 38-day strike
by its engineers, one of the largest ever by white-collar workers. The tentative
three-year contract gave a surprising, resounding victory to the 13,000-member
Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace, which won raises,
bonuses and extended health coverage. The union will vote on the contract on
Sunday, and the engineers and technical workers could be back on the job at the
world's No. 1 maker of passenger jets as early as Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Closes Down 35.37; Nasdaq Up 80.74
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A surge in technology shares today couldn't prevent a modest
selloff among large old-line stocks, hit by mild profit-taking in the wake of
yesterday's record 499.19-point gain. The Dow Jones industrial average ended
down 35.37 to 10,595.23, but still ended the week with a gain of 666.41 points,
a 6.7 percent surge. On the NYSE, losers led gainers by an 8-to-7 margin. The
Nasdaq closed up 80.74 at 4,798.13.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Temple Gains at NCAA Tournament
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Pepe Sanchez had a career-high 15 assists as
second-seeded Temple beat 15th-seeded Lafayette 73-47 today in the opening round
of the East Regional of the NCAA basketball tournament. Next Temple will play
10th-seeded Seton Hall, which beat seventh-seeded Oregon 72-71 in overtime. In
other games, it was Ohio St. over Appalachian St., 87-61; Cincinnati over
N.C.-Wilmington, 64-47; Tennessee over Louisiana-Lafayette, 63-58; and Florida
over Butler, 69-68, in OT; and Seton Hall over Oregon, 72-71, in OT.
</P>
