<HEADLINE> No.5 Notre Dame 87, San Diego 61  </HEADLINE>
By JR ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Ruth Riley and Niele Ivey scored 14
points apiece as No. 5 Notre Dame beat San Diego 87-61 Friday night
in the first round of the women's NCAA tournament Mideast Regional.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (17-13) had no starter taller than 6 feet and couldn't
contend inside with Notre Dame's front court led by the 6-5 Riley.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish (26-4), wearing green on St. Patrick's Day rather than
their usual gold home uniforms, saw an 18-point lead slip to single
digits in the first half after some sloppy play. Notre Dame
maintained a 20-point lead most of the second half even though most
starters played sparingly in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Up 44-33 less than two minutes into the second half, the Irish
went on a 13-3 run punctuated by Danielle Green's floating finger
roll to go up 57-36 with 15:05 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Siemon scored 13 and Green had 12 as every player on the
Notre Dame roster scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish went up 31-13 11:00 into the game with Riley
dominating inside. The All-American hit her first six shots as the
Irish scored 22 points inside in the first half to San Diego's six.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Irish became sloppy, committing nine first-half
turnovers. They lost their double-digit lead twice in the closing
minutes of the first half before Siemon's putback at the buzzer
gave Notre Dame a 42-31 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Susie Erpelding scored 19 to lead the Toreros, who were
outrebounded 32-19. They also shot 19-of-49 (39 percent) while the
Irish were better than 63 percent (28-of-44).
</P>
