<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ky. Police Protest Chief's Dismissal  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CHAMBERS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Police took to the streets Friday in a
second protest of Mayor Dave Armstrong, who fired their chief for
approving awards of valor to officers who fatally shot an unarmed
car theft suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 people marched several blocks from the police union
hall to a park across from City Hall. Police from several
departments, along with supporters, carried signs that read
''Armstrong's wrong,'' and ''Support police not felons.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Gene Sherrard was fired March 2, the day after officers
Chris Horn and Paul Kinkade received medals for valor for their
role in the May shooting death of 18-year-old Desmond Rudolph as he
was attempting to flee in a stolen truck. Armstrong said the
commendations were ''insensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The awards to white officers who shot Rudolph, who was black,
prompted outrage in Louisville's black community, and protesters
picketed the police awards banquet.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Kinkade and Horn offered to return their awards to
the city in an effort to calm tension between Armstrong and police.
Three other officers who received awards but were not involved in
the controversial shooting said Friday they were returning theirs
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were given these medals with honor, and we now today would
like to return them because someone has tarnished these medals,''
officer D'Shawn Johnson said to the rally.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who is also white, had called on police to cancel
Friday's demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's only purpose is to divide,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 2258 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000317.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passengers Subdue Man on Plane  </HEADLINE>
By KIM CURTIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A hulking, incoherent man muttering threats
and shedding his clothes broke through the locked cockpit door of
an Alaska Airlines jet, attacked the crew and lunged for the
controls before he was wrestled to the floor by terrified
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Police had no motive for Thursday night's attack on Flight 259,
which was making the same Mexico-to-San Francisco trip as an Alaska
Airlines jet that crashed in the Pacific in January, killing all 88
people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   A co-pilot using a fire ax fended off Peter L. Bradley, a
6-foot-2 carpenter weighing 250 pounds after Bradley screamed:
''I'm going to kill you'' as he grabbed for the controls, according
to an affidavit from FBI agent Margaret Eason.
</P>
<P>
   During the struggle, the pilot pleaded for help over the
intercom, and five to seven passengers sprang into action, tackling
Bradley and sitting on him while crew members put him in plastic
handcuffs and held him in a seat until the plane landed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fortunately all the guys moved quick and he ain't dead and
we're not dead,'' said passenger Robert Benjamin, 56, of West Linn,
Ore., who helped restrain Bradley. ''I was scared to death.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight was carrying 43 passengers and five crew members. The
co-pilot needed eight stitches to close a cut in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley appeared in court Friday with a black eye, cuts and
scratches on his face from the struggle. He had spent the night at
a hospital for observation and was in federal custody on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A judge ordered a psychological evaluation for Bradley and
scheduled a hearing for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, 39, of Blue Springs, Mo., faces charges of interfering
with flight crew members and attendants. He could face up to 20
years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not try to hijack the MD-83 jet but threatened to
kill people on board, the airline said. He threw his shoulder
against the locked cockpit door and broke it open 40 miles outside
of Monterey, Calif., authorities said
</P>
<P>
   He ''was going for the throttle and fuel controls,'' said police
Sgt. Joe Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't overemphasize the heroics that went on tonight,'' said
Reilly, referring to the passengers and crew. ''They averted a
tremendous disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Before breaking into the cockpit, Bradley had been roaming the
aisles, speaking nonsense and taking off his socks and his shirt,
Reilly said. He repeatedly switched seats, disobeying orders to
stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Eason's affidavit said Bradley pulled a folding pocket knife on
one passenger and asked: ''Do you want to kill me or something?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley eventually sat in first class, where, Reilly said, he
made this threat: ''I'm going to kill all of you. Keep away from
me,'' while simulating the shape of a gun with his hand.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot had been called out of the cockpit at one point to
help the crew with Bradley, but he became more agitated, witnesses
said.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin crew ''really were helpless against this guy,''
Benjamin's wife, Donnie.
</P>
<P>
   ''What really scared me was when he tried to open up an exit,''
said Chris Honochick, 37, a 225-pound former college football
player from Salem, Ore., who helped subdue the man.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley stormed the cockpit, the plane took a sudden dip,
passengers said. Honochick wrenched the man backward and they both
toppled into the aisle, where Benjamin and at least three other men
climbed on top in a gang tackle that put almost half a ton of
muscle to work to subdue him.
</P>
<P>
   With all that weight on top of him, Bradley passed out for a
moment and his feet and hands were lashed with plastic ties while
Honochick kept him in a wrestling hold, the passengers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't about to let go,'' Honochick said. ''Not until we had
this guy so he couldn't move.''
</P>
<P>
   The men put him in a chair and surrounded him as the pilot
finished the descent to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Missouri said they have no record of problems with
Bradley other than two traffic violations in 1979, when he
apparently moved to Blue Springs. The citations were not drug- or
alcohol-related.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's public defender, Ron Tyler, said Bradley has no
history of substance abuse or psychiatric problems. Neighbors said
he has a wife and a teen-age son. Both were en route to the San
Francisco Bay area Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd characterize him as a laid-back kind of guy. I never saw
any behavior that would make me think otherwise,'' said Earl
Anderson, a neighbor in their working-class neighborhood in the
Kansas City suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Magistrate Bernard Zimmerman put off concluding Bradley's
arraignment until he had more information.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a rather puzzling and bizarre incident and without
knowing why it happened I have to be concerned that it may happen
again,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   After a delay to gather evidence, the flight continued to
Portland, Ore., arriving just two hours late.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third incident this year involving the same Alaska
Airlines route. On Feb. 7, sparks flew from one of the engines of a
plane leaving San Francisco after arriving from Puerto Vallarta. No
one was injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 2259 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000317.0233 </DOCNO>
