<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwanese Begin Voting  </HEADLINE>
By DIRK BEVERIDGE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwanese could shake the delicate status
quo that has preserved peace between China and Taiwan in a vote
Saturday that will give them an untested leader facing growing
pressure to negotiate with a bellicose Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The race to succeed President Lee Teng-hui was too close to call
as the three top candidates wrapped up their campaigns Friday night
to the sounds of blaring air horns, fireworks and deafening
applause.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a very real possibility the ruling Nationalist
Party could lose the presidency for the first time since Taiwan was
separated politically from China when communist forces captured the
mainland in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   When polls opened at 8 a.m. local time Saturday, the retiring
Lee was among the first of Taiwan's 15 million eligible voters to
cast his ballot. People began lining up early for the election,
which was expected to attract a large turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Under overcast skies, Lee's chosen successor, Vice President
Lien Chan, told reporters at a Taipei poll that he was confident of
a win.
</P>
<P>
   ''The weather is very good. The election turnout should be
great,'' Lien said.
</P>
<P>
   After voting at a Taipei elementary school, Chen Shui-bian of
the opposition Democratic Progressive Party told reporters that he
would immediately pursue talks with Chinese leaders, who have made
it clear they dislike him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Permanent peace in the Taiwan Strait is going to be our
biggest goal,'' Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   With a hoarse, raspy voice, Chen campaigned close to midnight
Friday, addressing a rally of about 400,000 supporters in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the most important time for the democratic movement
and isn't it the most beautiful time indeed?'' said Chen, whose DPP
party has ruffled Beijing by advocating independence for the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has had to back off from his party's independence stance to
stand a chance at the polls, saying he would declare independence
only if China attacks. But in remarks clearly aimed at Chen,
Beijing has loudly warned any such step would lead to war.
</P>
<P>
   Chen saw his potential opening when the Nationalists split,
kicking out party star James Soong after he mounted an independent
candidacy instead of supporting Lien.
</P>
<P>
   The three top candidates were in a statistical dead heat last
week when a government ban on releasing poll results went into
effect. But as the race wound down, Chen built momentum and picked
up key endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Chen took pains to show he, too, will try to deal with China
rather than lead Taiwan and China into a war that analysts say
neither side can really afford as their economies become more
closely intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   Bi-khim Hsiao, a Chen spokeswoman, said that Chinese
individuals, whom she would not identify, had been meeting with
party officials recently, preparing for a possible Chen victory.
Some seemed genuinely interested in the party's views, while others
simply delivered anti-independence lectures, Hsiao said.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of Taiwan's second direct presidential election will
replace Lee, who during 12 years in office has often been an
irritant to Beijing but became more so last summer on his
insistence the two sides deal with one another on a
''state-to-state'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   China views Taiwan as a renegade province that must someday
reunify with the mainland, by force if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji sought to sway Taiwanese
voters by indicating that if they pick Chen, Taiwan could find
itself on the brink of war.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's language was harsh, but nothing like Beijing's response to
Taiwan's 1996 election, when China fired nuclear-capable missiles
near the island's two major ports. The United States sent in
warships to cool tensions.
</P>
<P>
   The Nationalists also sought to portray Chen, a former Taipei
mayor, as an unstable threat to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Using Chen's nickname, Lee warned some 80,000 supporters Friday
night: ''Abian has no experience. You can't depend on him. He's too
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The divided Nationalists fielded a lackluster candidate in Lien,
a long-serving politician and academic who had problems developing
rapport with many ordinary Taiwanese.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing wants Taiwan to rejoin the motherland under a so-called
''one country, two systems,'' model China used as it reclaimed
financial center Hong Kong from Britain in 1997 and the gambling
enclave of Macau from Portugal last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Washington has hinted it would defend Taiwan from a
Chinese attack, the United States recognizes Beijing as the
legitimate government of China and says it wants peaceful
reunification achieved through negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said Friday in Tokyo that
both sides should end their ''war of words'' that often has
threatened to destabilize Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Chen Shui-bian's Democratic Progressive Party,
http://www.dpp.org.tw
</P>
<P>
   Independent James Soong, http://www.soong.org.tw/global/
</P>
<P>
   Nationalist Vice President Lien Chan,
http://www.yes2000.org.tw/english/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
