<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, March 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Smith &AMP; Wesson To Make Guns Safer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gunmaker Smith &AMP; Wesson agreed today to make its weapons
more childproof by including safety locks with all of its handguns and pistols.
The company also will devote 2 percent of firearms revenues every year to
developing ''smart'' technology that limits a gun's use to its rightful owner.
In exchange, governments would drop lawsuits seeking damages for gun violence.
The National Shooting Sports Foundation, a firearms industry organization,
condemned Smith &AMP; Wesson, saying it had violated a trust with consumers and the
domestic firearms industry.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Attacks Gore on Education
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. CHARLES, Ill. (AP) -- Taking aim at Al Gore, George W. Bush is kicking
off the general election ad wars with a TV spot that is sharply critical of the
Clinton administration's education record. The ad also touts Bush's record in
Texas on education and his goals for the presidency. Gore's ad hits right back.
''George W. Bush -- from South Carolina to New York he used dirty politics to
trash John McCain's record. Now he's running attack ads against Al Gore,'' the
ad says.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taiwan's Presidential Voting Begins
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- As the three top candidates running to succeed
President Lee Teng-hui wrapped up their campaigns, the election on Saturday was
too close to call. The ruling Nationalist Party could lose the presidency for
the first time since Taiwan was separated politically from China in 1949. Chen
Shui-bian, the candidate from the opposition Democratic Progressive Party has
had to back off from his party's independence stance in order to stand a chance
at the polls. Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji this week sought to sway Taiwanese
voters by indicating that if they pick Chen, Taiwan could find itself on the
brink of war.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
DNA Changing Limitation Statutes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With DNA being used to solve crime after crime, some states
are extending or dropping the statute of limitations on prosecuting rape and
other violent offenses in case a genetic match that can prove who did it turns
up decades later. Such changes in the law challenge the legal tradition that
says prosecutors have to bring charges within a certain amount of time after the
crime -- a rule based on concern that evidence might get lost and witnesses
prove untrustworthy after many years have gone by.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mozambique Food Shortages Feared
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) -- A U.N. agricultural expert said Friday that
thousands of Mozambican flood victims could face further hunger unless their
fields dry up enough for planting soon. Saturated soil and a shortage of seed
are threatening the start of the planting season, which traditionally begins in
early April. If the farmers can't plant, they'll miss the September harvest,
meaning they will be dependent of food aid until April 2001, the World Food
Program said last week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
High-Tech Visa Allotment Exhausted
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- It took less than half the fiscal year to exhaust the
annual allotment of visas for skilled foreign professionals, the government said
today. The announcement likely boosts the prospects for congressional action
temporarily raising the ceiling on the visa program. The Immigration and
Naturalization Service, given authority by Congress to dole out 115,000 H-1B
visas for the fiscal year that ends Sept. 30, said it already has handed out
74,300 visas and has more than 45,000 petitions pending.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Closes Down 35.37; Nasdaq Up 80.74
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A surge in technology shares today couldn't prevent a modest
selloff among large old-line stocks, hit by mild profit-taking in the wake of
yesterday's record 499.19-point gain. The Dow Jones industrial average ended
down 35.37 to 10,595.23, but still ended the week with a gain of 666.41 points,
a 6.7 percent surge. On the NYSE, losers led gainers by an 8-to-7 margin. The
Nasdaq closed up 80.74 at 4,798.13.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ohio St. Beats Appalachian St. 87-61
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Scoonie Penn scored 23 points as Ohio State jumped
on Appalachian State early and cruised to an 87-61 victory tonight in the first
round of the South Regional of the NCAA basketball tournament. In other games,
Ohio St. beat Appalachian St., 87-61; Temple topped Lafayette 73-47; Cincinnati
controlled N.C.-Wilmington, 64-47; Tennessee beat Louisiana-Lafayette, 63-58;
Florida took Butler, 69-68, in OT; and Seton Hall beat Oregon, 72-71, in OT.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks Sting Hornets 118-99
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Allan Houston scored 27 points and Latrell Sprewell
added 23 points and 11 rebounds as the New York Knicks dominated the Charlotte
Hornets 118-99 tonight. Charlie Ward also scored 20 points and Marcus Camby --
in the lineup for a second time since returning from a knee injury -- had 15 for
the Knicks, who won their fourth straight behind 55 percent (42-of-76) shooting.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
