<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
Roy Henderson:
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Roy Henderson, a baritone famed for his
performances of Frederick Delius' works and a teacher of Kathleen
Ferrier, died Thursday. He was 100.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson learned to sing while serving with the Artists Rifles
during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   He studied at the Royal Academy of Music, and got his first
major break in 1925 in a performance of Delius' ''Mass of Life,''
which he sang at short notice at a Royal Philharmonic concert.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, Henderson was regarded as the ideal Delius
baritone. He sang on the first recording of Delius' ''Sea Drift''
and in the premiere of ''Idyll.''
</P>
<P>
   He also performed all the Elgar oratorios and choral works, and
sang Count Almaviva in ''The Marriage of Figaro'' at the 1934
opening night of the Glyndebourne summer opera festival.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's last singing performance was on March 29, 1952 in
the role of Christus in Bach's ''St. Matthew Passion'' at Southwark
Cathedral, the Anglican cathedral on the south bank of the Thames
in London.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson met Ferrier in 1942,and she later asked Henderson to
teach her. She went on to become one of Britain's renowned voices
of the century.
Sonny Hine:
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Sonny Hine, who owned and trained Skip Away, winner
of the 1997 Breeders' Cup Classic and the 1998 Horse of the Year,
died Friday of cancer. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Hine had been training thoroughbreds since 1948 including Guilty
Conscience, Technology, Skip Trial, Norquestor, Dawn Quixote, Amber
Pass, Chip, Patton, Bet Big and Cojak.
</P>
<P>
   But his best horse was Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 3-year-old Skip Away finished second in the Preakness
and Belmont Stakes before winning the Jockey Gold Cup over Cigar, a
two-time Horse of the Year who won 16 consecutive races.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Breeders' Cup the following year, he won the
Pimlico Special, Hollywood Gold Cup, Woodward Stakes and Donn
Handicap in 1998. Skip Away retired with career earnings of $9.8
million, second only to Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   Hine also worked as a fingerprint specialist for the FBI and
later as a State Department investigator in Hong Kong during the
Korean War. He was fluent in the Chinese dialect of Mandarin, and
intercepted and translated messages during the war.
Charlie Holt:
</P>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- Charlie Holt, who took New Hampshire's
hockey team to the NCAA Final Four three times, died Friday of
cancer. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Holt took the Wildcats to the NCAA Final Four in 1979, 1982 and
1983, and was inducted into the U.S. Hockey Hall of Fame in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He coached at New Hampshire from 1968-1986, compiling a record
of 347-232-18. Before that, he coached at Colby for six years,
leading the team to a Division II title.
</P>
<P>
   He was National Coach of the Year twice and several of his
players went on to the NHL or became coaches, including current
Phoenix Coyotes coach Bob Francis and current New Hampshire coach
Dick Umile. Four of Holt's players were on U.S. Olympic teams.
Fred Kelly:
</P>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Choreographer and award-winning entertainer
Fred Kelly, who taught his famed older brother, Gene Kelly, to tap
dance, died Wednesday of cancer. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly won three Tony Awards for his lead Broadway performance in
''Time of Your Life'' in 1940. He was also a dance instructor whose
students included Queen Elizabeth and John Travolta. He taught the
queen how to dance and Travolta how to strut.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly learned with his siblings to dance at an early age so they
could help teach classes in their mother's dance studio. During the
Depression, he earned money by performing in talent shows.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Kelly entered the military during World War II, he
stayed close to the dance floor. In 1944, he was called to
Buckingham Palace to teach Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret to
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Kelly became one of the most renowned dancers in 20th
century America.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Kelly choreographed the ''Colgate Comedy Hour'' on
television in the early 1950s and directed ''The Steve Allen
Show.'' He opened a dance studio in 1955 in Oradell, N.J., and also
joined the faculty of Pace University that year, where he remained
a dance instructor for 24 years. During that time he also
choreographed the Ice Capades.
</P>
<P>
   Fred and Gene Kelly appeared together on film only once, in the
1955 production of ''Deep in my Heart.''
Eugene D. Robin:
</P>
<P>
   EUREKA, Calif. (AP) -- Dr. Eugene D. Robin, a medical researcher
and advocate of patient rights, died March 8 of cancer. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Robin wrote ''Matters of Life and Death,'' widely used by
patients trying to determine the benefits and drawbacks of
treatment. He also wrote a medical column for The Press-Enterprise
of Riverside and the San Francisco Examiner from 1986 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Robin served as president of the National Thoracic Society from
1970 to 1971. He was acting chairman of the Stanford University
School of Medicine from 1976 to 1977 and acting chair of the
university's department of physiology from 1977 to 1986.
Richard Twohy:
</P>
<P>
   SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- The Rev. Richard Twohy, who served as
Gonzaga University's president from 1969 to 1974, died Thursday. He
was 86.
</P>
<P>
   His career with Gonzaga spanned 50 years. Twohy attended Gonzaga
High School and later taught there while studying to become a
Jesuit priest.
</P>
<P>
   He received his master's degree from Gonzaga University in 1936.
He then spent three years pursuing a doctorate in political science
at Yale University and taught at the University of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Gonzaga in 1950 to join the political science
department.
</P>
<P>
   Twohy was appointed president 19 years later, and led Gonzaga
through tough financial times.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 Twohy stepped down as president to return to teaching.
Lothrop Worth:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lothrop Worth, a cinematographer whose career
stretched from the silent era to the 3-D craze of the 1950s, died
on Thursday at the Motion Picture &AMP; Television Hospital. He was 96.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Melrose, Mass., Worth started his career as a still
photographer in the late 1920s but quickly moved into motion
pictures, working as a camera operator and cinematographer.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most remembered films was the 1957 cult hit, ''I Was
a Teenage Frankenstein.''
</P>
<P>
   He also worked with many of the biggest stars of his time,
including Orson Welles, Gary Cooper and James Cagney.
</P>
<P>
   Lothrop and his late wife, Jean, were also charitable donors to
the motion picture hospital, where a wing was dedicated in their
honor in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he gave 150 television sets to the retirement home in
memory of his wife. In January, he helped fund a new medicine
program at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At his request, there will be no memorial service.
Dorathy Yurkiewicz:
</P>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- Dorathy Yurkiewicz, a former rodeo
daredevil and stunt rider who turned in her spurs to become a
foster mother, died on Sunday. She was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Yurkiewicz, who rode Brahma bulls, gave sharpshooting
demonstrations and had knives thrown at her, performed as Dot Cole
in the 1930s and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Yurkiewicz ran off with her 16-year-old rodeo cowboy
lover, Ted Cole, whom she later married. Together, they toured with
the Milt Hinkle Texas Rangers Rodeo, the Sons of the Pioneers and
the Roy Rogers rodeo companies.
</P>
<P>
   She made her mark as the first woman to ride a Brahma bull in a
national rodeo, according to the Women's Professional Rodeo
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Performing with Cole, she would be tied to a rotating wheel
while he threw knives at her. But she always insisted that he have
a couple of drinks first.
</P>
<P>
   She had five children and raised 32 foster children after moving
to Union Beach. She taught her children rope tricks, yodeling,
songs and other acts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
