<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Texas Hoops Coach Sued  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Former Texas men's assistant basketball
coach Eddie Oran filed suit Friday against his former boss, coach
Tom Penders, alleging libel and slander.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges Penders made libelous and slanderous remarks
against Oran in the aftermath of the release of a player's grades
in 1998 to a local radio station, according to papers filed late
Friday in Travis County state district court.
</P>
<P>
   Oran seeks unspecified damages for loss of income, loss of his
employment at Texas, personal humiliation and mental anguish and
suffering, according to a report for Saturday's editions of the
Austin American-Statesman. Also cited in the suit was the loss of
an opportunity to regain a position as an assistant or head
basketball coach on the major-college level in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Oran now works for an Austin-area automobile dealership.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the grades of former Texas player Luke Axtell were
released to KVET-AM in violation of the Buckley Amendment, which
protects a student's constitutional right to privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Axtell, who now attends Kansas, filed suit against Capstar Texas
Limited Partnership, the parent company of KVET-AM. In statements
taken under oath in the Axtell suit, Oran said he took the blame
for the release of the grades to protect Penders.
</P>
<P>
   Oran was disciplined and lost a week's salary. When Penders
resigned after taking a settlement from the university, Oran was
not retained by new coach Rick Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no knowledge of anything,'' Penders, now the coach at
George Washington, said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Although he initially took responsibility for releasing Axtell's
grades to KVET, Oran testified under oath at his deposition that he
was merely carrying out the orders of Penders by instructing the
basketball secretary to fax the report.
</P>
<P>
   Oran's suit claims that, in the days surrounding the release of
the deposition transcripts, Penders made libelous statements to two
newspapers and a radio station and also made slanderous statements
to county residents as well as people in the basketball coaching
fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Axtell filed suit against Texas, Penders,
Texas athletic director DeLoss Dodds and Capstar Texas Limited
Partnership. Oran was not named in that suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-17-00 2330 </TRAILER>
