<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-17 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa State Wrestlers in NCAA Semis  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Cael Sanderson remained unbeaten for his career
and Iowa State closed in on its first NCAA wrestling championship
since 1987 Friday night, qualifying four finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson, the most valuable wrestler last year as a freshman,
easily advanced at 184 pounds and ran his career record to 78-0.
Cody Sanderson, a senior and Cael's older brother, made it to the
finals at 133 pounds. The Cyclones were most impressive at the
higher weights, also sending top seed Joe Heskett at 165 pounds and
No. 4 seed Zach Thompson at 197.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State tied for fourth last year and its highest finish in
recent years was second in 1996. The finals are Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now that I'm here, I don't know what to say,'' coach Bobby
Douglas said. ''I hope people aren't going to give me all the
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are excited,'' said Cody Sanderson, who'll face top-seeded
Eric Juergens of Iowa in the finals. ''But we are still
concentrating on our individual results.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones led by seven points after the quarterfinals, aided
by upsets to two No. 1 seeds for five-time defending champion Iowa.
A third top seed for the Hawkeyes lost in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Williams, the champion at 149 pounds last year, had won 67
consecutive matches before falling 3-1 in overtime to No. 5 seed
Larry Quisel of Boise State at 157 pounds in the upset of the
evening. Earlier, Jody Strittmatter lost at 125 pounds and
defending champion Doug Schwab fell at 141 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a real long day,'' coach Jim Zalesky said. ''They
weren't wrestling like they're capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State had a 17.5-point lead over Iowa after the semifinals,
although wrestleback results shaved it to 98-88.5 heading into the
finals. Minnesota was third with 67.5 points, followed by Oklahoma
(63.5), Oklahoma State (55.5) and Illinois (54.5).
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 10 top seeds made it to the finals. Iowa, Illinois
and Oklahoma each qualified two wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   For consolation, Iowa won the only head-to-head matchup with its
in-state rival when heavyweight Wes Hand decisioned previously
undefeated Trent Hynek 8-3. Hand gets the right to face the biggest
brute force of the tournament, Minnesota's Brock Lesnar.
</P>
<P>
   Lesnar, the top seed, twice lifted Bandele Adeniyi-Bada of Penn
off the mat before recording his third straight pin in 6:41.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just getting momentum, staying motivated and keeping my
eyes on the prize,'' Lesnar said. ''I know I am going to win if I'm
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson rang up his fourth big score of the tournament,
beating Brandon Eggum of Minnesota 16-5. He won his previous two
matches 20-5 and 21-6 and led his opening-round match 19-6 before
recording a pin.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Tucker, a 174-pounder from Oklahoma, has also put up some
big numbers. Tucker defeated Ryan Cunningham of Central Michigan
12-1 in the semifinals, on the heels of 16-9, 21-8 and 14-3
victories.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the semifinals at 125 went to double overtime. No. 8
Steve Garland of Virginia escaped with five seconds left in the
second extra period for a 6-5 victory over T.J. Hill, the only
unseeded wrestler in the semifinals. He'll face No. 2 Jeremy Hunter
of Penn State, the runnerup last year who won 2-1 when No. 3 Leroy
Vega of Minnesota was called for locking his hands.
</P>
<P>
   First-day leader Oklahoma State dropped to fourth after the
quarterfinals and to fifth after the semifinals. The Cowboys
dropped five of seven quarterfinal matches, and also lost a team
point when 184-pound Daniel Cormier made an obscene gesture after
losing in consolation matches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
