<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warriors 95, Bulls 92, 2 OT  </HEADLINE>
By RICK GANO, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Mookie Blaylock hit back-to-back 3-pointers in
the second overtime Friday night and the Golden State Warriors
outlasted the Chicago Bulls 95-92 to end an eight-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock finished with 23 points. Donyell Marshall scored five
of his 21 points in the second extra period for the Warriors, who
swept the season series with the Bulls for the first time in 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   Elton Brand, whose short jumper at the buzzer in regulation
forced the first overtime, scored 26 for the Bulls, who have lost
13 of their last 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Brown hit two free throws with 8.8 seconds left in the
first overtime to tie the game at 82. After Marshall was called for
a charge with five seconds left, Brown missed a jumper at the
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock hit 3-pointers with 2:31 and 1:46 remaining in the
second overtime to give the Warriors a 92-87 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carr's 3-pointer with five seconds left brought the Bulls
within three. Golden State then turned it over on the inbounds
pass, but Carr's 3-pointer just before the buzzer was off.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls trailed by 10 early in the fourth quarter, rallying
behind Brand's 13 points, including his jumper just before the
buzzer. Golden State didn't score in the final 2:46 of regulation
and Chicago scored six to force the tie.
</P>
<P>
Notes: John Starks, seeking his release by offering to forfeit his
salary with the Bulls, has missed 11 straight games. He's now on
the injured list with a sore knee. An arbitator will rule on his
status Tuesday. Starks came to the Bulls from the Warriors in a
three-way trade. Even even if he stays in Chicago, Starks is not
expected to play much the rest of the season. ... It was Jason
Caffey's first game in Chicago since he was traded to the Warriors
on Feb. 19, 1998 for David Vaughn and two second-round picks.
Caffey was the Bulls' first-round pick in 1995 and played on title
teams in 1996 and 1997. ... The Bulls had 27 turnovers, the
Warriors 21. ... Five players fouled out.
</P>
</TEXT>
